data.name: All
data.comment: Root of all terms in the Human Phenotype Ontology.

data.name: Abnormality of body height
data.def: "Deviation from the norm of height with respect to that which is expected according to age and gender norms." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Multicystic kidney dysplasia
data.def: "Multicystic dysplasia of the kidney is characterized by multiple cysts of varying size in the kidney and the absence of a normal pelvocaliceal system. The condition is associated with ureteral or ureteropelvic atresia, and the affected kidney is nonfunctional." [HPO:curators]
data.comment: Multicystic kidney dysplasia is the result of abnormal fetal renal development in which the affected kidney is replaced by multiple cysts and has little or no residual function. The vast majority of multicystic kidneys are unilateral. Multicystic kidney can be diagnosed on prenatal ultrasound.

data.name: Mode of inheritance
data.def: "The pattern in which a particular genetic trait or disorder is passed from one generation to the next." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Autosomal dominant inheritance
data.def: "A mode of inheritance that is observed for traits related to a gene encoded on one of the autosomes (i.e., the human chromosomes 1-22) in which a trait manifests in heterozygotes. In the context of medical genetics, an autosomal dominant disorder is caused when a single copy of the mutant allele is present. Males and females are affected equally, and can both transmit the disorder with a risk of 50% for each child of inheriting the mutant allele." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Autosomal recessive inheritance
data.def: "A mode of inheritance that is observed for traits related to a gene encoded on one of the autosomes (i.e., the human chromosomes 1-22) in which a trait manifests in homozygotes. In the context of medical genetics, autosomal recessive disorders manifest in homozygotes (with two copies of the mutant allele) or compound heterozygotes (whereby each copy of a gene has a distinct mutant allele)." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Abnormality of female internal genitalia
data.def: "An abnormality of the female internal genitalia." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Functional abnormality of the bladder
data.def: "Dysfunction of the urinary bladder." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Recurrent urinary tract infections
data.def: "Repeated infections of the urinary tract." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The urinary tract comprises the kidneys, ureters, a bladder, and a urethra.

data.name: Neurogenic bladder
data.def: "An inability to completely empty the urinary bladder during the process of urination owing to a neurological condition." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Urinary urgency
data.def: "Urge incontinence is the strong, sudden need to urinate." [HPO:probinson, pmid:12559262]
data.comment: Urinary urgency is the strong, sudden need to urinate and is usually due to bladder spasms or contractions. This symptom is suggestive of, but not necessarily conclusive for urodynamically demonstrable detrusor hyperactivity.

data.name: Hypoplasia of the uterus
data.def: "Underdevelopment of the uterus." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the bladder
data.def: "An abnormality of the urinary bladder." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Bladder diverticulum
data.def: "Diverticulum (sac or pouch) in the wall of the urinary bladder." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Urinary incontinence
data.def: "Loss of the ability to control the urinary bladder leading to involuntary urination." [HPO:sdoelken, pmid:12559262]
data.comment: Urinary incontinence can be defined as the complaint of any involuntary leakage of urine.

data.name: Abnormality of male internal genitalia
data.def: "An abnormality of the male internal genitalia." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The internal genital structures of the male including the testis, epididymis, vas deferens, seminal vesicle, ejaculatory duct, bulbourethral gland, and the prostate.

data.name: Functional abnormality of male internal genitalia
data.def: "The presence of inflammation of the prostate." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Azoospermia
data.def: "Absence of any measurable level of sperm in his semen." [HPO:probinson, pmid:20514278]

data.name: Cryptorchidism
data.def: "Testis in inguinal canal. That is, absence of one or both testes from the scrotum owing to failure of the testis or testes to descend through the inguinal canal to the testis." [HPO:probinson, pmid:23650202]
data.comment: The gonad is mobile and can be retracted superiorly by the cremaster muscle reflex stimulated, for instance, by cold or touch. A retracted testis is not cryptorchidism. An abdominal testis cannot be distinguished by physical examination from an (Apparently) absent testis and requires radiological (or, rarely, surgical) procedures for assessment.

data.name: Testicular atrophy
data.def: "Wasting (atrophy) of the testicle (the male gonad) manifested by a decrease in size and potentially by a loss of fertility." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of male external genitalia
data.def: "An abnormality of male external genitalia." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Ambiguous genitalia, male
data.def: "Ambiguous genitalia in an individual with XY genetic gender." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Hydrocele testis
data.def: "Accumulation of clear fluid in the  between the layers of membrane (tunica vaginalis) surrounding the testis." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the testis
data.def: "An anomaly of the testicle (the male gonad)." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Male pseudohermaphroditism
data.def: "Hermaphroditism refers to a discrepancy between the morphology of the gonads and that of the external genitalia. In male pseudohermaphroditism, the genotype is male (XY) and the external genitalia are imcompletely virilized, ambiguous, or complete female. If gonads are present, they are testes." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Long penis
data.def: "Penile length more than 2 SD above the mean for age." []
data.comment: Penile length is the distance between the midline attachment of the gently stretched, flaccid penis above the pubic symphysis and tip of the glans.

data.name: Chordee
data.def: "Ventral, lateral, or ventrolateral bowing of the shaft and glans penis of more than 30 degrees." [HPO:probinson, pmid:23650202]
data.comment: The degree of variation of penis curvature is a continuum, but traditionally 30 degrees is considered the threshold for surgical intervention on chordee. Bowing usually becomes more obvious in an erect penis, but is frequently also palpable when stretching a flaccid penis. Chordee can be congenital or acquired; if the former, it can be associated with Webbed Penis or Hypospadias, which should be coded separately.

data.name: Bifid scrotum
data.def: "Midline indentation or cleft of the scrotum." [HPO:probinson, pmid:23650202]
data.comment: A testis may or may not be present in each half of the scrotum.

data.name: Shawl scrotum
data.def: "Superior margin of the scrotum superior to the base of the penis." [HPO:probinson, pmid:23650202]
data.comment: A congenital overriding scrotum may disappear with growth and development, especially during puberty. If the entire scrotum is located superior to the penis, the term Penoscrotal transposition is used instead.

data.name: Hypoplastic male external genitalia
data.def: "Underdevelopment of part or all of the male external reproductive organs (which include the penis, the scrotum and the urethra)." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Macroorchidism
data.def: "The presence of abnormally large testes." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Micropenis
data.def: "Abnormally small penis. At birth, the normal penis is about 3 cm (stretched length from pubic tubercle to tip of penis) with micropenis less than 2.0-2.5 cm." [HPO:probinson, pmid:15102623]

data.name: Abnormality of female external genitalia
data.def: "An abnormality of the female external genitalia." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the clitoris
data.def: "An abnormality of the clitoris." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Clitoromegaly
data.def: "Increased size of the clitoris." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the labia
data.def: "An anomaly of the labia, the externally visible portions of the vulva." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Hypoplastic labia majora
data.def: "Undergrowth of the outer labia." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Clitoral hypoplasia
data.def: "Developmental hypoplasia of the clitoris." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Ambiguous genitalia, female
data.def: "Ambiguous genitalia in an individual with XX genetic gender." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Ambiguous genitalia
data.def: "A genital phenotype that is not clearly assignable to a single gender. Ambiguous genitalia can be evaluated using the Prader scale: Prader 0: Normal female external genitalia. Prader 1: Female external genitalia with clitoromegaly. Prader 2: Clitoromegaly with partial labial fusion forming a funnel-shaped urogenital sinus. Prader 3: Increased phallic enlargement. Complete labioscrotal fusion forming a urogenital sinus with a single opening. Prader 4: Complete scrotal fusion with urogenital opening at the base or on the shaft of the phallus. Prader 5: Normal male external genitalia. The diagnosis of ambiguous genitalia is made for Prader 1-4." [HPO:probinson, pmid:15102623]
data.comment: Note that this term can include or combine variations in size and shape, with partial or complete absence of structures. It is preferable to describe the individual components, which are defined below. It is nonetheless a widely used bundled term and as such is retained here. The distinction of this finding from a marked degree of Hypospadias is an example of how this term can be problematic. Genetic gender is determined at fertilization, whereby the presence of a Y chromosome determines male gender. Normally, genetic gender determines gonadal gender which in turn determines phenotypic gender. Testicular development is an active process requiring expression of the primary testis determining gene SRY, which is located on the Y chromosome.

data.name: Labial hypoplasia
data.def: "Fusion of the labia minora as a result of labial adhesions resulting in vaginal obstruction." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Abnormality of the ureter
data.def: "An abnormality of the ureter." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Ureteral stenosis
data.def: "The presence of a stenotic, i.e., constricted ureter." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Hydroureter
data.def: "The distention of the ureter with urine." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Ureteral duplication
data.def: "A developmental anomaly characterized by the presence of two, instead of one, ureter connecting a kidney to the bladder." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Ureteropelvic junction obstruction
data.def: "Blockage of urine flow from the renal pelvis to the proximal ureter." [Eurenomics:ewuehl]

data.name: Abnormality of the kidney
data.def: "An abnormality of the kidney." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The kidney is a paired organ whose primary function is the production of urine.

data.name: Abnormality of the genital system
data.def: "An abnormality of the genital system." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the urinary system
data.def: "An abnormality of the urinary system." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of reproductive system physiology
data.def: "An abnormal functionality of the genital system." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Horseshoe kidney
data.def: "A connection of the right and left kidney by an isthmus of functioning renal parenchyma or fibrous tissue that crosses the midline." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Ectopic kidney
data.def: "A developmental defect in which a kidney is located in an abnormal anatomic position." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Renal hypoplasia
data.def: "Hypoplasia of the kidney." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Oligomeganephronic renal hypoplasia differs from simple hypoplasia, in which the renal mass is reduced but the number of nephrons is normal.

data.name: Nephronophthisis
data.def: "Presence of cysts at the corticomedullary junction of the kidney in combination with tubulointerstitial fibrosis." [Eurenomics:fschaefer]
data.comment: Nephronophthisis is here regarded as a phenotypic feature. The disease of the same name results in progressive symmetrical destruction of the kidneys involving both the tubules and glomeruli.

data.name: Abnormality of the renal tubule
data.def: "An abnormality of the renal tubules." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The renal tubules are reabsorptive canals that are involved in the secreting, collecting, and conducting of the urine.

data.name: Tubular atrophy
data.def: "The presence of renal tubules with thick redundant basement membranes, or a reduction of greater than 50% in tubular diameter compared to surrounding non-atrophic tubules." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the glomerulus
data.def: "A structural anomaly of the glomerulus." [Eurenomics:ewuehl]

data.name: Glomerulosclerosis
data.def: "Accumulation of scar tissue within the glomerulus." [Eurenomics:fschaefer]

data.name: Focal segmental glomerulosclerosis
data.def: "Segmental accumulation of scar tissue in individual (but not all) glomeruli." [Eurenomics:fschaefer]

data.name: Tall stature
data.def: "A height above that which is expected according to age and gender norms." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Renal agenesis
data.def: "Agenesis, that is, failure of the kidney to develop during embryogenesis and development." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Renal agenesis can occur as a unilateral or bilateral trait.

data.name: Enlarged kidneys
data.def: "An abnormal increase in the size of the kidney." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The main causes of large kidney are hydronephrosis, polycystic disease, renal cell carcinoma, nephroblastoma/Wilm's tumor (in children), and solitary cysts. If possible, a specific term should be used instead of this one.

data.name: Renal cyst
data.def: "A fluid filled sac in the kidney." [Eurenomics:fschaefer]

data.name: Renal corticomedullary cysts
data.def: "The presence of multiple cysts at the border between the renal cortex and medulla." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Renal dysplasia
data.def: "The presence of developmental dysplasia of the kidney." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Polycystic kidney dysplasia
data.def: "The presence of multiple cysts in both kidneys." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Polycystic kidney disease (PKD) is a leading cause of end-stage renal disease. Most commonly, PKD arises as an inherited trait. Tremendous enlargement of both kidneys is characteristic of the autosomal dominant form of PKD, with up to hundreds or thousands of renal cysts. This term does not refer to the disease entity but rather to the finding of numerous cysts in both kidneys.

data.name: Proximal tubulopathy
data.def: "Dysfunction of the proximal tubule, which is the portion of the duct system of the nephron of the kidney which leads from Bowman's capsule to the loop of Henle." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Phenotypic abnormality
data.def: "A phenotypic abnormality." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This is the root of the phenotypic abnormality subontology of the HPO.

data.name: Abnormality of the genitourinary system
data.def: "The presence of any abnormality of the genitourinary system." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Nephrocalcinosis
data.def: "Nephrocalcinosis is the deposition of calcium salts in renal parenchyma." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Nephrocalcinosis can be intratubular or interstitial, and can be diagnosed by means of a radiologic exam (plain radiographs, ultrasonograms, or computed tomography scans) or via microscopic examination of the renal tissues. The term nephrocalcinosis most often applies to a generalized increase in renal calcium content.

data.name: Unilateral renal agenesis
data.def: "A unilateral form of agenesis of the kidney." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Hydronephrosis
data.def: "Severe distention of the kidney with dilation of the renal pelvis and calices." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Hydronephrosis can be caused by reflux or by retrograde pressure on the kidney when the flow of urine is obstructed.

data.name: Abnormality of the uterus
data.def: "An abnormality of the uterus." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the ovary
data.def: "An abnormality of the ovary." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: A uterus that is divided into two lateral horns as a result of imperfect fusion of the paramesonephric ducts.

data.name: Ovarian cyst
data.def: "The presence of one or more cysts of the ovary." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the vagina
data.def: "An abnormality of the vagina." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of head or neck
data.def: "An abnormality of head and neck." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the mouth
data.def: "An abnormality of the mouth." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Wide mouth
data.def: "Distance between the oral commissures more than 2 SD above the mean. Alternatively, an apparently increased width of the oral aperture (subjective)." [pmid:19125428]
data.comment: The width of the mouth varies with facial movement and must be assessed when the subject has a relaxed (neutral) face. This term replaces macrostomia, large mouth, and large oral aperture because these terms imply a wide and open mouth. The term should not be used to describe a patient with a lateral oral cleft.

data.name: Abnormality of the tongue
data.def: "Any abnormality of the tongue." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the lip
data.def: "An abnormality of the lip." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Narrow mouth
data.def: "Distance between the commissures of the mouth more than 2 SD below the mean. Alternatively, an apparently decreased width of the oral aperture (subjective)." [pmid:19125428]
data.comment: The width of the mouth varies with facial movement and must be assessed when the subject has a relaxed (neutral) face. This term replaces microstomia, small oral aperture, and small mouth because the reduced opening of the mouth is secondary to reduced width.

data.name: Glossoptosis
data.def: "Posterior displacement of the tongue into the pharynx, i.e., a tongue that is mislocalised posteriorly." [HPO:probinson, pmid:19125428]
data.comment: Presumably, use of the suffix ptosis refers to the situation where the patient is supine, and the displacement is downward. Strictly speaking, the term glossoptosis indicates falling of the tongue and thus can also be forward displacement; however by convention it is only used for backward displacement. Glossoptosis may cause obstruction of the airway.

data.name: Abnormality of the oral cavity
data.def: "Abnormality of the oral cavity, i.e., the opening or hollow part of the mouth." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the teeth
data.def: "Any abnormality of the teeth." [HPO:ibailleulforestier]
data.comment: Any abnormality of the primary (deciduous) or permanent teeth.

data.name: Microglossia
data.def: "Decreased length and width of the tongue." [pmid:19125428]
data.comment: Normal standards do not exist. The term aglossia is often used for extremely small tongue, but a nubbin of tongue tissue is almost always present and aglossia in sensu strictu is extremely rare. This is an acknowledged bundled term, but due to its frequent usage and relative paucity of situations that would call for separate individual assessments of tongue dimensions, the bundled term is retained.

data.name: Abnormality of the uvula
data.def: "Abnormality of the uvula, the conic projection from the posterior edge of the middle of the soft palate." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the palate
data.def: "Any abnormality of the palate, i.e., of roof of the mouth)." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of upper lip
data.def: "An abnormality of the upper lip." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of lower lip
data.def: "An abnormality of the lower lip." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Thick lower lip vermilion
data.def: "Increased thickness of the lower lip, leading to a prominent appearance of the lower lip. The height of the vermilion of the lower lip in the midline is more than 2 SD above the mean. Alternatively, an apparently increased height of the vermilion of the lower lip in the frontal view (subjective)." [HPO:curators, pmid:19125428]
data.comment: Normal values for the height of the vermilion are available [Farkas, 1981] but measurements are not commonly used. Most clinicians determine this feature subjectively. The lower lip is typically thicker than the upper one. The height of the vermilion of the lower lip varies among ethnic groups, and the vermilion should\nbe compared to a population of same ethnic background. When the vermilion is thick, it is more convex and more everted than usual on profile view, but that should be assessed separately.

data.name: Lobulated tongue
data.def: "Multiple indentations and/or elevations on the edge and/or surface of the tongue producing an irregular surface contour." [pmid:19125428]
data.comment: Lobulated tongue can bilobed, trilobed, or show multiple lobes.

data.name: Broad alveolar ridges
data.def: "Cleft of the soft palate (also known as the velum, or muscular palate) as a result of a developmental defect occurring between the 7th and 12th week of pregnancy. Cleft soft palate can cause functional abnormalities of the Eustachian tube with resulting middle ear anomalies and hearing difficulties, as well as speech problems associated with hypernasal speech due to velopharyngeal insufficiency." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Narrow palate
data.def: "Width of the palate more than 2 SD below the mean (objective) or apparently decreased palatal width (subjective)." [pmid:19125428]
data.comment: Palatal width is measured as the distance between the maxillary first permanent molar on the right and left sides, at the lingual cervical line, using a specific device. Palate width is typically assessed subjectively in routine clinical practice. Narrowing is often associated with a High palate, but this should be assessed and coded separately. Gingival overgrowth can give the impression of a narrow palate but should be distinguished and coded separately. The term gothic palate is used to indicate that the roof of the palate is not round but rather has an inverted V-shape, and therefore, only the upper part of the palate is narrow.

data.name: Abnormality of oral frenula
data.def: "An abnormality of the lingual frenulum, that is of the small fold of mucous membrane that attaches the tongue to the floor of the mouth, or the presence of accessory frenula in the oral cavity." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Bifid uvula
data.def: "Uvula separated into two parts most easily seen at the tip." [pmid:19125428]
data.comment: This finding is assessed by gently retracting the oral mucosa from the alveolar ridge. Typically there is a single maxillary and a single mandibular frenulum located in the midline between the two central incisors. Abnormalities of the alveolar ridges may accompany accessory frenula, but these should be assessed separately.

data.name: Open mouth
data.def: "A facial appearance characterized by a permanently or nearly permanently opened mouth." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of parotid gland
data.def: "Any abnormality of the parotid glands, which are the salivary glands that are located in the subcutaneous tissues of the face overlying the mandibular ramus and anterior and inferior to the external ear." [HPO:curators]
data.comment: A lip pit may be connected by a fistula to mucous minor salivary glands in the lower lip. In addition, a lip pit may on occasion be seen with a surrounding tissue elevation (mound). Pits located at the labial commisure (cheilon) are distinct from lip pits (see Commissural pit).

data.name: Pierre-Robin sequence
data.def: "Pierre Robin malformation is a sequence of developmental malformations characterized by micrognathia (mandibular hypoplasia), glossoptosis and cleft palate." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Oral cleft
data.def: "The presence of a cleft in the oral cavity, the two main types of which are cleft lip and cleft palate. In cleft lip, there is the congenital failure of the maxillary and median nasal processes to fuse, forming a groove or fissure in the lip. In cleft palate, there is a congenital failure of the palate to fuse properly, forming a grooved depression or fissure in the roof of the mouth. Clefts of the lip and palate can occur individually or together. It is preferable to code each defect separately." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Triangular mouth
data.def: "The presence of a triangular form of the mouth." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Xerostomia
data.def: "Dryness of the mouth due to salivary gland dysfunction." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: High palate
data.def: "Height of the palate more than 2 SD above the mean (objective) or palatal height at the level of the first permanent molar more than twice the height of the teeth (subjective)." [pmid:19125428]
data.comment: The measuring device for this assessment is described in (Hall JG, Froster-Iskenius UG, Allanson JE, Gripp K, Slavotinek A. 2006. Handbook of Normal Physical Measurements. 2nd edition. Oxford Medical, publishers). A high palate is often associated with a narrow palate. However, a narrow palate can easily give a false appearance of a high palate. Height and width of the palate should be assessed and coded separately. We do not recommend the subjective determination because this term can be overused and\napplied inaccurately.

data.name: Furrowed tongue
data.def: "Accentuation of the grooves on the dorsal surface of the tongue." [pmid:19125428]
data.comment: Usually there is a midline groove of the tongue with smaller radiating grooves. The deep furrows may extend to the lateral borders. They may follow a regular geometric pattern or be irregular. A furrowed tongue occurs in 10-25% of individuals but is rare in children.

data.name: Everted lower lip vermilion
data.def: "An abnormal configuration of the lower lip such that it is turned outward i.e., everted, with the Inner aspect of the lower lip vermilion (normally opposing the teeth) being visible in a frontal view." [pmid:19125428]
data.comment: In frontal view, with the face relaxed, the apparent height of the lower lip vermilion is excessive and the lower incisors may be visible. On profile view, the vermilion is more convex than usual. An everted lower lip may be viewed as pouting, but this designation is a functional term.

data.name: Thin vermilion border
data.def: "Reduced width of the \"skin of vermilion border region of upper lip\" (FMA:312645)." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The vermilion is the red part of the lips, and the vermilion border is the rim of paler skin that demarcates the vermilion from the rest of the skin of the face.

data.name: Abnormality of the head
data.def: "An abnormality of the head." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the face
data.def: "An abnormality of the face." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Small face
data.def: "A face that is short (HP:0011219) and narrow (HP:0000275)." [HP:probinson]
data.comment: This term represents a combination of two terms, short face and narrow face.

data.name: Narrow face
data.def: "Bizygomatic (upper face) and bigonial (lower face) width are both more than 2 standard deviations below the mean (objective); or, an apparent reduction in the width of the upper and lower face (subjective)." [pmid:19125436]
data.comment: Objective measurement of the upper facial width is made with spreading calipers. The tips of the calipers are passed over the zygomatic arches until the maximum width is determined. Objective measurement of the lower faces is made with spreading calipers, with the tips firmly pressed against the inferomedial surface of the angle of the mandible.

data.name: Long face
data.def: "Facial height (length) is more than 2 standard deviations above the mean (objective); or, an apparent increase in the height (length) of the face (subjective)." [pmid:19125436]
data.comment: Objective measurement of the face height is made with sliding calipers from the nasion, just above the depth of the nasal root, to the gnathion, the inferior border of the mandible, both in the midline. Note that long face is distinct from narrow face.

data.name: Coarse facial features
data.def: "Absence of fine and sharp appearance of brows, nose, lips, mouth, and chin, usually because of rounded and heavy features or thickened skin with or without thickening of subcutaneous and bony tissues." [pmid:19125436]

data.name: Broad face
data.def: "Bizygomatic (upper face) and bigonial (lower face) width greater than 2 standard deviations above the mean (objective); or an apparent increase in the width of the face (subjective)." [pmid:19125436]
data.comment: Note that broad face is distinct from round face.

data.name: Epicanthus
data.def: "A fold of skin starting above the medial aspect of the upper eyelid and arching downward to cover, pass in front of and lateral to the medial canthus." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: In extreme cases, the skin fold can start as high as the eyebrow; this is called epicanthus superciliaris.

data.name: Abnormality of the philtrum
data.def: "An abnormality of the philtrum." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The paralabial region is the region surrounding the lips and includes the philtrum.

data.name: Abnormality of the forehead
data.def: "An anomalyof the forehead." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The mean width of the philtrum was found to be 7 mm in infants by Franz and Sokol [1971] and 9.7 mm in adults by Ward and Jamison [1991]. Measuring width of the philtrum is even more inaccurate than measuring length (vide supra). A broad philtrum may be associated with reduced ridge prominence or a shallow groove, a Smooth philtrum, which should be assessed and coded separately. It may be found with a broad nasal septum.

data.name: Full cheeks
data.def: "Increased prominence or roundness of soft tissues between zygomata and mandible." [DDD:awilkie]

data.name: Mask-like facies
data.def: "A lack of facial expression often with staring eyes and a slightly open mouth." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Mask-like facies can be seen in many neurological disorders such as Parkinsonism and myotonic dystrophy.

data.name: Abnormality of the chin
data.def: "An abnormality of the chin, i.e., of the inferior portion of the face lying inferior to the lower lip and including the central prominence of the lower jaw." [HPO:probinson, pmid:19125436]

data.name: Pointed chin
data.def: "A marked tapering of the lower face to the chin." [pmid:19125436]
data.comment: The two rami of the mandible meet at an acute angle.

data.name: Abnormality of the midface
data.def: "An anomaly of the midface, which is a region and not an anatomical term. It extends, superiorly, from the inferior orbital margin to, inferiorly, the level of nasal base. It is formed by the maxilla (upper jaw) and zygoma. Traditionally, the nose and premaxilla are not included in the midface." [HPO:probinson, pmid:19125436]

data.name: Round face
data.def: "The facial appearance is more circular than usual as viewed from the front." [pmid:19125436]

data.name: Smooth philtrum
data.def: "Flat skin surface, with no ridge formation in the central region of the upper lip between the nasal base and upper vermilion border." [pmid:19152422]
data.comment: There is a spectrum of this finding from total absence of the philtral ridges to a some prominence of the ridges. The central groove varies from absent to shallow. Normal values for the frequency of smooth philtrum are available. Grading of the smoothness of the philtrum, used in the assessment of Fetal Alcohol Syndrome, has been developed. This finding is greatly influenced by the facial expression, and care should be taken to evaluate the philtrum when the face is in a neutral position. A smooth philtrum can be associated with a Long philtrum. However, the two findings should be coded separately.

data.name: Short philtrum
data.def: "Distance between nasal base and midline upper lip vermilion border more than 2 SD below the mean. Alternatively, an apparently decreased distance between nasal base and midline upper lip vermilion border." [pmid:19152422]

data.name: Facial asymmetry
data.def: "An abnormal difference between the left and right sides of the face." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Triangular face
data.def: "Facial contour, as viewed from the front, triangular in shape, with breadth at the temples and tapering to a narrow chin." [DDD:jclayton-smith, pmid:19125436]

data.name: Facial hemangioma
data.def: "Hemangioma, a benign tumor of the vascular endothelial cells, occurring in the face." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Short chin
data.def: "Decreased vertical distance from the vermilion border of the lower lip to the inferior-most point of the chin." [HPO:probinson, pmid:19125436]
data.comment: The term "micrognathia" should be used when the chin is both short (vertical dimension) and narrow (horizontal dimension).

data.name: Prominent supraorbital ridges
data.def: "Greater than average forward and/or lateral protrusion of the supraorbital portion of the frontal bones." [pmid:19125436]

data.name: Broad forehead
data.def: "Width of the forehead or distance between the frontotemporales is more than two standard deviations above the mean (objective); or apparently increased distance between the two sides of the forehead." [pmid:19125436]
data.comment: Frontotemporalis is a point lateral to the vertical component of the supraorbital ridge, where there is a hollowing. Spreading caliper tips are placed in the deepest part of that hollow. Note that this term should not be confused with prominent forehead.

data.name: Sloping forehead
data.def: "Inclination of the anterior surface of the forehead from the vertical more than two standard deviations above the mean (objective); or apparently excessive posterior sloping of the forehead in a lateral view." [pmid:19125436]
data.comment: Measurement requires an angle meter, inclined on the anterior surface of the forehead, in the midline, along a line connecting the hairline to the glabella, compared to the vertical.

data.name: Narrow forehead
data.def: "Width of the forehead or distance between the frontotemporales is more than two standard deviations below the mean (objective); or apparently narrow intertemporal region (subjective)." [pmid:19125436]
data.comment: A reduced distance between the temporal regions (temples) on each side of the head to one another. Frontotemporalis is a point lateral to the vertical component of the supraorbital ridge, where there is a hollowing. Spreading caliper tips are placed in the deepest part of that hollow.

data.name: Long philtrum
data.def: "Distance between nasal base and midline upper lip vermilion border more than 2 SD above the mean. Alternatively, an apparently increased distance between nasal base and midline upper lip vermilion border." [pmid:19152422]

data.name: High forehead
data.def: "An abnormally increased height of the forehead." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the outer ear
data.def: "An abnormality of the external ear." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The hair may need to be pulled back to recognize this feature. Historically, English widows in the 18th century wore a black hat, triangular in shape, with a point facing forward in the midline.

data.name: Abnormal location of ears
data.def: "Abnormal location of the ear." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Posteriorly rotated ears
data.def: "A type of abnormal location of the ears in which the position of the ears is characterized by posterior rotation (the superior part of the ears is rotated towards the back of the head, and the inferior part of the ears towards the front)." [HPO:probinson, pmid:19152421]
data.comment: Angle formed by the line perpendicular to the Frankfurt plane and the medial longitudinal axis of the ear (the two most remote points of the ear) greater than two standard deviations above the mean for age.

data.name: Abnormality of the inner ear
data.def: "An abnormality of the inner ear." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Tinnitus
data.def: "Tinnitus is an auditory perception that can be described as the experience of sound, in the ear or in the head, in the absence of external acoustic stimulation." [Cochrane:ab005233]

data.name: Abnormality of earlobe
data.def: "An abnormality of the lobule of pinna." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Otosclerosis cannot be seen on an office examination. The audiogram indicates a conductive type of hearing loss. Testing of the stapedial reflexes indicates limited or no movement of the bones of hearing.

data.name: Hearing abnormality
data.def: "An abnormality of the sensory perception of sound." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: According to the World Health Organization, deafness refers to the complete loss of hearing ability in one or two ears. Hearing impairment refers to both complete and partial loss of the ability to hear.

data.name: Hearing impairment
data.def: "A decreased magnitude of the sensory perception of sound." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Hearing loss can be categorized by which part of the auditory system is damaged, as conductive hearing loss, sensorineural hearing loss, and mixed hearing loss. Another axis of classification uses the degree of hearing impairment. The degree of hearing loss is computed by using a three frequency average taken at 500 Hz, 1,000 Hz and 2,000 Hz. The average of these three frequencies is called the Pure Tone Average (PTA). 0-20 dB is considered normal, 21-40 dB mild loss, 41-60 dB moderate loss, 61-70 dB moderately severe loss,71-90 dB severe loss, and greater than 90 dB profound loss. Note that the word deafness is occasionally used to describe partial hearing loss. The World Health Organization uses the word deafness to refer to complete loss of the ability to hear, and hearing impairment to refer to any degree of reduced hearing.

data.name: Abnormality of the nose
data.def: "An abnormality of the nose." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Low-set, posteriorly rotated ears
data.def: "Ears that are low-set (HP:0000369) and posteriorly rotated (HP:0000358)." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This bundled term is left for convenience because of its common use in the literature. It is preferable to code each feature separately.

data.name: Low-set ears
data.def: "Upper insertion of the ear to the scalp below an imaginary horizontal line drawn between the inner canthi of the eye and extending posteriorly to the ear." [HPO:probinson, pmid:19152421]

data.name: Abnormality of the middle ear
data.def: "An abnormality of the middle ear." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the auditory canal
data.def: "An abnormality of the External acoustic tube (also known as the auditory canal)." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of cochlea
data.def: "An abnormality of the cochlea." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The cochlea is an inner ear structure comprised of a snail-shell like structure divided into three fluid-filled parts. Two are canals for the transmission of pressure and in the third is the organ of Corti, which detects pressure impulses and responds with electrical impulses which travel along the auditory nerve to the brain.

data.name: Incomplete partition of the cochlea type II
data.def: "The cochlea is lacking the entire modiolus and cribriform area, resulting in a cystic appearance. This is accompanied by a large cystic vestibule." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the pinna
data.def: "An abnormality of the pinna, which is also referred to as the auricle or external ear." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The term 'dysplastic' is no longer accepted as a descriptor for an ear with unusual morphology. Each specific anatomical component of the ear should be described when the ear is thought to be abnormal in appearance.

data.name: Cupped ear
data.def: "Laterally protruding ear that lacks antihelical folding (including absence of inferior and superior crura)." [HPO:probinson, pmid:19162421]

data.name: Abnormality of periauricular region
data.def: "Stapes ankylosis refers to congenital or acquired fixation of the stapes (the stirrup-shaped small bone or ossicle in the middle ear), which is associated with conductive hearing resulting from impairment of the sound-conduction mechanism (the external auditory canal, tympanic membrane, and/or middle-ear ossicles)." [HPO:probinson, pmid:12089654]
data.comment: Stapes ankylosis may be congenital or acquired, in which case it is refered to as otosclerosis. Otosclerosis is the most common cause of progressive conductive hearing loss in adults, and is generally manifested as nonsyndromic, delayed-onset, conductive hearing loss, but it may also affect the inner ear to cause sensorineural loss. Congenital stapes ankylosis may be difficult to differentiate from otosclerosis when the diagnosis of conductive hearing loss is delayed.

data.name: Otitis media
data.def: "Inflammation or infection of the middle ear." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: All gradations in size of the earlobe may be seen from absent to clearly enlarged compared to average. This finding is highly variable.

data.name: Chronic otitis media
data.def: "Chronic otitis media refers to fluid, swelling, or infection of the middle ear that does not heal and may cause permanent damage to the ear." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Thickened helices
data.def: "Increased thickness of thehelix of the ear." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Lop ear
data.def: "Anterior and inferior folding of the upper portion of the ear that obliterates triangular fossa and scapha." [HPO:probinson, pmid:19152421]
data.comment: The term 'lop ear' refers to excessive protrusion of the ear from the side of the head, that is, the external ear stands away from the head at a greater than normal angle (Normal angle of the auricle to the median plane averages 25 degrees in boys and 18 degrees in girls). Lop ears are usually larger than normal ears. Mild forms are limited to the superior ear, more severe forms affect the superior and posterior ear. The concha may be excessively concave. This should be distinguished from an Overfolded helix where the external contour of the ear is normal.

data.name: Prominent antihelix
data.def: "The presence of an abnormally prominent antihelix." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Overfolded helix
data.def: "A condition in which the helix is folded over to a greater degree than normal. That is, excessive curling of the helix edge, whereby the free edge is parallel to the plane of the ear." [HPO:probinson, pmid:19152421]
data.comment: This is most often seen in the superior helix where it must be distinguished from a Lop ear (where the usual convexity of the posterior border of the ear is lost). Helix folding is highly variable.

data.name: Macrotia
data.def: "Median longitudinal ear length greater than two standard deviations above the mean and median ear width greater than two standard deviations above the mean (objective); or, apparent increase in length and width of the pinna (subjective)." [pmid:19152421]
data.comment: This is acknowledged to be a bundled term but retained here because of its usefulness in practice. Ear length is determined by the maximal distance from the superior aspect to the inferior aspect of the external ear. If only length is increased the term Long ear should be used.

data.name: Stenosis of the external auditory canal
data.def: "An abnormal narrowing of the external auditory canal." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Recurrent otitis media
data.def: "Increased susceptibility to otitis media, as manifested by recurrent episodes of otitis media." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Conductive hearing impairment
data.def: "An abnormality of vibrational conductance of sound to the inner ear leading to impairment of sensory perception of sound." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: A conductive hearing impariment with greater than 90 dB loss.

data.name: Sensorineural hearing impairment
data.def: "A type of hearing impairment  in one or both ears related to an abnormal functionality of the cochlear nerve." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Hearing loss caused by damage or dysfunction of the auditory nerve (cranial nerve VIII, also known as the cochlear nerve).

data.name: Progressive sensorineural hearing impairment
data.def: "A progressive form of sensorineural hearing impairment." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Mixed hearing impairment
data.def: "A type of hearing loss resulting from a combination of conductive hearing impairment and sensorineural hearing impairment." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Protruding ear
data.def: "Angle formed by the plane of the ear and the mastoid bone greater than the 97th centile for age (objective); or, outer edge of the helix more than 2 cm from the mastoid at the point of maximum distance (objective)." [pmid:19152421]

data.name: Atresia of the external auditory canal
data.def: "Absence or failure to form of the external auditory canal." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the choanae
data.def: "Abnormality of the choanae (the posterior nasal apertures)." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Narrow nasal ridge
data.def: "Decreased width of the nasal ridge." [pmid:19152422]
data.comment: This feature may be accompanied by narrow nasal bridge and narrow nasal base, which should be coded separately.

data.name: Abnormality of the nasal septum
data.def: "An abnormality of the nasal septum." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the nasal bridge
data.def: "Abnormality of the nasal bridge, which is the saddle-shaped area that includes the nasal root and the lateral aspects of the nose. It lies between the glabella and the inferior boundary of the nasal bone, and extends laterally to the inner canthi." [HPO:probinson, pmid:19152422]
data.comment: The nasal root is the most depressed, superior part of the nose along the nasal ridge.

data.name: Prominent nasal bridge
data.def: "Anterior positioning of the nasal root in comparison to the usual positioning for age." [pmid:19152422]
data.comment: A prominent nasal bridge can occur irrespective of the width of the nasal bridge, and the width should be assessed separately. The nasal bridge becomes more prominent with age. Although the nasal root may be anteriorly placed without increasing the space between the eyes, prominence of the nasal bridge may be accompanied by Telecanthus or ocular Hypertelorism. If such findings are present these should be coded separately. Deep-set eyes may lead to the impression of a prominent nasal bridge, but this finding should be coded separately.

data.name: Abnormality of the nasal alae
data.def: "An abnormality of the Ala of nose." [HPO:probinson, pmid:19152422]
data.comment: The nasal ala is the tissue comprising the lateral boundary of the nose, inferiorly, surrounding the naris.

data.name: Underdeveloped nasal alae
data.def: "Thinned, deficient, or excessively arched ala nasi." [pmid:19152422]
data.comment: The alae nasi are the lateral portions of the nose or the wings of the nostrils, which partly encircle the nostrils (nares). They are usually about the width of the columella, but vary greatly depending on the shape of the nostril. Note that individuals may be described as having a Cleft ala nasi, but have a severely underdeveloped ala nasi. In an underdeveloped ala the continuity of the tissue encircling the nostril is undisturbed while in a cleft it is disrupted. With severe hypoplasia of the nasal alae, the nasal tip may appear depressed.

data.name: Wide nasal bridge
data.def: "Increased breadth of the nasal bridge (and with it, the nasal root)." [HPO:probinson, pmid:19152422]
data.comment: Care should be taken to distinguish between increased width of bone and Fullness of paranasal tissue. A wide nasal bridge should be distinguished from Telecanthus and Hypertelorism. A wide nasal bridge can be either prominent or depressed, which should be coded separately.

data.name: Abnormality of the nasal tip
data.def: "An abnormality of the nasal tip." [HPO:probinson, pmid:19152422]
data.comment: The nasal tip is located at the junction of the inferior margin of the nasal ridge and the columella. Commonly, it is the part of the nose furthest from the plane of the face. In rare circumstances, such as markedly prominent and convex nasal profiles, other parts of the ridge may be further removed from the facial plane.

data.name: Depressed nasal tip
data.def: "Decreased distance from the nasal tip to the nasal base." [pmid:19152422]
data.comment: This often accompanies a Short columella, Overhanging nasal tip, and Underdeveloped nasal tip, but these should be assessed and coded separately.

data.name: Convex nasal ridge
data.def: "Nasal ridge curving anteriorly to an imaginary line that connects the nasal root and tip. The nose appears often also prominent, and the columella low." [pmid:19152422]

data.name: Wide nose
data.def: "Interalar distance more than two standard deviations above the mean for age, i.e., an apparently increased width of the nasal base and alae." [pmid:19152422]

data.name: Narrow nasal bridge
data.def: "Decreased width of the bony bridge of the nose." [pmid:19152422]
data.comment: The narrowness may be accompanied by a sharp, keel-shaped appearance. The nasal bridge may narrow with age.

data.name: Prominent nose
data.def: "Distance between subnasale and pronasale more than two standard deviations above the mean, or alternatively, an apparently increased anterior protrusion of the nasal tip." [pmid:19152422]

data.name: Choanal stenosis
data.def: "Abnormal narrowing of the choana (the posterior nasal aperture)." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Choanal atresia
data.def: "Absence or abnormal closure of the choana (the posterior nasal aperture)." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Depressed nasal ridge
data.def: "Lack of prominence of the nose resulting from a posteriorly-placed nasal ridge." [HPO:probinson, pmid:19152422]
data.comment: The adjective 'depressed' here does not indicate an active process but a status. The feature should be assessed in a profile view. This finding is typically associated with a Short columella, but this should be assessed separately.

data.name: Narrow nose
data.def: "Interalar distance more than 2 SD below the mean for age, or alternatively, an apparently decreased width of the nasal base and alae." [pmid:19152422]
data.comment: Note: a small nose has both decreased height and a decreased width. These should be coded separately.

data.name: Abnormality of the neck
data.def: "An abnormality of the neck." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Webbed neck
data.def: "Pterygium colli is a congenital skin fold that runs along the sides of the neck down to the shoulders. It involves an ectopic fibrotic facial band superficial to the trapezius muscle. Excess hair-bearing skin is also present and extends down the cervical region well beyond the normal hairline." [HPO:probinson, pmid:24523736]

data.name: Thickened nuchal skin fold
data.def: "A thickening of the skin thickness in the posterior aspect of the fetal neck. A nuchal fold measurement is obtained in a transverse section of the fetal head at the level of the cavum septum pellucidum and thalami, angled posteriorly to include the cerebellum. The measurement is taken from the outer edge of the occiput bone to the outer skin limit directly in the midline. A measurement 6 mm or more is considered significant between 18 and 24 weeks and a measurement of 5 mm or more is considered significant at 16 to 18 weeks (pmid:16100637)." [HPO:probinson, pmid:16100637]
data.comment: A thickened nuchal fold should be distinguished from cystic hygroma, in which the skin in this area has fluid-filled loculations. A thickened nuchal fold should not be confused with nuchal translucency, which is a specific measurement of fluid in the posterior aspect of the neck at 11 to 14 weeks gestation (see practice guidelines at http://www.sogc.org).

data.name: Broad neck
data.def: "Increased side-to-side width of the neck." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Cystic hygroma
data.def: "A cystic lymphatic lesion of the neck." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Cystic hygroma refers to a cystic lymphatic lesion, that can in principle occur anywhere in the body, but is most commonly seen in the head and neck region. The term 'Cystic hygroma' alone is generally used to refer to cystic hygroma of the neck.

data.name: Abnormality of the eye
data.def: "Any abnormality of the eye, including location, spacing, and intraocular abnormalities." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the retina
data.def: "An abnormality of the retina." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the cornea
data.def: "Any abnormality of the cornea, which is the transparent tissue at the front of the eye that covers the iris, pupil, and anterior chamber." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Microcornea
data.def: "A congenital abnormality of the cornea in which the cornea and the anterior segment of the eye are smaller than normal. The horizontal diameter of the cornea does not reach 10 mm even in adulthood." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Note that the cornea's diameter is normally about 9.5-10.0 mm at birth and reaches 10.0-12-5 mm in adulthood.

data.name: Megalocornea
data.def: "An enlargement of the cornea with normal clarity and function. Megalocornea is diagnosed with a horizontal corneal diameter of 12 mm or more at birth or 13 mm or more after two years of age." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Strabismus
data.def: "Strabismus (also known as squint) is a condition in which the eyes are not properly aligned with each other." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Retinopathy
data.def: "Any noninflammatory disease of the retina. This nonspecific term is retained here because of its wide use in the literature, but if possible new annotations should indicate the precise type of retinal abnormality." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the eyelid
data.def: "An abnormality of the eyelids." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the fovea
data.def: "An abnormality of the fovea centralis, the central area of the macula that mediates central, high resolution vision and contains the largest concentration of cone cells in the retina." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Downslanted palpebral fissures
data.def: "The palpebral fissure inclination is more than two standard deviations below the mean." [pmid:19125427]

data.name: Recurrent corneal erosions
data.def: "The presence of recurrent corneal epithelial erosions. Although most corneal epithelial defects heal quickly, some may show recurrent ulcerations." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Abnormality of eye movement
data.def: "An abnormality in voluntary or involuntary eye movements or their control." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Glaucoma
data.def: "Glaucoma refers loss of retinal ganglion cells in a characteristic pattern of optic neuropathy usually associated with increased intraocular pressure." [HPO:probinson, pmid:11815354]
data.comment: The feature that differentiates glaucoma from other causes of visual morbidity is a characteristic pattern of damage to the optic nerve head. This is most easily recognised at the superior and inferior poles of the optic disc. The vertical cup:disc ratio (VCDR) has proved to be a simple, relatively robust index of glaucomatous loss of the neuroretinal rim. As with intraocular pressure, VCDR is a continuous variable within the population.

data.name: Abnormality of the conjunctiva
data.def: "An abnormality of the conjunctiva." [HPO:curators]
data.comment: The conjunctiva is a thin, sparsely vascularized transparent membrane that covers and protects the sclera (the bulbar conjunctiva), and forms the inner lining of the eyelids (the tarsal conjunctiva).

data.name: Abnormality of vision
data.def: "Abnormality of eyesight (visual perception)." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Visual impairment
data.def: "Visual impairment (or vision impairment) is vision loss (of a person) to such a degree as to qualify as an additional support need through a significant limitation of visual capability resulting from either disease, trauma, or congenital or degenerative conditions that cannot be corrected by conventional means, such as refractive correction, medication, or surgery." [DDD:gblack]

data.name: Telecanthus
data.def: "Distance between the inner canthi more than two standard deviations above the mean (objective); or, apparently increased distance between the inner canthi." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Dystopia canthorum (also called telecanthus) describes a subtle but unusual facial feature in which the inner corners of the eyes (canthi) are spaced farther apart than normal, yet the eyes (pupils) themselves are not necessarily widely spaced.

data.name: Ptosis
data.def: "The upper eyelid margin is positioned 3 mm or more lower than usual and covers the superior portion of the iris (objective); or, the upper lid margin obscures at least part of the pupil (subjective)." [pmid:19125427]

data.name: Conjunctivitis
data.def: "Inflammation of the  conjunctiva." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Retinitis pigmentosa
data.def: "Hereditary degeneration and atrophy of the retina." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Retinitis pigmentosa is a group of hereditary diseases of the eye. However, the term retinitis pigmentosa has also been used to describe the retinal findings characteristic of these diseases but also seen on other diseases such as Usher syndrome. It is preferable to describe the findings precisely if possible, but this term is kept for convenience.

data.name: Abnormal electroretinogram
data.def: "Any abnormality of the electrical responses of various cell types in the retina as measured by electroretinography." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The electrical responses of the photoreceptors (rods and cones), inner retinal cells (bipolar and amacrine cells), and the ganglion cells can be assessed by ERG.

data.name: Slow saccadic eye movements
data.def: "An abnormally slow velocity of the saccadic eye movements." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Saccades are rapid eye movements that align the fovea with the target.

data.name: Abnormality of the lens
data.def: "An abnormality of the lens." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Cataract
data.def: "A cataract is an opacity or clouding that develops in the crystalline lens of the eye or in its capsule." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Note that some ophthalmologists call any opacity in the lens a cataract, while others restrict the term to lens opacities that impair vision. We use the term to refer to the first meaning (any lens opacity).

data.name: Congenital cataract
data.def: "A congenital cataract." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: In general, congenital cataracts are bilateral and that is the assumption with the terms in this cataract subhierarchy.

data.name: Alacrima
data.def: "Absence of tear secretion." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Alacrima is generally a congenital deficiency.

data.name: Subcapsular cataract
data.def: "A cataract that affects the region of the lens directly beneath the capsule of the lens." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the iris
data.def: "An abnormality of the iris, which is the pigmented muscular tissue between the cornea and the lens, that is perforated by an opening called the pupil." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Aniridia
data.def: "Congenital absence of the iris." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Progressive visual loss
data.def: "A reduction of previously attained ability to see." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of refraction
data.def: "An abnormality in the process of focusing of light by the eye in order to produce a sharp image on the retina." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Papilledema is disc edema secondary to increased intracranial pressure.

data.name: Hypermetropia
data.def: "An abnormality of refraction characterized by the ability to see objects in the distance clearly, while objects nearby appear blurry." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Retinal detachment
data.def: "Separation of the inner layers of the retina (neural retina) from the pigment epithelium." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Optic disc pallor
data.def: "A pale yellow discoloration of the optic disk (the area of the optic nerve head in the retina). The optic disc normally has a pinkish hue with a central yellowish depression." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Optic disc pallor can be judged clinically with serial color photographs or by comparison to the other eye. The pallor reflects replacement of dead axons by glial tissue. The loss of the small capillaries within the nerve accounts for the shift from orange-pink to white.

data.name: External ophthalmoplegia
data.def: "Paralysis of the external ocular muscles." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Myopia
data.def: "An abnormality of refraction characterized by the ability to see objects nearby clearly, while objects in the distance appear blurry." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Retinal degeneration
data.def: "A deterioration of the retina. This nonspecific term is retained here because of its wide use in the literature, but if possible new annotations should indicate the precise type of retinal abnormality." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormal conjugate eye movement
data.def: "Any deviation from the normal motor coordination of the eyes that allows for bilateral fixation on a single object." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abolished electroretinogram (ERG)
data.def: "Lack of any response to stimulation upon electroretinography." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of color vision
data.def: "An anomaly in the ability to discriminate between or recognize colors." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the uvea
data.def: "An abnormality of the uvea, the vascular layer of the eyeball." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Retinal dystrophy
data.def: "An abnormal white reflection from the pupil rather than the usual black reflection." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The word leukocoria literally means white pupil, but leukocoria is not an abnormality of the pupil. Rather, leukocoria can be caused by cataract, retinal detachment, retinopathy of prematurity, retinal malformation, endophthalmitis, retinal vascular abnormality, and intraocular tumor (e.g., retinoblastoma).

data.name: Buphthalmos
data.def: "Buphthalmos refers to a congenital open-angle glaucoma of the eye. The term buphthalmos (from Greek 'bous' or ox and 'ophthalmos' or eye) is descriptive of an enlarged eyeglobe resulting from increased intraocular pressure. The eyeglobe is especially prone to distension in newborns and infants because its collagen filaments are not as rigid as in adults and may easily be stretched." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Keratoconus
data.def: "A cone-shaped deformity of the cornea." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Esotropia
data.def: "A form of strabismus with one or both eyes turned inward ('crossed')." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of saccadic eye movements
data.def: "An abnormality of eye movement characterized by impairment of fast (saccadic) eye movements." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Fast (saccadic) eye movements comprise voluntary or involuntary refixation movements, the fast phase of vestibular nystagmus, optokinetic nystagmus, and microsaccades.

data.name: Hypometric saccades
data.def: "Saccadic undershoot, i.e., a saccadic eye movement that has less than the magnitude that would be required to gain fixation of the object." [HPO:probinson, pmid:572501]

data.name: Visual loss
data.def: "Loss of visual acuity (implying that vision was better at a certain timepoint in live - otherwise the term is impaired vision or a subclass of that)." [HPO:sdoelken]

data.name: Scotoma
data.def: "Scotoma refers to an area or island of loss or impairment of visual acuity surrounded by a field of normal or relatively well-preserved vision." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Exotropia
data.def: "A form of strabismus with one or both eyes deviated outward." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Nasolacrimal duct obstruction
data.def: "Blockage of the  lacrimal duct." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Blepharophimosis
data.def: "A fixed reduction in the vertical distance between the upper and lower eyelids with short palpebral fissures." [pmid:19125427]
data.comment: When the palpebral fissures are severely shortened, they cannot be widely separated, actively or passively.

data.name: Upslanted palpebral fissure
data.def: "The palpebral fissure inclination is more than two standard deviations above the mean for age (objective); or, the inclination of the palpebral fissure is greater than typical for age." [pmid:19125427]

data.name: Abnormality of the optic nerve
data.def: "Abnormality of the optic nerve." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The optic nerve, which is also known as cranial nerve II, transmits visual information from the retina to the brain. The term 'optic disc' is frequently used to describe the portion of the optic nerve clinically visible on fundoscopic examination.

data.name: Progressive external ophthalmoplegia
data.def: "Initial bilateral ptosis followed by limitation of eye movements in all directions and slowing of saccades." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Progressive external ophthalmoplegia (PEO) can be regarded as a diagnosis, or as a feature of several other syndromes. The latter is the meaning of this term.

data.name: Abnormality of the sclera
data.def: "An abnormality of the sclera." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Blue sclerae
data.def: "An abnormal bluish coloration of the sclera." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the anterior chamber
data.def: "Abnormality of the anterior chamber, which is the space in the eye that is behind the cornea and in front of the iris." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Shallow anterior chamber
data.def: "Reduced depth of the anterior chamber, i.e., the anteroposterior distance between the cornea and the iris is decreased." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Ophthalmoparesis
data.def: "Ophthalmoplegia is a paralysis or weakness of one or more of the muscles that control eye movement." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Abnormality of the ear
data.def: "An abnormality of the ear." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Either a morphological abnormality or hearing deficit. This should be split more cleanly in the future.

data.name: Abnormality of the pharynx
data.def: "An anomaly of the pharynx, i.e., of the tubular structure extending from the base of the skull superiorly to the esophageal inlet inferiorly." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The pharynx is tubular structure extending from base of skull superiorly\nto esophageal inlet inferiorly, and is composed of three distinct areas: the nasopharynx, the oropharynx, and the hypopharynx, with the pharyngeal walls being composed of the superior, middle, and inferior pharyngeal constrictor muscles. It is part of the digestive system and of the conducting zone of the respiratory system.

data.name: Ophthalmoplegia
data.def: "Paralysis of one or more extraocular muscles that are responsible for eye movements." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Central scotoma
data.def: "An area of depressed vision located at the point of fixation and that interferes with central vision." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Supranuclear gaze palsy
data.def: "A supranuclear gaze palsy is an inability to look in a particular direction as a result of cerebral impairment. There is a loss of the voluntary aspect of eye movements, but, as the brainstem is still intact, all the reflex conjugate eye movements are normal." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the periorbital region
data.def: "An abnormality of the region situated around the orbit of the eye." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Macular degeneration
data.def: "Degeneration of the macula lutea." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Photophobia
data.def: "Excessive sensitivity to light with the sensation of discomfort or pain in the eyes due to exposure to bright light." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Note that the term photodysphoria is used to describe extreme photophobia.

data.name: Abnormality of the nasolacrimal system
data.def: "An abnormality of the nasolacrimal drainage system, which serves as a conduit for tear flow from the external eye to the nasal cavity." [DDD:ncarter]
data.comment: The nasolacrimal system consists of the puncta, canaliculi, lacrimal sac, and nasolacrimal duct.

data.name: Abnormality of the pupil
data.def: "An abnormality of the pupil." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Miosis
data.def: "Abnormal (non-physiological) constriction of the pupil." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of ocular smooth pursuit
data.def: "An abnormality of eye movement characterized by impaired smooth-pursuit eye movements." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Tracking eye movements consist of two different components, namely, smooth pursuit and saccades. Smooth pursuit, or just pursuit, is a class of rather slow eye movements that minimizes retinal target motion. Saccades are rapid eye movements that align the fovea with the target. Slow-pursuit eye movements are involved in tracking a slowly moving target after the saccadic system has placed the image of the target on the fovea.

data.name: Blindness
data.def: "Blindness is the condition of lacking visual perception due to physiological or neurological factors." [DDD:gblack]
data.comment: Various scales have been developed to describe the extent of vision loss and define blindness. Total blindness is the complete lack of form and visual light perception and is clinically recorded as NLP (no light perception). Blindness is frequently used to describe severe visual impairment with residual vision. Those described as having only light perception have no more sight than the ability to tell light from dark and the general direction of a light source.

data.name: Entropion
data.def: "An inward turning (inversion) of the eyelid margin." [pmid:19125427]
data.comment: The inward turned eyelid margin increases the potential for mechanical irritation of the eye by eyelashes. Entropion is to be distinguished from epiblepharon.

data.name: Blurred vision
data.def: "Lack of sharpness of vision resulting in the inability to see fine detail." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This is a very nonspecific term and it is preferable to describe the correlates of blurred vision with the corresponding terms if possible.

data.name: Posterior embryotoxon
data.def: "A posterior embryotoxon is the presence of a prominent and anteriorly displaced line of Schwalbe." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Schwalbe's line is the anatomical line found on the interior surface of the cornea, and delineates the outer limit of the corneal endothelium layer. Specifically, it represents the termination of Descemet's membrane. Up to 30% of the population has posterior embryotoxon as an isolated normal variant.

data.name: Periorbital fullness
data.def: "Increase in periorbital soft tissue." [HPO:sdoelken]

data.name: Lacrimation abnormality
data.def: "Abnormality of tear production." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Decreased lacrimation
data.def: "Abnormally decreased lacrimation, that is, reduced ability to produce tears." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Blue irides
data.def: "A markedly blue coloration of the iris." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Long palpebral fissure
data.def: "Distance between medial and lateral canthi is more than two standard deviations above the mean for age (objective); or, apparently increased length of the palpebral fissures." [pmid:19125427]

data.name: Nystagmus
data.def: "Rhythmic, involuntary oscillations of one or both eyes related to abnormality in fixation, conjugate gaze, or vestibular mechanisms." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Gaze-evoked nystagmus
data.def: "Nystagmus made apparent by looking to the right or to the left." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Dysmetric saccades
data.def: "The controller signal for saccadic eye movements has two components: the pulse that moves the eye rapidly from one point to the next, and the step that holds the eye in the new position. When both the pulse and the step are not the correct size, a dysmetric refixation eye movement results." [HPO:probinson, pmid:572501]

data.name: Amblyopia
data.def: "Reduced visual acuity that is uncorrectable by lenses in the absence of detectable anatomic defects in the eye or visual pathways." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Ambylopia can result from visual deprivation during the critical period of development of visual abilities which lasts to about the age of 8 years. Thus, ambylopia can result from strabismus, anisometropia, or high hypermetropia in there is a failure to form a focused image in one or both eyes.

data.name: Sclerocornea
data.def: "A congenital anomaly in which a part or the whole of the cornea acquires the characteristics of sclera, resulting in clouding of the cornea." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Optic atrophy
data.def: "Atrophy of the optic nerve. Optic atrophy results from the death of the retinal ganglion cell axons that comprise the optic nerve and manifesting as a pale optic nerve on fundoscopy." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The diagnosis of optic atrophy is made when the optic disc loses its normal orange-pink color. Optic atrophy is an end stage that arises from myriad causes of optic nerve damage anywhere along the path from the retina to the lateral geniculate. Some of the most common etiologies are advanced glaucoma, optic neuritis, arteritic or non-arteritic ischaemic optic neuropathy or a compressive lesion.

data.name: Abnormality of vision evoked potentials
data.def: "An anomaly of visually evoked potentials (VEP), which are electrical potentials, initiated by brief visual stimuli, which are recorded from the scalp overlying the visual cortex." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The terms visually evoked potential (VEP), visually evoked response (VER) and visually evoked cortical potential (VECP) are equivalent.

data.name: Diplopia
data.def: "Diplopia is a condition in which a single object is perceived as two images, it is also known as double vision." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Decreased electroretinogram (ERG) amplitude
data.def: "Descreased amplitude of eletrical response upon electroretinography." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Vitreoretinal degeneration
data.def: "Gradual deterioration of the vitreous humor and retina." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Ectropion
data.def: "An outward turning (eversion) or rotation of the eyelid margin." [pmid:19125427]
data.comment: Ectropion is frequently associated wit overexposure of the palpebral and scleral conjunctiva and cornea. It usually involves the lower eyelid.

data.name: Peters anomaly
data.def: "A form of anterior segment dysgenesis in which abnormal cleavage of the anterior chamber occurs. Peters anomaly is characterized by central, paracentral, or complete corneal opacity." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Lipemia retinalis
data.def: "A creamy appearance of the retinal blood vessels that occurs when the concentration of lipids in the blood are extremely increased, with pale pink to milky white retinal vessels and altered pale reflexes from choroidal vasculature." [pmid:10379021, pmid:16120862]
data.comment: Lipemia retinalis is thought to be directly correlated with the serum triglyceride level; typically, the retinal findings do not occur until the triglyceride level reaches 2500 mg per deciliter (28.2 mmol per liter).

data.name: Night blindness
data.def: "Inability to see well at night or in poor light." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Horizontal nystagmus
data.def: "Nystagmus consisting of horizontal to-and-fro eye movements." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Hypodontia
data.def: "A developmental anomaly characterized by a reduced number of teeth, whereby up to 6 teeth are missing." [HPO:ibailleulforestier]
data.comment: Hypodontia refers to a reduced number of primary or permanent teeth. Hypodontia may affect either both primary and permanent teeth or only the permanent teeth. Wisdom teeth (the third secondary maxillary and mandibular molar teeth) are not included in this count.

data.name: Carious teeth
data.def: "Caries is a multifactorial bacterial infection affecting the structure of the tooth. This term has been used to describe the presence of more than expected dental caries." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: It should be noted that it is not always possible to rule out environmental influences and that reports of association between hereditary diseases and susceptibility to dental caries should be regarded with caution.

data.name: Anodontia
data.def: "The congenital absence of all teeth." [HPO:ibailleulforestier]
data.comment: Anodontia can affect both primary and permanent teeth. Alternatively, there can be anodontia of just the permanent teeth. Anodontia must be distinguished from non-erupted teeth.

data.name: Abnormality of the incisor
data.def: "An abnormality of the Incisor tooth." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Oligodontia
data.def: "A developmental anomaly characterized by a reduced number of teeth, whereby more than 6 teeth are missing." [HPO:curators, pmid:19125428]
data.comment: The diagnosis of oligodontia requires a radiograph, as is true for anodontia and for the other designation of tooth agenesis, hypodontia. The terms hypodontia and oligodontia are sometimes used interchangeably in the literature while on other occasions hypodontia is used for selective agenesis of six or less missing teeth while oligodontia is applied when there are more than six missing teeth. Tooth agenesis or oligodontia/hypodontia can be mistaken for delayed eruption and again a radiograph is needed for diagnosis. Absence of teeth may be congenital (tooth agenesis) or acquired. The incidence of congenital absence of teeth is different depending on the type and position of the tooth [Gorlin et al, 2001].

data.name: Dental crowding
data.def: "Overlapping teeth within an alveolar ridge." [pmid:19125428]

data.name: Abnormality of dental enamel
data.def: "An abnormality of the dental enamel." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The dental enamel is the external layer of the teeth, being a highly mineralized substance consisting primarily of hydroxylapatite.

data.name: Delayed eruption of teeth
data.def: "Delayed tooth eruption, which can be defined as tooth eruption more than 2 SD beyond the mean eruption age." [HPO:ibailleulforestier, pmid:19125428]
data.comment: This term should not be used in a patient with Gingival overgrowth. There are established norms for the timing of eruption in both deciduous and permanent teeth [Garn and Rohmann, [1966]; Lunt and Law, [1974]; McDonald et al. [2004]]. Eruption is defined by the appearance of a tooth that has pierced the gum.

data.name: Hypoplasia of teeth
data.def: "Developmental hypoplasia of teeth." [HPO:ibailleulforestier]

data.name: Widely spaced teeth
data.def: "Increased spaces (diastemata) between most of the teeth in the same dental arch." [pmid:19125428]
data.comment: Wide spacing can be secondary to increased room by an unusually large dental arch, microdontia or mixed primary and secondary dentition. It should be carefully noted that slight spacing between the primary teeth is normal, so experience in evaluation is important in determining this feature. This descriptor must be distinguished from Diastema.

data.name: Dental malocclusion
data.def: "Dental malocclusion refers to an abnormality of the occlusion, or alignment, of the teeth and the way the upper and lower teeth fit together, resulting in overcrowding of teeth or in abnormal bite patterns." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Microdontia
data.def: "Decreased size of the teeth, which can be defined as a mesiodistal tooth diameter (width) more than 2 SD below mean. Alternatively, an apparently decreased maximum width of tooth." [HPO:ibailleulforestier, pmid:19125428]
data.comment: Standard reference has means and standard deviations by gender [Moyers et al, 1976].
