It is easy to measure the width of teeth, for which reason the definition of microdontia can be made with reference to the width of the tooth. However, microdontia means that the overall size of the tooth is decreased. In microdontia, the gaps between the teeth, particularly the anterior upper and lower teeth, are increased, creating diastemata. This should be assessed and coded separately.

data.name: Misalignment of teeth
data.def: "Abnormal alignment, positioning, or spacing of the teeth, i.e., misaligned teeth." [HPO:ibailleulforestier]

data.name: Natal tooth
data.def: "Erupted tooth or teeth at birth." [pmid:19125428]

data.name: Delayed eruption of permanent teeth
data.def: "Delayed tooth eruption affecting the secondary dentition." [HPO:ibailleulforestier]

data.name: Conical tooth
data.def: "An abnormal conical form of the teeth, that is, a tooth whose sides converge or taper together incisally." [HPO:ibailleulforestier]

data.name: Diastema
data.def: "Increased space between two adjacent teeth in the same dental arch." [pmid:19125428]
data.comment: Usually there is contact between the lateral aspects of the permanent teeth, at their broadest point. Diastema can apply to any pair of teeth and the term should be modified by a descriptor of the involved teeth. This descriptor must be distinguished from Widely spaced teeth.

data.name: Dentinogenesis imperfecta
data.def: "Developmental dysplasia of dentin." [HPO:ibailleulforestier]
data.comment: This term refers to the phenotypic feature of dentinogenesis imperfecta rather than to the disease entity.

data.name: Amelogenesis imperfecta
data.def: "A developmental dysplasia of the dental enamel." [HPO:ibailleulforestier, pmid:18499550]
data.comment: Amelogenesis imperfecta (AI) is a term for a clinically and genetically heterogeneous group of diseases that affect the dental enamel, occasionally in conjunction with other dental, oral and extraoral tissues. This term has often been used to describe the phenotype associated with AI, but for new annotations it is recommended to describe the individual manifestations.

data.name: Unerupted tooth
data.def: "The presence of one or more embedded tooth germs which have failed to erupt." [HPO:ibailleulforestier]

data.name: Abnormality of the nervous system
data.def: "An abnormality of the nervous system." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The nervous system comprises the neuraxis (brain, spinal cord, and ventricles), the autonomic nervous system, the enteric nervous system, and the peripheral nervous system.

data.name: Behavioral abnormality
data.def: "An abnormality of mental functioning including various affective, behavioural, cognitive and perceptual abnormalities." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Psychosis
data.def: "A condition characterized by changes of personality and thought patterns often accompanied by hallucinations and delusional beliefs." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Hyperorality
data.def: "A tendency or compulsion to examine objects by mouth." [HPO:sdoelken]

data.name: Depression
data.def: "A condition characterized by pervasive dysphoric mood, loss of interests, and inability to experience pleasure." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Autism
data.def: "Autism is a neurodevelopmental disorder characterized by impaired social interaction and communication, and by restricted and repetitive behavior. Autism begins in childhood. It is marked by the presence of markedly abnormal or impaired development in social interaction and communication and a markedly restricted repertoire of activity and interest. Manifestations of the disorder vary greatly depending on the developmental level and chronological age of the individual (DSM-IV)." [DDD:hvfirth]
data.comment: The term refers to the diagnosis of autism and is left for convenience. However, it is preferable to annotate the exact phenotypic abnormalities rather than merely the diagnostic category autism.

data.name: Aggressive behavior
data.def: "Aggressive behavior can denote verbal aggression, physical aggression against objects, physical aggression against people, and may also include aggression towards oneself." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Obsessive-compulsive behavior
data.def: "Recurrent obsessions or compulsions that are severe enough to be time consuming (i.e., they take more than 1 hour a day) or cause marked distress or significant impairment (DSM-IV)." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Dementia
data.def: "A loss of global cognitive ability of sufficient amount to interfere with normal social or occupational function. Dementia represents a loss of previously present cognitive abilities, generally in adults, and can affect memory, thinking, language, judgment, and behavior." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Autistic behavior
data.def: "A disorder beginning in childhood. It is marked by the presence of markedly abnormal or impaired development in social interaction and communication and a markedly restricted repertoire of activity and interest. Manifestations of the disorder vary greatly depending on the developmental level and chronological age of the individual (DSM-IV)." [DSM-IV:299.00, HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This term can be used to refer to autism spectrum disorder as a phenotypic feature that can be a component of a disease. Autism spectrum disorder range from a severe form, called autistic disorder, to a milder form, Asperger syndrome.

data.name: Stereotypic behavior
data.def: "A repetitive behaviour that does not serve an observable goal. In general the movements are not aimed at the environment, but at the person itself. Stereotypical behaviour is seen especially in children with sensory, intellectual and/or cognitive handicaps." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: An abnormality of behavior characterized by one or more stereotyped and restricted patterns of behavior such as inflexible adherence to specific, nonfunctional routines or rituals, stereotyped and repetitive motor mannerisms (e.g., hand or finger flapping or twisting, or complex whole-body movements), or persistent preoccupation with parts of objects.

data.name: Disinhibition
data.def: "A lack of restraint manifested in several ways, including disregard for social conventions, impulsivity, and poor risk assessment." [HPO:sdoelken]
data.comment: Disinhibition affects motor, instinctual, emotional, cognitive and perceptual aspects with signs and symptoms similar to the diagnostic criteria for mania. Hypersexuality, hyperphagia, and aggressive outbursts are indicative of disinhibited instinctual drives.

data.name: Impaired social interactions
data.def: "Difficulty in social interactions related to an impairment of characteristics such as eye contact, smiling, appropriate facial expressions, and body postures and characterized by difficulty in forming peer relationships and forming friendships." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Short attention span
data.def: "Reduced attention span characterized by distractibility and impulsivity but not necessarily satisfying the diagnostic criteria for attention deficit hyperactivity disorder." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Hallucinations
data.def: "Perceptions in a conscious and awake state in the absence of external stimuli which have qualities of real perception, in that they are vivid, substantial, and located in external objective space." [HPO:sdoelken]

data.name: Anxiety
data.def: "Feeling or dread, apprehension, and impending disaster." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Apathy
data.def: "Lack of emotion or emotional expression; a disorder of motivation that persists over time." [MeSH:D057565]

data.name: Diminished motivation
data.def: "A reduction in goal-directed behavior, that is, motivation, the determinant of behavior and adaptation that allows individuals to get started, be energized to perform a sustained and directed action." [HPO:probinson, pmid:16030444]

data.name: Delusions
data.def: "A belief that is pathological and is held despite evidence to the contrary." [HPO:sdoelken]

data.name: Delayed speech and language development
data.def: "A degree of language development that is significantly below the norm for a child of a specified age." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Language delay can be characterized by a failure to meet the developmental milestones for language development, an inability to follow directions, or slow or incomprehensible speech after the age of three years, as well as with severe problems with syntax or articulation.

data.name: Personality changes
data.def: "An abnormal shift in patterns of thinking, acting, or feeling." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This term refers to changes in personality that are perceived as being abnormal. It does not refer to the usual gradual personality changes that tend to accompany aging and certain life situations.

data.name: Abnormal peripheral nervous system morphology
data.def: "An abnormality of the peripheral nervous system, which is composed of the nerves that lead to or branch off from the central nervous system. This includes the cranial nerves (olfactory and optic nerves are technically part of the central nervous system)." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The peripheral nervous system is divided into autonomic and somatic components, which both include afferent (sensory) and efferent (motor) nerves.

data.name: Decreased nerve conduction velocity
data.def: "A reduction in the speed at which electrical signals propagate along the axon of a neuron." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Nerve conduction velocity is usually measured with surface electrodes placed on the skin over nerves at various locations. Following stimulation at one electrode, the speed at which the signal is propagated to other electrodes is recorded. Abnormal values may suggest demyelination, a conduction block, or axonopathy.

data.name: Sensory neuropathy
data.def: "Peripheral neuropathy affecting the sensory nerves." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Peripheral axonal degeneration
data.def: "Progressive deterioration of peripheral axons." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This finding is typically demonstrated by nerve biopsy.

data.name: Abnormality of the thorax
data.def: "Any abnormality of the thorax (the region of the body formed by the sternum, the thoracic vertebrae and the ribs)." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Abnormality of the sternum
data.def: "An anomaly of the sternum, also known as the breastbone." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Pectus excavatum
data.def: "A defect of the chest wall characterized by a depression of the sternum, giving the chest (\"pectus\") a caved-in (\"excavatum\") appearance." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Pectus carinatum
data.def: "A deformity of the chest caused by overgrowth of the ribs and characterized by protrusion of the sternum." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the breast
data.def: "An abnormality of the breast." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Gynecomastia
data.def: "Abnormal development of large mammary glands in males resulting in breast enlargement." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the ribs
data.def: "An anomaly of the rib." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Narrow chest
data.def: "Reduced width of the chest from side to side, associated with a reduced distance from the sternal notch to the tip of the shoulder." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the scapula
data.def: "Any abnormality of the scapula, also known as the shoulder blade." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Nephrolithiasis
data.def: "The presence of calculi (stones) in the kidneys." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Urinary stone disease is caused by supersaturation of the urine by stone forming substances including calcium, oxalate, and uric acid. Crystals or foreign bodies can act as a nidus for further stone formation. THe resulting kidney stones (calculi) lead to symptoms if they become impacted in the ureter.

data.name: Renal cortical cysts
data.def: "Cysts of the cortex of the kidney." [Eurenomics:fschaefer]

data.name: Enuresis
data.def: "Lack of the ability to control the urinary bladder leading to involuntary urination at an age where control of the bladder should already be possible." [HPO:sdoelken]

data.name: Abnormal external genitalia
data.def: "Congenital absence of the normal opening of a structure of the urinary tract." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormal internal genitalia
data.def: "An anomaly of the  adnexa, uterus, and vagina (in female) or seminal tract and prostate (in male)." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Bicornuate uterus
data.def: "The presence of a bicornuate uterus." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Uterus with two horn-shaped branches.

data.name: Abnormality of Krebs cycle metabolism
data.def: "An abnormality of the tricarboxylic acid cycle." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Poor eye contact
data.def: "Difficulty in looking at another person in the eye." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Eye contact, define as the meeting of the gaze between two people during a conversation, is an important form of nonverbal communication.

data.name: Abnormality of the endocrine system
data.def: "Ab abnormality of the endocrine system." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The endocrine system is composed of glands that secrete hormones directly into the bloodstream and includes the following glands: thyroid, parathyroids, adrenals, pancreas, gonads (testicles and ovaries), and pituitary. Many other organs, such as the kidney, liver, and heart, have secondary endocrine functions.

data.name: Abnormality of the thyroid gland
data.def: "An abnormality of the thyroid gland." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Hypothyroidism
data.def: "Deficiency of thyroid hormone." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Hypertension
data.def: "The presence of chronic increased pressure in the systemic arterial system." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Hypertension is sustained elevation of resting systolic BP (140 mm Hg or higher), diastolic BP (90 mm Hg or higher), or both.

data.name: Delayed puberty
data.def: "Passing the age when puberty normally occurs with no physical or hormonal signs of the onset of puberty." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The age at which delayed puberty may be diagnosed in a person without signs of secondary sexual development is 13 years in a girl or 14 years in a boy.

data.name: Precocious puberty
data.def: "The onset of secondary sexual characteristics before a normal age. Although it is difficult to define normal age ranges because of the marked variation with which puberty begins in normal children, precocious puberty can be defined as the onset of puberty before the age of 8 years in girls or 9 years in boys." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the parathyroid gland
data.def: "An abnormality of the parathyroid gland." [HPO:curators]
data.comment: There are four parathyroid glands, which are small endocrine glands located in the neck behind the thyroid gland that produce parathyroid hormone.

data.name: Hypoparathyroidism
data.def: "A condition caused by a deficiency of parathyroid hormone characterized by hypocalcemia and hyperphosphatemia." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Glucose intolerance
data.def: "A type of hypothyroidism that results from a defect in the thyroid gland." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the adrenal glands
data.def: "Abnormality of the adrenal glands, i.e., of the endocrine glands located at the top of the kindneys." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Adrenal hypoplasia
data.def: "Developmental hypoplasia of the adrenal glands." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Hyperthyroidism
data.def: "An abnormality of thyroid physiology characterized by excessive secretion of the thyroid hormones thyroxine (i.e., T4) and/or 3,3',5-triiodo-L-thyronine zwitterion (i.e., triiodothyronine or T3)." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Hyperactive renin-angiotensin system
data.def: "An abnormally increased activity of the renin-angiotensin system, causing hypertension by a combination of volume excess and vasoconstrictor mechanisms." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: If the kidneys sense reduced renal blood flow, as can happen with reduced blood pressure, they secrete renin into the blood, where it reacts with angiotensinogen to produce angiotensin I, which is converted to angiotensin II by angiotensin converting enzyme (ACE). Both angiotensin I and II are vasoconstrictors. Angiotensin II additionally leads to the production of aldosterone by the adrenal cortex, which in turn leads to an increase in blood volume.

data.name: Hyperparathyroidism
data.def: "Excessive production of parathyroid hormone (PTH) by the parathyroid glands." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Adrenal insufficiency
data.def: "Insufficient production of steroid hormones (primarily cortisol) by the adrenal glands as a result of a primary defect in the glands themselves." [HPO:probinson, pmid:11443143]
data.comment: Adrenal insufficiency may cause persistent vomiting, anorexia, hypoglycemia, poor weight gain in a child, or unexplained weight loss in an adult, malaise, fatigue, muscular weakness, unexplained isotonic or hyponatremic dehydration, hyperkalemia, hypotension, hypoglycemia and especially generalized hyperpigmentation.

data.name: Abnormality of renin-angiotensin system
data.def: "An abnormality of the renin-angiotensin system." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The renin-angiotensin system is a hormone system that regulates blood pressure and water (fluid) balance.

data.name: Increased circulating renin level
data.def: "An increased level of renin (PRO:000013883) in the blood." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Congenital hypothyroidism
data.def: "A type of hypothyroidism with congenital onset." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Goiter
data.def: "An enlargement of the thyroid gland." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Insulin resistance
data.def: "Increased resistance towards insulin, that is, diminished effectiveness of insulin in reducing blood glucose levels." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Hyperaldosteronism
data.def: "Overproduction of the mineralocorticoid aldosterone by the adrenal cortex." [DDD:spark, HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the hypothalamus-pituitary axis
data.def: "Abnormality of the pituitary gland (also known as hypophysis), which is an endocrine gland that protrudes from the bottom of the hypothalamus at the base of the brain. The pituitary gland secretes the hormones ACTH, TSH, PRL, GH, endorphins, FSH, LH, oxytocin, and antidiuretic hormone. The secretion of hormones from the anterior pituitary is under the strict control of hypothalamic hormones, and the posterior pituitary is essentially an extension of the hypothalamus, so that  hypothalamus and pituitary gland may be regarded as a functional unit." [DDD:spark]

data.name: Decreased fertility in females
data.def: "Secondary hyperparathyroidism refers to the production of higher than normal levels of parathyroid hormone in the presence of hypocalcemia." [HPO:probinson, pmid:19836494]
data.comment: Secondary hyperparathyroidism occurs most commonly secondary to chronic renal failure. Other causes of secondary hyperparathyroidism include osteomalacia, rickets, and malabsorption. The pathophysiology of secondary hyperparathyroidism results from abnormalities in the renal tubular absorption of phosphate with reduced phosphate excretion and hyperphosphatemia, as well as impaired renal conversion of 25-hydroxycholecalciferal to 1,25-dihydroxycholecalciferol, which in turn leads to a decrease in the intestinal absorption of calcium. In combination, elevated serum phosphate levels and reduced vitamin D production result in decreases in serum calcium levels or hypocalcemia, leading to hyperparathyroidism.

data.name: Diabetes insipidus
data.def: "A state of excessive water intake and hypotonic (dilute) polyuria. Diabetes insipidus may be due to failure of vasopressin (AVP) release (central or neurogenic diabetes insipidus) or to a failure of the kidney to respond to AVP (nephrogenic diabetes insipidus)." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Short sternum
data.def: "Decreased inferosuperior length of the sternum." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Hypoplastic scapulae
data.def: "Underdeveloped scapula." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Thin ribs
data.def: "Ribs with a reduced diameter." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Broad ribs
data.def: "Increased width of ribs." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Cupped ribs
data.def: "Wide, concave rib end." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the clavicle
data.def: "Any abnormality of the clavicles (collar bones)." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Long clavicles
data.def: "Increased length of the clavicles." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Short clavicles
data.def: "Reduced length of the clavicles." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The costochondral junction is the structure where the ribs articulate with the sternum.

data.name: Lateral clavicle hook
data.def: "An excessive upward convexity of the lateral clavicle." [HPO:probinson, pmid:7322653]

data.name: Thickened ribs
data.def: "Increased thickness (diameter) of ribs." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Rib fusion
data.def: "Complete or partial merging of adjacent ribs." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Anterior rib cupping
data.def: "Wide, concave anterior rib end." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Sprengel anomaly
data.def: "A congenital skeletal deformity characterized by the elevation of one scapula (thus, one scapula is located superior to the other)." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Sprengel deformity is associated with malposition and dysplasia of the scapula and also involves regional muscle hypoplasia or atrophy, which causes disfigurement and limitation of shoulder movement. Sprengel deformity may be unilateral or bilateral and occur in isolation or as a syndromic component. Abduction of shoulder beyond 90 degrees is impossible.

data.name: Shield chest
data.def: "A broad chest." [HPO:probinson, pmid:22368597]
data.comment: Stretching of the thoracic cage as a result of fetal edema may contribute to the shield chest with widely spaced nipples that can be obsered in persons with Turner syndrome.

data.name: Broad clavicles
data.def: "Increased width (cross-sectional diameter) of the clavicles." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the costochondral junction
data.def: "Any anomaly of the costochondral junction. The costochondral junctions are located between the distal part of the ribs and the costal cartilages, which are bars of hyaline cartilage that connect the ribs to the sternum." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The first seven pairs of ribs are connected with the sternum; the next three ribs are each articulated with the lower border of the cartilage of the preceding rib; the last two ribs have pointed extremities, which do not connect with the sternum.

data.name: Enlargement of the costochondral junction
data.def: "Abnormally increased size of the costochondral junctions, which are located between the distal part of the ribs and the costal cartilages, which are bars of hyaline cartilage that connect the ribs to the sternum." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the skeletal system
data.def: "An abnormality of the skeletal system." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Beaded ribs, sometimes referred to as rachitic rosary, were often seen in rachitic children.

data.name: Abnormality of the vertebral column
data.def: "Any abnormality of the vertebral column." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Platyspondyly
data.def: "A flattened vertebral body shape with reduced distance between the vertebral endplates." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of skeletal maturation
data.def: "The bones of the skeleton undergo a series of characteristic changes in size, shape, and calcification from fetal life until puberty. An abnormality of this process can include delayed or accelerated skeletal maturation, or deviation of some, but not all bones from the expected patterns of maturation." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Osteopenia
data.def: "Osteopenia refers to a reduction in bone mineral density (BMD) below normal peak BMD but not low enough to be classified as osteoporosis. According to the WHO, osteopenia is characterized by a value of BMD more than 1 standard deviation below the young adult mean, but less than 2 standard deviations below this value." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Osteoporosis
data.def: "Osteoporosis is a systemic skeletal disease characterized by low bone density and microarchitectural deterioration of bone tissue with a consequent increase in bone fragility. According to the WHO, osteoporosis is characterized by a value of BMD 2.5 standard deviations or more below the young adult mean." [HPO:curators]
data.comment: Note, that this class is not equivalent to "generalized osteoporosis", which is a subclass of this class

data.name: Hypoplastic ilia
data.def: "Underdevelopment of the ilium." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the skin
data.def: "An abnormality of the skin." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Hyperpigmentation of the skin
data.def: "A darkening of the skin related to an increase in melanin production and deposition." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Single transverse palmar crease
data.def: "The distal and proximal transverse palmar creases are merged into a single transverse palmar crease." [HPO:probinson, pmid:19125433]
data.comment: The presence of a single palmar crease (instead of the two palmar creases that are typically present).

data.name: Acanthosis nigricans
data.def: "A dermatosis characterized by thickened, hyperpigmented plaques, typically on the intertriginous surfaces and neck." [DDD:cmoss, pmid:19061584]
data.comment: Acanthosis nigricans is seen in a variety of syndromes including those characterized by insulin resistance or fibroblast growth factor receptor (FGFR) mutations, and may also occur as an adverse effect of several medications that promote hyperinsulinemia.

data.name: Cafe-au-lait spot
data.def: "Cafe-au-lait spots are hyperpigmented lesions that can vary in color from light brown to dark brown with smooth borders and having a size of 1.5 cm or more in adults and 0.5 cm or more in children." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The phrase cafe-au-lait comes from the French word for milk-coffee. A single cafe-au-lait spot can be an isolated finding in otherwise normal individuals. Multiple cafe-au-lait spots often indicate the presence of neurofibromatosis type 1 but may also be seen in other diseases including McCune-Albright syndrome, tuberous sclerosis, and Fanconi anemia.

data.name: Dry skin
data.def: "Skin characterized by the lack of natural or normal moisture." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Hyperkeratosis
data.def: "Hyperkeratosis is thickening of the outer layer of the skin, the stratum corneum, which is composed of large, polyhedral, plate-like envelopes filled with keratin which are the dead cells that have migrated up from the stratum granulosum." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Thin skin
data.def: "Reduction in thickness of the skin, generally associated with a loss of suppleness and elasticity of the skin." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Eczema
data.def: "Eczema is a form of dermatitis. The term eczema is broadly applied to a range of persistent skin conditions and can be related to a number of underlying conditions. Manifestations of eczema can include dryness and recurring skin rashes with redness, skin edema, itching and dryness, crusting, flaking, blistering, cracking, oozing, or bleeding." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Hypohidrosis
data.def: "Abnormally diminished capacity to sweat." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Ectodermal dysplasia
data.def: "Ectodermal dysplasia is a group of conditions in which there is abnormal development of the skin, hair, nails, teeth, or sweat glands." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This term is kept in the HPO for now as 'ectodermal dysplasia' has been recorded as a phenotypic of other disorders such as DEAFNESS WITH ANHIDROTIC ECTODERMAL DYSPLASIA (MIM125050). Nevertheless it is preferable to use precise descriptions of the phenotypic abnormalities and this term should not be used for new annotations. It will be made obsolete in the future.

data.name: Edema
data.def: "An abnormal accumulation of fluid beneath the skin, or in one or more cavities of the body." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Edema may be related to one or more of the following factors: 1) increased capillary hydrostatic pressure, 2) decreased osmotic pressure of plasma, 3) decreased tissue tension and lymphatic drainage, 4) increased osmotic pressure of tissue fluids, and 5) increased capillary permeability.

data.name: Anhidrosis
data.def: "Inability to sweat." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the sweat gland
data.def: "An abnormality of the sweat gland." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Cutis laxa
data.def: "Wrinkled, redundant, inelastic and sagging skin." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Hyperextensible skin
data.def: "A condition in which the skin can be stretched beyond normal, and then returns to its initial position." [HPO:sdoelken]
data.comment: Skin hyperelasticity is to be distinguished from cutis laxa, which refers to extra, redundant skin which tends to hang in folds.

data.name: Hyperhidrosis
data.def: "Abnormal excessive perspiration (sweating)." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Soft skin
data.def: "Subjective impression of increased softness upon palpitation of the skin." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Pallor
data.def: "Abnormally pale skin." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Palmoplantar keratoderma
data.def: "Abnormal thickening of the skin of the palms of the hands and the soles of the feet." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Skin rash
data.def: "A red eruption of the skin." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Pruritus
data.def: "Pruritus is an itch or a sensation that makes a person want to scratch. This term refers to an abnormally increased disposition to experience pruritus." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Xanthomatosis
data.def: "The presence of multiple xanthomas (xanthomata) in the skin. Xanthomas are yellowish, firm, lipid-laden nodules in the skin." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Cutaneous photosensitivity
data.def: "An increased sensitivity of the skin to light. Photosensitivity may result in a rash upon exposure to the sun (which is known as photodermatosis). Photosensitivity can be diagnosed by phototests in which light is shone on small areas of skin." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Molluscoid pseudotumors
data.def: "Bluish-grey, spongy nodules associated with scars over pressure points and easily traumatized areas like the elbows and knees." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Axillary freckling
data.def: "The presence in the axillary region (armpit) of an increased number of freckles, small circular spots on the skin that are darker than the surrounding skin because of deposits of melanin." [pmid:12186179]

data.name: Hypertrichosis
data.def: "Hypertrichosis is increased hair growth that is abnormal in quantity or location." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of skin pigmentation
data.def: "An abnormality of the pigmentation of the skin." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Pyoderma is mainly seen with bacterial skin infections but can also be observed in autoimmune conditions.

data.name: Lymphedema
data.def: "Localized fluid retention and tissue swelling caused by a compromised lymphatic system." [HPO:sdoelken]

data.name: Hypotrichosis
data.def: "Congenital lack of hair growth." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Unlike alopecia, which describes hair loss where formerly there was hair growth, hypotrichosis describes a situation where there wasn't any hair growth in the first place.

data.name: Hirsutism
data.def: "Abnormally increased hair growth referring to a male pattern of body hair (androgenic hair)." [HPO:sdoelken]

data.name: Hypopigmentation of the skin
data.def: "A reduction of skin color related to a decrease in melanin production and deposition." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Multiple lipomas
data.def: "The presence of multiple lipomas (a type of benign tissue made of fatty tissue)." [HPO:sdoelken]
data.comment: A lipoma is a benign tumor composed of fatty tissue. They are the most common form of soft tissue tumor and are usually soft to the touch, movable, and generally painless (but there is a separate entity of painful multiple lipomas which is a hereditary disease called Dercum disease or adiposis dolorosa). Many lipomas are small (under one centimeter diameter) but can enlarge to sizes greater than six centimeters. Lipomas are commonly found in adults from 40 to 60 years of age, but can also be found in children.

data.name: Abnormal palmar dermatoglyphics
data.def: "An abnormality of the dermatoglyphs, i.e., an abnormality of the patterns of ridges of the skin of palm of hand." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Erythroderma
data.def: "An inflammatory exfoliative dermatosis involving nearly all of the surface of the skin. Erythroderma develops suddenly. A patchy erythema may generalize and spread to affect most of the skin. Scaling may appear in 2-6 days and be accompanied by hot, red, dry skin, malaise, and fever." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Hemangioma
data.def: "A hemangioma is a benign tumor characterized by blood-filled spaces lined by benign endothelial cells. A hemangioma characterized by large endothelial spaces (caverns) is called a cavernous hemangioma (in contrast to a hemangioma with small endothelial spaces, which is called capillary hemangioma)." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Poikiloderma
data.def: "Poikiloderma refers to a patch of skin with (1) reticulated hypopigmentation and hyperpigmentation, (2) wrinkling secondary to epidermal atrophy, and (3) telangiectasias." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Poikiloderma does not refer to a specific disease entity, but can be seen owing to a number of different causes.

data.name: Fragile skin
data.def: "Skin that splits easily with minimal injury." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Parakeratosis
data.def: "Abnormal formation of the keratinocytes of the epidermis characterized by persistence of nuclei, incomplete formation of keratin, and moistness and swelling of the keratinocytes." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Persistence of the nuclei of keratinocytes as they rise into the stratum corneum of the epidermis. Parakeratosis is observed as scaling in many conditions such as psoriasis.

data.name: Vitiligo
data.def: "Redness of the skin of the face, caused by hyperemia of the capillaries in the lower layers of the skin." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Cavernous hemangioma
data.def: "The presence of a cavernous hemangioma. A hemangioma characterized by large endothelial spaces (caverns) is called a cavernous hemangioma." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: In infants, atopic dermatitis is known as infantile eczema.

data.name: Seborrheic dermatitis
data.def: "Seborrheic dermatitis is a form of eczema which is closely related to dandruff. It causes dry or greasy peeling of the scalp, eyebrows, and face, and sometimes trunk." [HPO:curators]
data.comment: Dandruff.

data.name: Erysipelas
data.def: "Increased susceptibility to erysipelas, as manifested by a medical history of repeated episodes of erysipelas, which is a superficial infection of the skin, typically involving the lymphatic system." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Milia
data.def: "Presence of multiple small cysts containing keratin (skin protein) and presenting as tiny pearly-white bumps just under the surface of the skin." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Milia are a normal finding in newborn babies (40-50%), often occurring around the nose.

data.name: Aplasia cutis congenita
data.def: "A developmental defect resulting in the congenital absence of skin in multiple or solitary non-inflammatory, well-demarcated, oval or circular ulcers with a diameter of about 1 to 2 cm. Aplasia cutis congenita most commonly occurs on the scalp, but may present in the face, trunk, or limbs." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Poor wound healing
data.def: "A reduced ability to heal cutaneous wounds." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Pterygium
data.def: "Pterygia are 'winglike' triangular membranes occurring in the neck, eyes, knees, elbows, ankles or digits." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Acne
data.def: "A skin condition in which there is an increase in sebum secretion by the pilosebaceous apparatus associated with  open comedones (blackheads), closed comedones (whiteheads), and pustular nodules (papules, pustules, and cysts)." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Thickened skin
data.def: "Laminar thickening of skin." [HPO:sdoelken]

data.name: Biliary tract abnormality
data.def: "An abnormality of the biliary tree." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Cholelithiasis
data.def: "Hard, pebble-like deposits that form within the gallbladder." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Gallstones range in size from as small as a grain of sand to as large as a golf ball. Cholesterol gallstones are the most common type of gallstone. Gallstones resulting from too much bilirubin in the bile are referred to as pigment stones.

data.name: Cholecystitis
data.def: "The presence of inflammatory changes in the gallbladder." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Ectopia lentis
data.def: "Dislocation or malposition of the crystalline lens of the eye. A partial displacement (or dislocation) of the lens is described as a subluxation of the lens, while a complete displacement is termed luxation of the lens. A complete displacement occurs if the lens is completely outside the patellar fossa of the lens, either in the anterior chamber, in the vitreous, or directly on the retina. If the lens is partially displaced but still contained within the lens space, then it is termed subluxation." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Corneal arcus
data.def: "A hazy, grayish-white ring about 2 mm in width located close to but separated from the limbus (the corneoscleral junction). Corneal arcus generally occurs bilaterally, and is related to lipid deposition in the cornea. Corneal arcus can occur in elderly persons as a part of the aging process but may be associated with hypercholesterolemia in people under the age of 50 years." [HPO:curators]
data.comment: A grey opaque line which surrounds the margin of the cornea caused by lipid deposits.

data.name: Congenital glaucoma
data.def: "Papilledema refers to edema (swelling) of the optic disc secondary to any factor which increases cerebral spinal fluid pressure." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The borders of the optic disc are normally clear and well defined upon fundoscopic examination. Papilledema is optic disc swelling that can lead to the blurring of optic margins and elevation of optic disc.

data.name: Brushfield spots
data.def: "The presence of whitish spots in a ring-like arrangement at the periphery of the iris." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Brushfield spots are relatively common in the general population but opccur more frequently in persons with certain disorders (especially Down syndrome).

data.name: Absent lacrimal punctum
data.def: "No identifiable superior and/or inferior lacrimal punctum." [pmid:19125427]
data.comment: The lacrimal puncta (openings of the tear ducts) are normally located at the medial margin of each eyelid. The opening on the lower eyelid border is more visible than the opening on the upper eyelid border.

data.name: Optic nerve dysplasia
data.def: "The presence of developmental dysplasia of the optic nerve." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Hypertensive retinopathy
data.def: "A type of anterior uveitis, in which there is Inflammation of the iris and the ciliary body." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the fundus
data.def: "Dryness of the eye related to deficiency of the tear film components (aqueous, mucin, or lipid), lid surface abnormalities, or epithelial abnormalities. Keratoconjunctivitis sicca often results in a scratchy or sandy sensation (foreign body sensation) in the eyes, and may also be associated with itching, inability to produce tears, photosensitivity, redness, pain, and difficulty in moving the eyelids." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Heterochromia iridis
data.def: "Heterochromia iridis is a difference in the color of the iris in the two eyes." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Angioid streaks of the retina
data.def: "Bilateral, narrow, irregular lines inferior to the retina and emanating in a radiating fashion from the optic disc." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Angioid streaks result from breaks in a weakened Bruch's membrane.

data.name: Abnormality of the macula
data.def: "An abnormality of the macula lutea is an oval-shaped highly pigmented yellow spot near the center of the retina." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Retinal atrophy
data.def: "Underdevelopment of the macula lutea." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Posterior polar cataract
data.def: "A polar cataract that affects the posterior pole of the lens." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of corneal size
data.def: "Any abnormality of the size or morphology of the cornea." [HPO:curators]
data.comment: Juvenile cataracts are generally either hereditary (especially if bilateral) or due to trauma (especially if unilateral).

data.name: Visual field defect
data.def: "Absence or underdevelopment of the choroid." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Corneal dystrophy
data.def: "An abnormality of the cornea that is characterized by opacity of one or parts of the cornea." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Eyelash inversion.

data.name: Constricted visual fields
data.def: "Partial dislocation of the lens of the eye." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Partial dislocation of the lens of the eye can be recognized by trembling of the iris (iridodonesis).

data.name: Optic neuropathy
data.def: "The presence of an increased number of twists and turns of the retinal arterioles." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Severe visual impairment
data.def: "An epibulbar dermoid is a benign tumor typically found at the junction of the cornea and sclera (limbal epibullar dermoid)." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Orbital cyst
data.def: "Presence of a cyst in the region of the orbita. Orbital cysts can be derived from epithelial or glandular tissue within or surrounding the orbit (lacrimal glands, salivary glands, conjunctival, oral, nasal, or sinus epithelium)." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: A conical projection of the anterior or posterior surface of the lens.

data.name: Retinal exudate
data.def: "Fluid which has escaped from retinal blood vessels with a high concentration of lipid, protein, and cellular debris with a typically bright, reflective, white or cream colored appearance on the surface of the retina." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Retinal exudates indicate increased vessel permeability and an associated risk of retinal edema.

data.name: Impaired horizontal smooth pursuit
data.def: "An abnormality of ocular smooth pursuit characterized by an impairment of the ability to track horizontally moving objects." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Saccadic smooth pursuit
data.def: "An abnormality of tracking eye movements in which smooth pursuit is interrupted by an abnormally high number of saccadic movements." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Tracking eye movements consist of two different components, namely, smooth pursuit and saccades. Smooth pursuit, or just pursuit, is a class of rather slow eye movements that minimizes retinal target motion. Saccades are rapid eye movements that align the fovea with the target.

data.name: Septate vagina
data.def: "The presence of a vaginal septum, thereby creating a vaginal duplication. The septum is longitudinal in the majority of cases." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Abnormality of the hand
data.def: "An abnormality affecting one or both hands." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the metacarpal bones
data.def: "An abnormality of the metacarpal bones." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Broad palm
data.def: "For children from birth to 4 years of age the palm width is more than 2 SD above the mean; for children from 4 to 16 years of age the palm width is above the 95th centile; or, the width of the palm appears disproportionately wide for the length." [HPO:probinson, pmid:19125433]
data.comment: Hand width is measured across the palm at the level of the MCPJ (radial aspect of the second MCPJ to the ulnar aspect of the fifth MCPJ) [Hall et al., 2007]. Caution is advised with the subjective assessment as short metacarpals can mimic a broad palm. In persons with polydactyly that includes a supernumerary metacarpal, that should be separately coded and the measurement technique from Hall et al, [2007] would need to be modified to account for the supernumerary digit (i.e., with postaxial polydactyly, measure to the sixth MCPJ).

data.name: Ulnar claw
data.def: "An abnormal hand position characterized by hyperextension of the fourth and fifth fingers at the metacarpophalangeal joints and flexion of the interphalangeal joints of the same fingers such that they are curled towards the palm." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: An ulnar claw, also known as claw hand, is an abnormal hand position that is associated with lesions of the ulnar nerve. Note that ulnar claw is to be distinguished from ectrodactyly, which also can be referred to as claw hand.

data.name: Ulnar deviation of the hand or of fingers of the hand
Abnormalities of placenta or umbilical cord
data.def: "An abnormality of the placenta (the organ that connects the developing fetus to the uterine wall) or of the umbilical cord (the cord that connects the fetus to the placenta)." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Short umbilical cord
data.def: "Decreased length of the umbilical cord." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of prenatal development or birth
data.def: "An abnormality of the fetus or the birth of the fetus, excluding structural abnormalities." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Because of the close link between prenatal developmental abnormalities and abnormalities of the birth process, a single term is chosen to subsume both classes of abnormality.

data.name: Autoamputation
data.def: "Spontaneous detachment (amputation) of an appendage from the body." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the thenar eminence
data.def: "An abnormality of the thenar eminence, i.e., of the muscle on the palm of the human hand just beneath the thumb." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Abnormality of the fingernails
data.def: "An abnormality of the fingernails." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Small thenar eminence
data.def: "Underdevelopment of the thenar eminence with reduced palmar soft tissue mass surrounding the base of the thumb." [HPO:probinson, pmid:19125433]
data.comment: The reduced soft tissue is typically abductor pollicis brevis and flexor pollicis brevis muscle bulk. Detection of this abnormality entails clinical judgment, especially in mild cases. The bulk of the muscle mass around the base of the thumb is diminished, and there may be a mild concavity over the volar aspect of the first metacarpal. When the deficiency is unilateral, comparison between the two hands will point up the often-subtle change in contour of the thenar muscles. If the degree of involvement is severe, the palm may taper in width proximally.

data.name: Intellectual disability
data.def: "Subnormal intellectual functioning which originates during the developmental period. Intellectual disability, previously referred to as mental retardation, has been defined as an IQ score below 70." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This term should be used for children at least five years old. For younger children, consider the term Global developmental delay (HP:0001263).

data.name: Seizures
data.def: "Seizures are an intermittent abnormality of the central nervous system due to a sudden, excessive, disorderly discharge of cerebral neurons and characterized clinically by some combination of disturbance of sensation, loss of consciousness, impairment of psychic function, or convulsive movements. The term epilepsy is used to describe chronic, recurrent seizures." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The term epilepsy is not used to describe recurrent febrile seizures. Epilepsy presumably reflects an abnormally reduced seizure threshold.

data.name: Muscular hypotonia
data.def: "Muscular hypotonia is an abnormally low muscle tone (the amount of tension or resistance to movement in a muscle), often involving reduced muscle strength. Hypotonia is characterized by a diminished resistance to passive stretching." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Lethargy
data.def: "A state of  disinterestedness, listlessness, and indifference, resulting in difficulty performing simple tasks or concentrating." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Intellectual disability, mild
data.def: "Mild intellectual disability is defined as an intelligence quotient (IQ) in the range of 50-69." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Coma
data.def: "Complete absence of wakefulness and content of conscience, which manifests itself as a lack of response to any kind of external stimuli." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Coma is generally a result of diffuse or extensive involvement of both hemispheres of the brain or lesions in the brainstem.

data.name: Dysarthria
data.def: "Dysarthric speech is a general description referring to a neurological speech disorder characterized by poor articulation. Depending on the involved neurological structures, dysarthria may be further classified as spastic, flaccid, ataxic, hyperkinetic and hypokinetic, or mixed." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Global developmental delay
data.def: "A delay in the achievement of motor or mental milestones in the domains of development of a child, including motor skills, speech and language, cognitive skills, and social and emotional skills. This term should only be used to describe children younger than five years of age." [DDD:hvfirth, HPO:sdoelken]
data.comment: Developmental retardation is any significant lag in development in the any or all of the physical, cognitive, behavioral, emotional, or social spheres. Note that the term intellectual disability (mental retardation) refers to not merely a delay in development but rather a permanent limitation. Note that the term 'psychomotor retardation' is also used in some contexts to refer to a slowing of thought and physical movements as a result of major depression or intoxication.

data.name: Hyporeflexia
data.def: "Reduction of neurologic reflexes such as the knee-jerk reaction." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Choreoathetosis
data.def: "Involuntary movements characterized by both athetosis (inability to sustain muscles in a fixed position) and chorea (widespread jerky arrhythmic movements)." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Mental deterioration
data.def: "Loss of previously present mental abilities, generally in adults." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Hemiparesis
data.def: "Loss of strength in the arm, leg, and sometimes face on one side of the body. Hemiplegia refers to a complete loss of strength, whereas hemiparesis refers to an incomplete loss of strength." [HPO:probinson, UKB:tklockgether]

data.name: Motor delay
data.def: "A type of Developmental delay characterized by a delay in acquiring motor skills." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Polyneuropathy
data.def: "A generalized disorder of peripheral nerves." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Cerebellar atrophy
data.def: "Atrophy (wasting) of the cerebellum." [HPO:probinson, pmid:12169461]
data.comment: Cerebellar atrophy can be diagnosed if the cerebellum is small with shrunken folia and large cerebellar fissures or if it has been shown to undergo progressive volume loss.

data.name: Abnormality of the corpus callosum
data.def: "Abnormality of the corpus callosum." [HPO:probinson, pmid:21263138]
data.comment: The corpus callosum, a broad thick band of nerve fibers that connects the right and left cerebral hemispheres, is the largest white matter structure in the brain. This finding can be demonstrated by cerebral magenetic resonance tomography. The corpus callosum structurally consists of 4 major anatomic features including the rostrum, genu, corpus, and splenium.

data.name: Syncope
data.def: "Syncope refers to a generalized weakness of muscles with loss of postural tone, inability to stand upright, and loss of consciousness. Once the patient is in a horizontal position, blood flow to the brain is no longer hindered by gravitation and consciousness is regained. Unconsciousness usually lasts for seconds to minutes. Headache and drowsiness (which usually follow seizures) do not follow a syncopal attack. Syncope results from a sudden impairment of brain metabolism usually due to a reduction in cerebral blood flow." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Tetany
data.def: "A disorder characterized by muscle twitches, cramps, and carpopedal spasm, and when severe, laryngospasm and seizures. This condition is associated with unstable depolarization of axonal membranes, primarily in the peripheral nervous system." [MeSH:D013746]

data.name: Areflexia
data.def: "Absence of neurologic reflexes such as the knee-jerk reaction." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The strectch reflexes (also called deep tendon relfexes) include the knee-jerk reflex (patellar reflex, the biceps reflex, the triceps reflex, and the ankle jerk reflex or Achilles tendon reflex).

data.name: Meningitis
data.def: "Inflammation of the meninges." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Gait disturbance
data.def: "The term gait disturbance can refer to any disruption of the ability to walk. In general, this can refer to neurological diseases but also fractures or other sources of pain that is triggered upon walking. However, in the current context gait disturbance refers to difficulty walking on the basis of a neurological or muscular disease." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: If possible, this term should not be used for new annotations. Rather, a more specific term should be sought.

data.name: Confusion
data.def: "Lack of clarity and coherence of thought, perception, understanding, or action." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Generalized hypotonia
data.def: "Generalized muscular hypotonia (abnormally low muscle tone)." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Abnormality of the cranial nerves
data.def: "Abnormality affecting one or more of the cranial nerves, which emerge directly from the brain stem." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Encephalopathy
data.def: "Encephalopathy is a term that means brain disease, damage, or malfunction. In general, encephalopathy is manifested by an altered mental state." [HPO:probinson, KI:phemming]
data.comment: This term and its children are general and bundled terms that are kept for convenience. For new annotations, it is recommended that the specific phenotypic abnormalities be noted.

data.name: Parkinsonism
data.def: "Characteristic neurologic anomaly resulting form degeneration of dopamine-generating cells in the substantia nigra, a region of the midbrain, characterized clinically by shaking, rigidity, slowness of movement and difficulty with walking and gait." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormal nervous system electrophysiology
data.def: "An abnormality of the function of the electrical signals with which nerve cells communicate with each other or with muscles as measured by electrophysiological investigations." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Reduced tendon reflexes
data.def: "Diminution of tendon reflexes, which is an invariable sign of peripheral nerve disease." [HPO:probinson, pmid:20941667]
data.comment: The deep tendon reflex is a monosynaptic reflex arc with sensory and motor nerve components, but the arc is much more vulnerable to sensory nerve damage. Ankle plantar flexion is retained in all but the most severe peripheral neuropathies, and thus loss of the Achilles tendon reflex in an objective indication of a substantial sensory nerve defect.

data.name: Abnormality of the cerebellum
data.def: "An abnormality of the cerebellum." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Neonatal hypotonia
data.def: "Muscular hypotonia (abnormally low muscle tone) manifesting in the neonatal period." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Cerebellar vermis hypoplasia
data.def: "Underdevelopment of the vermis of cerebellum." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Muscle weakness
data.def: "Reduced strength of muscles." [HPO:probinson, pmid:15832536]
data.comment: It is important clinical to distinguish between muscle weakness, fatigue, and asthenia. Fatigue describes the inability to continue performing a task after multiple repetitions; in contrast, a patient with primary weakness is unable to perform the first repetition of the task. Asthenia is a sense of weariness or exhaustion in the absence of muscle weakness. Conditions that result in intrinsic muscle weakness can be divided into several main categories: infectious, neurologic, endocrine, inflammatory, rheumatologic, genetic, metabolic, electrolyte-induced, or drug-induced.

data.name: Specific learning disability
data.def: "Impairment of certain skills such as reading or writing, coordination, self-control, or attention that interfere with the ability to learn. The impairment is not related to a global deficiency of intelligence." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The term learning disability is used with different meanings in different contexts. Significant impairments of mental functioning with a reduction in IQ below 70 should be coded as mental retardation.

data.name: Absent septum pellucidum
data.def: "Absence of the septum pellucidum." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: TODO: Bundled term. Revise annotations and split this term.

data.name: Dystonia
data.def: "An abnormally increased muscular tone that causes fixed abnormal postures. There is a slow, intermittent twisting motion that leads to exaggerated turning and posture of the extremities and trunk." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Bimanual synkinesia
data.def: "Mirror hand movements." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Myoclonus
data.def: "Very brief, involuntary random muscular contractions occurring at rest, in response to sensory stimuli, or accompanying voluntary movements." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Tremor
data.def: "An unintentional, oscillating to-and-fro muscle movement." [HPO:probinson, pmid:16344298]
data.comment: Tremor is differentiated from other involuntary movement disorders, such as chorea, athetosis, ballism, tics, and myoclonus, by its repetitive, stereotyped movements of a regular amplitude and frequency. Clonus, unlike tremor, represents a rhythmic movement, which is increased by muscle stretching.

data.name: Hyperreflexia
data.def: "Hyperreflexia is the presence of hyperactive stretch reflexes of the muscles." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Reflexes are graded according to the following scale: 0=absent; 1=present but diminished; 2=normoactive; 3=exaggerated; and 4=clonus. Clonus is always abnormal, and a grade 3 reflex may be abnormal if it is asymmetric or if it was previously grade 2 or less.

data.name: Slurred speech
data.def: "Abnormal coordination of muscles involved in speech." [DDD:fmunitoni]

data.name: Megalencephaly
data.def: "Enlargement of all or parts of the cerebral hemispheres." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Holoprosencephaly
data.def: "Holoprosencephaly is a structural anomaly of the brain in which the developing forebrain fails to divide into two separate hemispheres and ventricles." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The presence of a single cerebral ventricle (instead of the usual four) may be seen as part of holoprosencephaly.

data.name: Abnormal joint morphology
data.def: "An abnormal structure or form of the joints, i.e., one or more of the articulations where two bones join." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Arthritis
data.def: "Inflammation of a joint." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Joint dislocation
data.def: "Displacement or malalignment of joints." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Limitation of joint mobility
data.def: "A reduction in the freedom of movement of one or more joints." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Joint hypermobility
data.def: "The ability of a joint to move beyond its normal range of motion." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Hip dysplasia
data.def: "The presence of developmental dysplasia of the hip." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Joint stiffness
data.def: "Joint stiffness is a perceived sensation of tightness in a joint or joints when attempting to move them after a period of inactivity. Joint stiffness typically subsides over time." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This term may be made obsolete in the future. The mild degree can be indicated in the annotation file.

data.name: Joint laxity
data.def: "Lack of stability of a joint." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Joint laxity may be caused by a number of factors including intraarticular disease and injury or slacking of extraarticular structures such as joint capsules, ligaments, and muscles.

data.name: Abnormality of the liver
data.def: "An abnormality of the liver." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Cirrhosis
data.def: "A chronic disorder of the liver in which liver tissue becomes scarred and is partially replaced by regenerative nodules and fibrotic tissue resulting in loss of liver function." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Cirrhosis is caused by chronic liver disease as a result of viral infections (hepatitis), alcohol abuse, certain medications, certain metabolic disorders of iron and copper, and many others. Cirrhosis may lead to a number of abnormalities including hepatomegaly, jaundice, abnormal liver function tests, ascites, dilatation of veins in the abdominal wall, anemia, and clotting deficiencies.

data.name: Hepatic fibrosis
data.def: "The presence of fibrosis of the liver tissue." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Cholestasis
data.def: "Impairment of bile flow due to obstruction in bile ducts." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Hepatic steatosis
data.def: "The presence of steatosis in the liver." [eMedicine:175472, HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Steatosis refers to an abnormal accumulation of lipids within a cell or tissue.

data.name: Macrovesicular hepatic steatosis
data.def: "A form of hepatic steatosis characterized by the presence of large, lipid-laden vesicles in the affected hepatocytes." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Intrahepatic cholestasis
data.def: "Impairment of bile flow due to obstruction in the small bile ducts within the liver." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Liver fibrosis is not only the result of necrosis, collapse and scar formation but also the result of derangements in the synthesis and degradation of matrix by injured mesenchymal cells.

data.name: Bile duct proliferation
data.def: "Proliferative changes of the bile ducts." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Decreased liver function
data.def: "Reduced ability of the liver to perform its functions." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Micronodular cirrhosis
data.def: "A type of cirrhosis characterized by the presence of small regenerative nodules." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: In micronodular cirrhosis (Laennec's cirrhosis or portal cirrhosis) regenerating nodules are under 3 mm. This finding can be demonstrated by liver biopsy.

data.name: Microvesicular hepatic steatosis
data.def: "A form of hepatic steatosis characterized by the presence of small, lipid-laden vesicles in the affected hepatocytes." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This finding can be demonstrated by liver biopsy.

data.name: X-linked inheritance
data.def: "A mode of inheritance that is observed for traits related to a gene encoded on the X chromosome." [HPO:curators]

data.name: X-linked recessive inheritance
data.def: "A mode of inheritance that is observed for recessive traits related to a gene encoded on the X chromosome. In the context of medical genetics, X-linked recessive disorders manifest in males (who have one copy of the X chromosome and are thus hemizygotes), but generally not in female heterozygotes who have one mutant and one normal allele." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Abnormality of the musculature of the hand
X-linked dominant inheritance
data.def: "A mode of inheritance that is observed for dominant traits related to a gene encoded on the X chromosome. In the context of medical genetics, X-linked dominant disorders tend to manifest very severely in affected males. The severity of manifestation in females may depend on the degree of skewed X inactivation." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Multifactorial inheritance
data.def: "A mode of inheritance that depends on a mixture of major and minor genetic determinants possibly together with environmental factors. Diseases inherited in this manner are termed complex diseases." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Mitochondrial inheritance
data.def: "A mode of inheritance that is observed for traits related to a gene encoded on the mitochondrial genome. Because the mitochondrial genome is essentially always maternally inherited, a mitochondrial condition can only be transmitted by females, although the condition can affect both sexes. The proportion of mutant mitochondria can vary (heteroplasmy)." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Hepatosplenomegaly
data.def: "Simultaneous enlargement of the liver and spleen." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the shoulder girdle musculature
Abnormality of the foot musculature
data.def: "An anomaly of the musculature of foot." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the musculature of the lower limbs
Abnormality of the abdomen
data.def: "Abnormality of the abdomen ('belly'), that is, the part of the body between the pelvis and the thorax." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the musculature of the thigh
Somatic mosaicism
data.def: "The presence of genetically distinct populations of somatic cells in a given organism caused by DNA mutations, epigenetic alterations of DNA, chromosomal abnormalities or the spontaneous reversion of inherited mutations." [HPO:probinson, pmid:12360233]

data.name: Abnormality of the musculature of the upper limbs
Y-linked inheritance
data.def: "A mode of inheritance that is observed for traits related to a gene encoded on the Y chromosome." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia involving the skeletal musculature
data.def: "Absence or underdevelopment of the musculature." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Abnormality of the musculature of the pelvis
data.def: "Absence or underdevelopment of the muscles of the upper arm." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Freckling
data.def: "The presence of an increased number of freckles, small circular spots on the skin that are darker than the surrounding skin because of deposits of melanin." []

data.name: Subcutaneous nodule
data.def: "Slightly elevated lesions on or in the skin with a diameter of over 5 mm." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Subcutaneous nodules may move freely within the dermis or may be fixed to skin above or subcutaneous tissue below.

data.name: Failure to thrive
data.def: "Failure to thrive (FTT) refers to a child whose physical growth is substantially below the norm." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Although there is no clear consensus on the exact definition of FTT, it is usually diagnoses in a child growing below the 3rd percentile or in a child whose decreased growth has cross two major growth percentiles (for example, from above the 75th percentile to below the 25th percentile).

data.name: Growth delay
data.def: "A deficiency or slowing down of growth pre- and postnatally." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Poor or abnormally slow gains in weight or height in a child.

data.name: Intrauterine growth retardation
data.def: "An abnormal restriction of fetal growth with fetal weight below the tenth percentile for gestational age." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Intrauterine growth restriction is a newer term that is preferred over Intrauterine growth retardation. The causes of IUGR include maternal abnormalities (chronic hypertension, cyanotic heart disease, smoking, drug abuse), placental or umbilical cord abnormalities (including placenta previa and cord anomalies), maternal medicationas, and genetic disorders of the fetus.

data.name: Obesity
data.def: "Body weight that is grossly above the acceptable or desirable weight, usually due to accumulation of excess fats in the body. The standards may vary with age, sex, genetic or cultural background. In the body mass index (BMI), a BMI greater than 30.0 kg/m2 is considered obese, and a BMI greater than 40.0 kg/m2 is considered morbidly obese." [HPO:probinson, MeSH:D009765]

data.name: Small for gestational age
data.def: "Smaller than normal size according to sex and gestational age related norms, defined as a weight below the 10th percentile for the gestational age." [DDD:hfirth]

data.name: Disproportionate tall stature
data.def: "A tall and slim body build with increased arm span to height ratio (>1.05) and a reduced upper-to-lower segment ratio (<0.85), i.e., unusually long arms and legs. The extremities as well as the hands and feet are unusually slim." [DDD:hfirth, HPO:probinson]

data.name: Large for gestational age
data.def: "The term large for gestational age applies to babies whose birth weight lies above the 90th percentile for that gestational age." [eMedicine:262679, HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Fetal macrosomia has been defined in several different ways, including birth weight of 4000-4500 g (8 lb 13 oz to 9 lb 15 oz) or greater than 90% for gestational age after correcting for neonatal sex and ethnicity. Based on these definitions, macrosomia affects 1-10% of all pregnancies. A diagnosis of fetal macrosomia can be made only by measuring birth weight after delivery; therefore, the condition is confirmed only retrospectively, ie, after delivery of the neonate.

data.name: Death in infancy
data.def: "Death within the first 24 months of life." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Failure to thrive in infancy
data.def: "A mild degree of slow or limited growth after birth, being between two and three standard deviations below age- and sex-related norms." [DDD:hfirth]

data.name: Slender build
data.def: "Asthenic habitus refers to a slender build with long limbs, an angular profile, and prominent muscles or bones." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Slender, long-limbed habitus.

data.name: Protuberant abdomen
data.def: "A thrusting or bulging out of the abdomen." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Ascites
data.def: "Accumulation of fluid in the peritoneal cavity." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Ascites is commonly associated with liver disease that has resulted in portal hypertension and low serum albumin levels.

data.name: Anteriorly placed anus
data.def: "Anterior malposition of the anus." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the rib cage
data.def: "A morphological anomaly of the rib cage." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the umbilicus
data.def: "Abnormality of the umbilicus." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The umbilicus is also known as the belly button or the navel.

data.name: Barrel-shaped chest
data.def: "A rounded, bulging chest that resembles the shape of a barrel. That is, there is an increased anteroposterior diameter and usually some degree of kyphosis." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Barrel chest is often seen in persons with pulmonary emphysema or chronic obstructive pulmonary disease.

data.name: Prenatal movement abnormality
data.def: "An abnormality of fetal movement." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Fetal movements generally become apparent during the second trimester of pregnancy around the 20th week but occasionally up to the 25th week. The initiation of perceptible fetal movements is referred to as 'quickening'.

data.name: Decreased fetal movement
data.def: "An abnormal reduction in quantity or strength of fetal movements." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Abnormality of the amniotic fluid
data.def: "Abnormality of the amniotic fluid, which is the fluid contained in the amniotic sac surrounding the developing fetus." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Polyhydramnios
data.def: "The presence of excess amniotic fluid in the uterus during pregnancy." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Polyhydramnios is diagnosed if the deepest vertical pool of amniotic fluid is more than 8 cm or amniotic fluid index is more than 95th percentile for the corresponding gestational age.

data.name: Oligohydramnios
data.def: "Diminished amniotic fluid volume in pregnancy." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Oligohydramnios is the opposite of polyhydramnios. In normal pregnancy the amniotic fluid volume increases by about 10 ml/day until the 34th, after which it slowly diminishes. A normal amniotic fluid volume at term is about 500-2,000 ml. Oligohydramnios is defined as an AFI (amniotic fluid index) less than 5 cm or smallest vertical pocket of fluid less than 2 cm.

data.name: Fetal polyuria
data.def: "Abnormally increased production of urine by the fetus resulting in polyhydramnios." [HPO:probinson, pmid:21460147]
data.comment: The fetal urine production rate can be measured by ultrasonography.

data.name: Macrodontia
data.def: "Increased size of the teeth, which can be defined as a mesiodistal tooth diameter (width) more than 2 SD above mean for age. Alternatively, an apparently increased maximum width of the tooth." [HPO:ibailleulforestier, pmid:19125428]
data.comment: The standard reference has means and standard deviations by gender [Moyers et al, 1976]. Although it is easy to measure the width of teeth, and the definition is made with reference to the width of teeth, macrodontia actually means that the overall size of the tooth is increased.

data.name: Abnormality of the integument
data.def: "An abnormality of the integument, which consists of the skin and the superficial fascia." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Abnormality of skin, hair, or nails.

data.name: Hypercortisolism
data.def: "Overproduction of the hormone of cortisol by the adrenal cortex, resulting in a characteristic combination of clinical symptoms termed Cushing syndrome, with truncal obesity, a round, full face, striae atrophicae and acne, muscle weakness, and other features." [DDD:spark, HPO:probinson]

data.name: Recurrent skin infections
data.def: "Infections of the skin that happen multiple times." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Redundant skin
data.def: "Loose and sagging skin often associated with loss of skin elasticity." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Rotary nystagmus
data.def: "A form of nystagmus in which the eyeball makes rotary motions around the axis." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Bell-shaped thorax
data.def: "The rib cage has the shape of a wide mouthed bell. That is, the superior portion of the rib cage is constricted, follwed by a convex region, and the inferior portion of the rib cage expands again to have a large diameter." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: A bell-shaped thorax is a non-specific finding. In newborns, bell-spahed thorax can indicate a history of intrauterine neuromuscular abnormalities.

data.name: Selective tooth agenesis
data.def: "Agenesis specifically affecting one of the classes incisor, premolar, or molar." [HPO:ibailleulforestier]

data.name: Abnormality of the hair
data.def: "An abnormality of the hair." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Alopecia
data.def: "Loss of hair from the head or body." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the nail
data.def: "Abnormality of the nail." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Abnormality of the fingernails and/or toenails.

data.name: Concave nail
data.def: "The natural longitudinal (posterodistal) convex arch is not present or is inverted." [pmid:19125433]
data.comment: Koilonychia literally means spoon nails. This often results in a saucer- or spoon-shaped nail and the free edge of the nail is typically everted. The affected digits should be specified. Note that the bundled term koilonychia is an abnormal shape of the fingernail where the nail has raised ridges and is thin and concave.

data.name: Abnormality of the larynx
data.def: "An abnormality of the larynx." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Laryngomalacia
data.def: "Laryngomalacia is a congenital abnormality of the laryngeal cartilage in which the cartilage is floppy and prolapses over the larynx during inspiration." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Laryngomalacia may affect the epiglottis, the arytenoid cartilages, or both. It is the most common cause of congenital stridor.

data.name: Laryngeal stenosis
data.def: "Stricture or narrowing of the larynx that may be associated with symptoms of respiratory difficulty depending on the degree of laryngeal narrowing." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Vocal cord paresis
data.def: "Decreased strength of the vocal folds." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Vocal cord paresis can be characterized by a hoarseness, reduced volume of speech, aspiration and pain in the throat.

data.name: Vocal cord paralysis
data.def: "A loss of the ability to move the vocal folds." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Vocal cord paralysis may lead to signs and symptoms such as hoarseness, inability to speak loudly, choking or coughing while eating with the risk of aspiration pneumonia. Affected patients may also experience breathing difficulties.

data.name: Abnormality of the voice
data.def: "Any abnormality of the voice." [HPO:probinson, MeSH:D014831]
data.comment: This term describes any abnormality of the voice, i.e., of the sounds produced by humans by the passage of air through the larynx and over the vocal cords, and then modified by the resonance organs, the nasopharynx, and the mouth.

data.name: Hoarse voice
data.def: "Hoarseness refers to a change in the pitch or quality of the voice, with the voice sounding weak, very breathy, scratchy, or husky." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Nasal speech
data.def: "A type of speech characterized by the presence of an abnormally increased nasal airflow during speech, associated with incomplete or weak closure of the velum." [HPO:sdoelken]
data.comment: Examination is by nasal endoscopy.

data.name: High pitched voice
data.def: "An abnormal increase in the pitch (frequency) of the voice." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Premature birth
data.def: "The birth of a baby of less than 37 weeks of gestational age." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Hypophonia refers to an abnormally weak voice due to incoordination of the muscles concerned in vocalization.

data.name: Breech presentation
data.def: "A position of the fetus at delivery in which the fetus enters the birth canal with the buttocks or feet first." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the cardiovascular system
data.def: "Any abnormality of the cardiovascular system." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The cardiovascular system consists of the heart, vasculature, and the lymphatic system.

data.name: Abnormality of cardiac morphology
data.def: "An abnormality of the heart." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Ventricular septal defect
data.def: "A hole between the two bottom chambers (ventricles) of the heart. The defect is centered around the most superior aspect of the ventricular septum." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Abnormality of the mitral valve
data.def: "An abnormality of the mitral valve." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Mitral valve prolapse
data.def: "One or both of the leaflets (cusps) of the mitral valve bulges back into the left atrium upon contraction of the left ventricle." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Mitral valve prolapse can be associated with mitral regurgitation.

data.name: Congestive heart failure
data.def: "The presence of an abnormality of cardiac function that is responsible for the failure of the heart to pump blood at a rate that is commensurate with the needs of the tissues or a state in which abnormally elevated filling pressures are required for the heart to do so. Heart failure is frequently related to a defect in myocardial contraction." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Tetralogy of Fallot
data.def: "A congenital cardiac malformation comprising pulmonary stenosis, overriding aorta, ventricular septum defect, and right ventricular hypertrophy. The diagnosis of TOF is made if at least three of the four above mentioned features are present." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Cardiomyopathy
data.def: "A myocardial disorder in which the heart muscle is structurally and functionally abnormal, in the absence of coronary artery disease, hypertension, valvular disease and congenital heart disease sufficient to cause the observed myocardial abnormality." [HPO:probinson, pmid:17916581]

data.name: Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy
