data.name: Malformation of the heart and great vessels
data.def: "Congenital malformation of the heart or great vessels (i.e., the large blood vesslesentering and leaving the heart: aorta, the pulmonary arteries and veins, and the superior and inferior vena cava)." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This category is meant to comprise congenital (developmental) structural heart defects.

data.name: Intestinal malrotation
data.def: "An abnormality of the intestinal rotation and fixation that normally occurs during the development of the gut. This can lead to volvulus, or twisting of the intestine that causes obstruction and necrosis." [HPO:probinson, pmid:12438031]

data.name: Steatorrhea
data.def: "Greater than normal amounts of fat in the feces. This is a result of malabsorption of lipids in the small intestine and results in frothy foul-smelling fecal matter that floats." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Achalasia
data.def: "A disorder of esophageal motility characterized by the inability of the lower esophageal sphincter to relax during swallowing and by inadequate or lacking peristalsis in the lower half of the body of the esophagus." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Achalasia may lead to regurgitation of food, chest pain, cough, and difficulty swallowing.

data.name: Tracheoesophageal fistula
data.def: "An abnormal connection (fistula) between the esophagus and the trachea." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the stomach
data.def: "An abnormality of the stomach." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The stomach the hollow, muscular organ of the gastrointestinal tract between the esophagus and the small intestine.

data.name: Gastrointestinal dysmotility
data.def: "Abnormal intestinal contractions, such as spasms and intestinal paralysis, related to the loss of the ability of the gut to coordinate muscular activity because of endogenous or exogenous causes." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Volvulus
data.def: "Abnormal twisting of a portion of intestine around itself or around a stalk of mesentery tissue." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Volvulus can lead to intestinal obstruction and ischemia.

data.name: Abnormality of the peritoneum
data.def: "An abnormality of the peritoneum." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The peritoneum is the thin tissue that lines the inner wall of the abdomen and covers most of the abdominal organs.

data.name: Peritonitis
data.def: "Inflammation of the peritoneum." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Gastrointestinal atresia
data.def: "An erosion of the mucous membrane of in a portion of the duodenum." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Polyphagia
data.def: "A neurological anomaly with gross overeating associated with an abnormally strong desire or need to eat." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the vasculature
data.def: "An abnormality of the vasculature." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Hepatic necrosis
data.def: "The presence of necrosis affecting the liver." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Telangiectasia affecting stomach, duodenum, small bowel, and/or colon.

data.name: Bowel incontinence
data.def: "Involuntary fecal soiling in adults and children who have usually already been toilet trained." [HPO:sdoelken]

data.name: Congenital hepatic fibrosis
data.def: "The presence of fibrosis of that part of the liver with congenital onset." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Congenital hepatic fibrosis is characterized by enlarged portal tracts with extensive fibrosis and numerous bile ductules that communicate with the bile tree. The affected area tends to be sharply demarcated from normal liver parenchyma and does not display regenerative nodules (which distinguished the condition from cirrhosis).

data.name: Hypotension
data.def: "Low Blood Pressure, vascular hypotension." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Aneurysm
data.def: "Abnormal outpouching or sac-like dilatation in the wall of an atery, vein or the heart." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Varicose veins
data.def: "Enlarged and tortuous veins." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Atherosclerosis
data.def: "A condition characterized by patchy atheromas or atherosclerotic plaques which develop in the walls of medium-sized and large arteries and can lead to arterial stenosis with reduced or blocked blood flow." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Strictly speaking, atherosclerosis is a specific type of arteriosclerosis ('hardening of the arteries'), although the terms are sometimes used interchangeably in clinical jargon.

data.name: Venous abnormality
data.def: "An anomaly of vein." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Deep venous thrombosis
data.def: "Formation of a blot clot in a deep vein. The clot often blocks blood flow, causing swelling and pain. The deep veins of the leg are most often affected." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Fat malabsorption
data.def: "Abnormality of the absorption of fat from the gastrointestinal tract." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Vasculitis
data.def: "Inflammation of blood vessel." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Arteriosclerosis
data.def: "Sclerosis (hardening) of the arteries with increased thickness of the wall of arteries as well as increased stiffness and a loss of elasticity." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Although arteriosclerosis and atherosclerosis are often used as if they were synonyms, they are not. Atherosclerosis is the most common type of arteriosclerosis, and is caused by plaque building up in the vessel, which in turn causes sclerosis, increased stiffness, and loss of elasticity of the affected arteries.

data.name: Hypertension associated with pheochromocytoma
data.def: "A type of hypertension associated with pheochromocytoma." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of pelvic girdle bone morphology
data.def: "An abnormality of the bony pelvic girdle, which is a ring of bones connecting the vertebral column to the femurs." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Aortic dissection
data.def: "Aortic dissection refers to a tear in the intimal layer of the aorta causing a separation between the intima and the medial layers of the aorta." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Scoliosis
data.def: "The presence of an abnormal lateral curvature of the spine." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Skeletal dysplasia
data.def: "A general term describing features characterized by abnormal development of bones and connective tissues." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The word skeletal dysplasia is most often used to describe a group of over 380 inherited conditions that involve abnormal development of bones and connective tissues. However, the word can also be used to describe the presence of a congenital defects of bones or connective tissues that are found in one or more of the diseases, especially on prenatal ultrasound, i.e., a situation in which it is often not yet possible to make an exact etiological diagnosis. This is the sense of the phrase we use in the HPO. It is, however, preferable to annotate the observed abnormalities.

data.name: Bone pain
data.def: "An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to bone." []

data.name: Spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia
data.def: "A disorder of bone growth affecting the vertebrae and the ends of the long bones (epiphyses)." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Increased susceptibility to fractures
data.def: "An abnormally increased tendency to fractures of bones caused by an abnormal reduction in bone strength that is generally associated with an increased risk of fracture." [HPO:sdoelken]
data.comment: This is a bundled term that will be made obsolete.

data.name: Neoplasm
data.def: "An organ or organ-system abnormality that consists of uncontrolled autonomous cell-proliferation which can occur in any part of the body as a benign or malignant neoplasm (tumour)." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The World Health Organization (WHO) classifies neoplasms into four main groups: (i) benign neoplasm, (ii) in situ neoplasm, (iii) malignant neoplasm, and (iv) neoplasm of uncertain or unknown behavior. A malignant neoplasm is also known as cancer.

data.name: Osteosarcoma
data.def: "A malignant bone tumor that usually develops during adolescence and usually affects the long bones including the tibia, femur, and humerus. The typical symptoms of osteosarcoma comprise bone pain, fracture, limitation of motion, and tenderness or swelling at the site of the tumor." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Basal cell carcinoma
data.def: "The presence of a basal cell carcinoma of the skin." [HPO:sdoelken]
data.comment: A basal cell carcinoma is the most common type of skin cancer which rarely metastasizes, but is still considered malignant because it can cause significant destruction and disfigurement by invading surrounding tissues. In 80 percent of all cases, basal cell cancers are found on the head and neck or on other sun-exposed areas of the body. Apart from sporadic basal cell carcinoma, there are hereditary conditions such as the basal cell nevus syndrome where patients develop multiple basal cell carcinomas throughout life.

data.name: Coxa valga
data.def: "Coxa valga is a deformity of the hip in which the angle between the femoral shaft and the femoral neck is increased compared to age-adjusted values (about 150 degrees in newborns gradually reducing to 120-130 degrees in adults)." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Downturned corners of mouth
data.def: "A morphological abnormality of the mouth in which the angle of the mouth is downturned. The oral commissures are positioned inferior to the midline labial fissure." [HPO:probinson, pmid:19125428]
data.comment: This finding should be assessed with the mouth closed, the lips in relaxed contact, and the face relaxed. The finding may be difficult to assess if the lower lip is enlarged. Previous terms for downturned corners of mouth included Carp mouth andFish mouth which are no longer recommended (pejorative terms).

data.name: Abnormality of the immune system
data.def: "An abnormality of the immune system." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The immune system is composed of organs and interdependent cell types that collectively protect the body from infections and from the growth of tumor cells. The organs of the immune system comprise the bone marrow, the spleen, the thymus,the lymph nodes, and the cell types comprise B cells, T cells, natural killer cells, granulocytes,dendritic cells, and macrophages.

data.name: Lymphadenopathy
data.def: "Enlargment (swelling) of a lymph node." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Adrenal overactivity
data.comment: Cortisol is the main member of the glucocorticoid family in humans and together with aldosterone is one of the main secretions of the adrenal cortex.

data.name: Recurrent bacterial infections
data.def: "Increased susceptibility to bacterial infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of bacterial infection." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Recurrent infections
data.def: "Increased susceptibility to microbial infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of infection." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Recurrent abscess formation
data.def: "An increased susceptibility to abscess formation, as manifested by a medical history of recurrent abscesses." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Systemic lupus erythematosus
data.def: "A chronic, relapsing, inflammatory, and often febrile multisystemic disorder of connective tissue, characterized principally by involvement of the skin, joints, kidneys, and serosal membranes." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This is a bundled term that describes a disease rather than a phenotypic feature, but is left for convenience for annotations of lupus conceived of as a feature of another disease.

data.name: Recurrent Staphylococcus aureus infections
data.def: "Increased susceptibility to Staphylococcus aureus infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of Staphylococcus aureus infection." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the lymph nodes
data.def: "A lymph node abnormality." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Apoptosis is a form of programmed cell death.

data.name: Oral leukoplakia
data.def: "A white patch on the oral mucosa that cannot be rubbed off." [HPO:probinson, pmid:17944749]
data.comment: The definition of oral leukoplakia states that the lesion be characterized clinically or histologically as any other condition, and is not associated with any physical or chemical causative agent except tobacco.

data.name: Osteomalacia
data.def: "Osteomalacia is a general term for bone weakness owing to a defect in mineralization of the protein framework known as osteoid. This defective mineralization is mainly caused by lack in vitamin D. Osteomalacia in children is known as rickets." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Delayed skeletal maturation
data.def: "A decreased rate of skeletal maturation. Delayed skeletal maturation can be diagnosed on the basis of an estimation of the bone age from radiographs of specific bones in the human body." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Kyphoscoliosis
data.def: "An abnormal curvature of the spine in both a coronal (lateral) and sagittal (back-to-front) plane." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Thin bony cortex
data.def: "Abnormal thinning of the cortical region of bones." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Osteomyelitis
data.def: "An infection of bone." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Osteomyelitis can be acute or chronic and can be caused by a variety of microbial agents.

data.name: Pathologic fracture
data.def: "A pathologic fracture occurs when a bone breaks in an area that is weakened secondary to another disease process such as tumor, infection, and certain inherited bone disorders. A pathologic fracture can occur without a degree of trauma required to cause fracture in healthy bone." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Recurrent fractures
data.def: "The repeated occurence of bone fractures (implying an abnormally increased tendency for fracture)." [HPO:curators]
data.comment: This term will be made obsolete. The annotations need to be checked.

data.name: Generalized joint laxity
data.def: "Joint hypermobility (ability of a joint to move beyond its normal range of motion) affecting many or all joints of the body." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Abnormal cartilage morphology
data.def: "Any abnormality of cartilage." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Tracheal stenosis

data.name: Abnormality of the trachea

data.name: Tachypnea
data.def: "Very rapid breathing." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: In adults, a beathing rate of between 12-20 breaths per minute is normal and tachypnea is present with a ventilatory rate greater than 20 breaths per minute.

data.name: Hypoventilation
data.def: "A reduction in the amount of air transported into the pulmonary alveoli by breathing, leading to hypercapnia (increase in the partial pressure of carbon dioxide)." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormal pattern of respiration

data.name: Functional respiratory abnormality
data.comment: This category describes not-primarily structural lesions.

data.name: Osteolysis
data.def: "Osteolysis refers to the destruction of bone through bone resorption with removal or loss of calcium." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Osteolysis may be a feature of neoplastic, infectious, metabolis, vascular, and joint disorders and is also a component of many hereditary diseases. Osteolysis may be highly localized or more diffuse. This term is meant to group the more specific osteolysis terms.

data.name: Kyphosis

data.name: Coxa vara
data.def: "Coxa vara includes all forms of decrease of the femoral neck shaft angle (the angle between the neck and the shaft of the femur) to less than 120 degrees." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The Latin word 'coxa' refers to the hip, and varus is a term for the inward angulation of the distal segment of a bone or joint. The normal range of the angle between the ball and the shaft of the femur is 120 to 135 degrees. Coxa vara can be congenital, developmental, or acquired.

data.name: Abnormality of the upper limb

data.name: Arthralgia

data.name: Urinary bladder sphincter dysfunction

data.name: Recurrent fungal infections

data.name: Meningioma

data.name: Squamous cell carcinoma

data.name: Melanoma

data.comment: A malignant skin tumor of originating from melanocytes, pigment cells normally present in the epidermis and sometimes in the dermis.

data.name: Hypoplastic iliac wing
data.def: "Underdevelopment of the ilium ala." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the ilium
data.def: "An abnormality of the ilium, the largest and uppermost bone of the pelvis." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Narrow iliac wings
data.def: "Decreased width of the wing (or ala) of the ilium (which is the large expanded portion which bounds the greater pelvis laterally)." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Flared iliac wings
data.def: "Widening of the ilium ala, that is of the wing of the ilium, combined with external rotation, leading to a flared appearance of the iliac wing." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Central apnea

data.name: Nocturnal hypoventilation

data.name: Respiratory difficulties

data.name: Hyperventilation
data.def: "Hyperventilation refers to an increased pulmonary ventilation rate that is faster than necessary for the exchange of gases. Hyperventilation can result from increased frequency of breathing, an increased tidal volume, or both, and leads to an excess intake of oxygen and the blowing off of carbon dioxide." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Medulloblastoma
data.def: "A rapidly growing embryonic tumor arising in the posterior part of the cerebellar vermis and neuroepithelial roof of the fourth ventricle in children. More rarely, medulloblastoma arises in the cerebellum in adults." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Medulloblastoma is a highly malignant primary brain tumor that originates in the cerebellum or posterior fossa and belonging to the family of cranial primitive neuroectodermal tumors.

data.name: Embryonal neoplasm

data.def: "An abnormally decreased potassium concentration in the blood." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Hypocalcemia

data.name: Hyponatremia

data.name: Hyperbilirubinemia

data.name: Elevated hepatic transaminases
data.def: "Elevations of the levels of SGOT and SGPT in the serum. SGOT (serum glutamic oxaloacetic transaminase) and SGPT (serum glutamic pyruvic transaminase) are transaminases primarily found in the liver and heart and are released into the bloodstream as the result of liver or heart damage. SGOT and SGPT are used clinically mainly as markers of liver damage." [HPO:probinson]

data.comment: The cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is secreted by the choroid plexus, and flows uninterrupted throughout the central nervous system (the central cerebrospinal canal of the spinal cord and through the four interconnected cerebral ventricles in the brain).

data.name: Increased CSF protein

data.name: Abnormality of thyroid physiology

data.name: Hemivertebrae
data.def: "Absence of one half of the vertebral body." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Lateral hemivertebrae represent a developmental defect resulting from the failure of the contralateral chondral center to develop. Dorsal hemivertebrae result from a developmental defect in which the anterior chondral centers fail to develop, and ventral hemivertebrae result from failure of the posterior centers to ossify. The affected half of the vertebral body may by hypoplastic or absent, as is the pedicle, and (for thoracic vetebrae) the corresponding rib. The affected half of the vertebral body may also show a fusion or segmentation defect.

data.name: Lumbar hyperlordosis
data.def: "An abnormal accentuation of the inward curvature of the spine in the lumbar region." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Vertebral compression fractures
data.def: "Congenital absence of a part of the vermis of cerebellum." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Autoimmunity
data.def: "The occurrence of an immune reaction against the organism's own cells or tissues." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The generation of the antibody repertoire requires two successive steps. The first is antigen- and T-cell-independent; it takes place in the fetal liver and the bone marrow. Immature B lymphocytes rearrange their immunoglobulin-gene variable segments (V segments), diversity segments (D segments) and joining segments (J segments), producing a functionally integrated VDJ segment linked to the mu constant region (C-mu), which determines the primary antibody repertoire composed of IgM antibodies. The second step is antigen- and T-cell-dependent and takes place in secondary lymphoid organs. After encountering antigen, B cells proliferate and form germinal centers. In this unique anatomic formation, two genetic events lead to generation of the secondary antibody repertoire: class-switch recombination (CSR) and somatic hypermutation (SHM). CSR of immunoglobulins occurs by a recombination process between two different switch regions (S regions) located upstream of each C region. Replacement of C-mu by a constant region of another class of immunoglobulin (C-gamma, C-alpha or C-epsilon) ensues and leads to the production of IgG, IgA or IgE.

data.name: Abnormality of the forearm
data.def: "An abnormality of the lower arm." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia involving the central nervous system

data.name: Prolonged bleeding time
data.def: "Prolongation of the time taken for a standardized skin cut of fixed depth and length to stop bleeding." [DDD:mumford]
data.comment: The bleeding time test measures the time taken for blood vessel constriction and platelet plug formation to occur. No clot is allowed to form, so that the arrest of bleeding depends exclusively on blood vessel constriction and platelet action. To perform the test, pressure is maintained throughout the test by inflating a sphygmomanometer cuff on the upper arm. The dorsal surface of the forearm is then cleaned, and the bleeding time device placed onto the skin  and the trigger is depressed. At 30-second intervals, the flow of blood is blotted with filter paper. The time from puncture to cessation of bleeding is then recorded as the bleeding time. Normal values depend on the device used and other parameters, but are around 2 to 9 minutes.

data.name: Abnormality of the musculature
data.def: "Abnormality originating in one or more muscles, i.e., of the set of muscles of body." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the humerus
data.def: "An abnormality of the humerus (i.e., upper arm bone)." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Hypercalcemia
data.def: "An abnormally increased calcium concentration in the blood." [HPO:curators]

data.def: "Reduction in the concentration of albumin in the blood." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Hyperlipidemia
data.def: "An elevated lipid concentration in the blood." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Hyperlipidemia is an elevation of the blood levels of lipids including primarily cholesterol, phospholipids and triglycerides and cholesterol esters. The lipids are transported on lipoproteins some of which are commonly used for clinical measurements, including chylomicrons, very-low density lipoproteins (VLDL), intermediate-density lipoproteins (IDL), low-density lipoproteins, and high-density lipoproteins (HDL).

data.name: Abnormal cortical bone morphology
data.def: "An abnormality of compact bone (also known as cortical bone), which forms the dense surface of bones." [HPO:sdoelken]
data.comment: Anatomically, the carrying angle in human adults is approximately 10 degrees in men and 13 degrees in women. Increasing the carrying angle may lead to elbow instability and pain during exercise or in throwing activities of sports, may reduce function of elbow flexion, predispose to risk of elbow dislocation, and increase evidence of elbow fracture when falling on the outstretched hand and fracture of the distal humeral epiphysis.

data.name: Abnormal EKG
data.comment: Consider abnormality of the cardiovascular system, HP:0001626.

data.name: Abnormality of circulating hormone level
data.def: "An abnormal concentration of a hormone in the blood." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Note that while structural heart anomalies can cause abnormal echocardiograpy findings, structural abnormalities are detectable by multiple imaging modalities and should be coded using terms from the hierarchy under 'Abnormality of cardiac morphology' (HP:0001627).

data.name: Abnormality of lipid metabolism
data.def: "An abnormality in the of lipid metabolism." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: According to CHEBI:18059 'Lipids' is a loosely defined term for substances of biological origin that are soluble in nonpolar solvents. They consist of saponifiable lipids, such as glycerides (fats and oils) and phospholipids, as well as nonsaponifiable lipids, principally steroids.

data.name: Hypercholesterolemia
data.def: "An increased concentration of cholesterol in the blood." [HPO:gcarletti]

data.name: Lactic acidosis
data.def: "An abnormal buildup of lactic acid in the body, leading to acidification of the blood and other bodily fluids." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Note that the term acidemia is used to describe the state of low pH in the blood, whereas acidosis is used to describe the processes that lead to acidemia. In medical jargon, however, the two terms are used interchangeably.

data.name: Abnormal peripheral myelination
data.def: "An abnormality of the myelination of motor and sensory peripheral nerves. These are axons for motor nerves and dendrites for sensory nerves in the strict anatomic sense." [DDD:fmunitoni, HPO:jbaets]
data.comment: This finding may be observed upon biopsy of the sural nerve. Myelination, i.e., the presence of a segmented lipid-rich sheath (myelin), enables faster and more energetically efficient conduction of electrical impulses. The sheath is formed by the cell membranes of Schwann cells in the peripheral nervous system (GO:0022011).

data.name: Abnormality of the spinocerebellar tracts
data.def: "An abnormality of the spinocerebellar tracts, a set of axonal fibers originating in the spinal cord and terminating in the ipsilateral cerebellum. The spinocerebellar tract convey information to the cerebellum about limb and joint position (proprioception). They comprise the ventral spinocerebellar tract (FMA:72642), the anterior spinocerebellar tract (FMA:72642), and the posterior spinocerebellar tract (FMA:72641)." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Cystine is a sulfur-containing amino acid.

data.name: Abnormality of peripheral nerve conduction
data.def: "An abnormality of the conduction of electrical impulses by peripheral (motor or sensory) nerves. This finding is elicited by a nerve conduction study (NCS)." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: A  nerve conduction study (NCS) is commonly conducted together with electromyography in order to evaluate muscle disorders. For the NCS, dermal electrodes are placed at intervals over the nerve to be examined, and a low-intensity current is introducted to generate action potentials. The velocity of the action potential is related to the diameter of the nerve fiber and the presence of a myelin sheath. Diseases of the myelin sheath characteristically reduce the nerve conduction velocity (NCV). The amplitude of the response is also measured.

data.comment: Cystathionine can be directly interconverted to cysteine. Normal cystathione urinary values are under 150 micromole per gram creatinine.

data.name: Abnormal isoelectric focusing of serum transferrin
data.def: "Glycosylated transferrin concentrations can be measured in serum as a marker of N-linked glycosylation fidelity. In the traditional nomenclature for congenital disorders of glycosylation, absence of entire glycans was designated type I, and loss of one or more monosaccharides as type II. These terms are retained for historical reasons but for new annotations the precise glycosylation defect should be recorded." [HPO:probinson, pmid:22516080]
data.comment: Human serum transferrin has two N-glycosylation sites, which are normally both fully occupied by disialylated biantennary glycans to generate tetrasialotransferrin.

data.name: Fasting hypoglycemia
data.def: "Increased concentration of pyruvic acid in the urine." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Elevated circulating parathyroid hormone (PTH) level

data.comment: Delta-aminolevulinic acid synthesis is a rate-controlling step in heme synthesis.

data.name: Abnormality of the pubic bone

data.name: Abnormality of the ischium

data.name: Breast hypoplasia

data.name: Long nose

data.name: Short nose

data.comment: Note: a small nose has both decreased height and a decreased width. These should be coded separately.

data.name: Myopathy
data.def: "A disorder of muscle unrelated to impairment of innervation or neuromuscular junction." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The diagnosis of myopathy is often confirmed on the basis of myopathic changes in muscle biopsy.

data.name: Ragged-red muscle fibers
data.def: "An abnormal appearance of muscle fibers observed on muscle biopsy. Ragged red fibers can be visualized with Gomori trichrome staining as irregular and intensely red subsarcolemmal zones, whereas the normal myofibrils are green. The margins of affect fibers appear red and ragged. The ragged-red  is due to the accumulation of abnormal mitochondria below the plasma membrane of the muscle fiber, leading to the appearance of a red rim and speckled sarcoplasm." [HPO:probinson, pmid:12075011, pmid:16537564]
data.comment:

data.name: Rhabdomyolysis
data.def: "Breakdown of muscle fibers that leads to the release of muscle fiber contents (myoglobin) into the bloodstream." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Skeletal muscle atrophy
data.def: "The presence of skeletal muscular atrophy (which is also known as amyotrophy)." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Intracellular accumulation of autofluorescent lipopigment storage material
data.def: "The intracellular accumulation of autofluorescent storage material." [HPO:probinson, pmid:16455164]
data.comment: Accumulation of intracellular autofluorescent material or aging pigment has been characterized as a normal aging event. Lipofuscin (from the Greek word for fat and the Latin word for dark), refers to intracellular autofluorescent material that accumulates in aging cells with a excitation wavelength between 320 and 480 nm and an emission wavelength between 460 and 630 nm. Lpofuscin consists of a mixture of oxidized proteins and lipids, carbohydrates and trace amount of metals. Ceroid iss a lipofuscin-like lipopigment that arises from pathological conditions such as disease, malnutrition, and cell stress. Subunit c of mitochondrial ATP synthase makes up approximately 40% of this lipopigment/ceroid accumulation.

data.name: Curvilinear intracellular accumulation of autofluorescent lipopigment storage material
data.def: "An intracellular accumulation of autofluorescent lipopigment storage material in a curved pattern." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Generalized amyloid deposition
data.def: "A diffuse form of amyloidosis." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: According to MeSH (D000682), Amyloid is fibrous protein complex that consists of proteins folded into a specific cross beta-pleated sheet structure. This fibrillar structure has been found as an alternative folding pattern for a variety of functional proteins. Deposits of amyloid in the form of amyloid plaques are associated with a variety of degenerative diseases. The amyloid structure has also been found in a number of functional proteins that are unrelated to disease.

data.name: Abnormality of chromosome stability

data.name: Chromosomal breakage induced by crosslinking agents

data.comment: Increased tendency to chromosomal breakage induced by crosslinking agents is typical for the various forms of Fanconi anemia.

data.name: Hypermethioninemia

data.comment: Elevated blood methionine levels in the range of 500-2000 micromolar.

data.name: Elevated serum creatine phosphokinase
data.def: "An elevation of the level of the enzyme creatine kinase (also known as creatine phosphokinase, CPK; EC 2.7.3.2) in the blood. CPK levels can be elevated in a number of clinical disorders such as myocardial infarction, rhabdomyolysis, and muscular dystrophy." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: 'has part' some \n('increased amount' and ('inheres in' some \n(IMR_0002602 and ('part of' some blood))) and ('has modifier' some abnormal))

data.name: External genital hypoplasia
data.def: "Underdevelopment of part or all of the external reproductive organs." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Partial or complete failure of the genitalia to develop, often as a consequence of hypogonadism.

data.name: Male infertility
data.def: "Aplasia of the vagina." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of DNA repair
data.def: "An abnormality of the process of DNA repair, that is, of the process of restoring DNA after damage." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the coagulation cascade
data.def: "An abnormality of the coagulation cascade, which is comprised of the contact activation pathway (also known as the intrinsic pathway) and the tissue factor pathway (also known as the extrinsic pathway) as well as cofactors and regulators." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Elevated serum creatinine
data.def: "An increased amount of creatinine in the blood." [HPO:gcarletti]

data.name: Abdominal distention
data.def: "Distention of the abdomen." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Abdominal distention can be a secondary feature associated with a number of conditions such as bowel obstruction.

data.name: Visceromegaly
data.def: "Abnormal increased size of the viscera of the abdomen." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Visceromegaly is enlargement of the internal organs in the abdomen, including liver, spleen, stomach, kidneys, or pancreas.

data.name: Abnormality of the hip bone
data.def: "An abnormality of the hip bone." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The hip region (as defined by the FMA) comprises the vasculature of hip, skin of hip, superficial fascia of hip, the hip bone, hip joint, and musculature of hip. The hip is part of the pelvic girdle.

data.name: Increased serum ferritin
data.def: "Abnormal raised concentration of ferritin, a ubiquitous intracellular protein that stores iron, in the blood." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Ferritin levels measured in serum usually have a direct correlation with the total amount of iron stored in the body, but ferritin levels may also be increased with anemia of chronic disease or in the course of an acute phase reaction.

data.name: Abnormality of mitochondrial metabolism
data.def: "A functional anomaly of mitochondria." [ORCID:0000-0001-5208-3432]
data.comment: Cystathionine can be directly interconverted to cysteine. Cystathionine is not normally detectable in plasma.

data.name: Ovoid vertebral bodies
data.def: "When viewed in lateral radiographs, vertebral bodies have a roughly rectangular configuration. This term applies if the vertebral body appears rounded or oval." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Irregular vertebral endplates
data.def: "An irregular surface of the vertebral end plates, which are normally relatively smooth." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Spondylolisthesis
data.def: "Complete bilateral fractures of the pars interarticularis resulting in the anterior slippage of the vertebra." [HPO:probinson, pmid:20411054]

data.name: Spondylolysis
data.def: "Spondylolysis is an osseous defect of the pars interarticularis, thought to be a developmental or acquired stress fracture secondary to chronic low-grade trauma." [HPO:probinson, pmid:20440613]
data.comment: The pars interarticularis is one of the bony bridges that connect the upper with the lower facet joints of the vertebra. Lumbar spondylolysis is a common cause of lower back pain. The vast majority of cases of spondylolysis occur at the L5 or L4 levels, and is usually diagnosed radiographically. Over half of patients affected by spondylolysis have associated spondylolisthesis.

data.name: Spinal rigidity
data.def: "Reduced ability to move the vertebral column with a resulting limitation of neck and trunk flexion." [HPO:probinson, pmid:11601420, pmid:2246660]

data.name: Hyperlordosis
data.def: "Abnormally increased cuvature (anterior concavity) of the lumbar or cervical spine." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Cervical subluxation
data.def: "A partial dislocation of one or more intervertebral joints in the cervical vertebral column." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the odontoid process
data.def: "Abnormality of the dens of the axis, which is also known as the odontoid process." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The dens of the axis is a protuberance of the C2 vetebral body around which the first vertebra rotates.

data.name: Hypoplasia of the odontoid process
data.def: "Developmental hypoplasia of the dens of the axis." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormal form of the vertebral bodies
data.def: "Abnormal morphology of vertebral body." []

data.name: Abnormality of the cervical spine
data.def: "Any abnormality of the cervical vertebral column." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Progressive muscle weakness
data.def: "A partial dislocation of the atlantoaxial joints." [HPO:curators]
data.comment: A subluxation affecting the intervertebral joint between the first and second cervical vertebrae.

data.name: Generalized muscle weakness
data.def: "Generalized weakness or decreased strength of the muscles, affecting both distal and proximal musculature." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Myalgia
data.def: "A tendency to experience muscle pain." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Axial muscle weakness
data.def: "Reduced strength of the axial musculature (i.e., of the muscles of the head and neck, spine, and ribs)." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Abnormal bone structure
data.def: "Any anomaly in the composite material or the layered arrangement of the bony skeleton." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormal enchondral ossification
data.def: "An abnormality of the process of endochondral ossification, which is a type of replacement ossification in which bone tissue replaces cartilage." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This term is intended to describe histological abnormalities of enchondral ossification observed upon bone biopsy.

data.name: Junctional split
data.def: "The formation of bullae (blisters) with cleavage in the lamina lucida layer of the skin." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Consider integument abnormality, HP:0001574.

data.name: Decreased circulating renin level
data.def: "An decreased level of renin (PRO:000013883) in the blood." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the femoral neck or head region
data.def: "Joint pain affecting the hip." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the femoral neck
data.def: "An abnormality of the femoral neck (which is the process of bone, connecting the femoral head with the femoral shaft)." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the femoral head
data.def: "An abnormality of the femoral head." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Narrow greater sacrosciatic notches
data.def: "A narrowing of the sacrosciatic notch, i.e., the deep indentation in the posterior border of the hip bone at the point of union of the ilium and ischium." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Steppage gait
data.def: "An abnormal gait pattern that arises from weakness of the pretibial and peroneal muscles due to a lower motor neuron lesion. Affected patients have footdrop and are unable to dorsiflex and evert the foot. The leg is lifted high on walking so that the toes clear the ground, and there may be a slapping noise when the foot strikes the ground again." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Axonal degeneration/regeneration
data.def: "A pattern of simultaneous degeneration and regeneration of axons (see comment)." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This finding is typically demonstrated by nerve biopsy. Following focal damage to an axon, the part of the axon that is distal to the lesion invariably degenerates, a process that is known as anterograde (or Wallerian) degeneration. During Wallerian degeneration, often a microenvironment is created that can allow successful regrowth of nerve fibres from the proximal nerve segment.

data.name: Decreased number of peripheral myelinated nerve fibers
data.def: "A loss of myelinated nerve fibers in the peripheral nervous system (in general, this finding can be observed on nerve biopsy)." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This finding can be demonstrated by nerve biopsy.

data.name: Onion bulb formation
data.def: "Repeated episodes of segmental demyelination and remyelination lead to the accumulation of supernumerary Schwann cells around axons, which is referred to as onion bulb formation. This finding affects peripheral nerves." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This feature is characteristic of chronic demyelinating neuropathies as well as certain hereditary neuropathies. Onion-bulb formation may be observed in electron microscopic examinations of peripheral nerve biopsy material. Often, this examination is performed on the sural nerve.

data.name: Decreased number of large peripheral myelinated nerve fibers
data.def: "A reduced number of large myelinated nerve fibers." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This finding can be demonstrated by nerve biopsy.

data.name: Sensory axonal neuropathy
data.def: "An axonal neuropathy of peripheral sensory nerves." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Gowers sign
data.def: "A phenomenon whereby patients are not able to stand up without the use of the hands owing to weakness of the proximal muscles of the lower limbs." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Muscle cramps
data.def: "Sudden and involuntary contractions of one or more muscles." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Syringomyelia
data.def: "Dilated, glial-lined cavity in spinal cord. This cavity does not communicate with the central canal, and usually is between the dorsal columns unilaterally or bilaterally along the side of the cord." [HPO:sdoelken]

data.name: Abnormal synaptic transmission at the neuromuscular junction
data.def: "Any abnormality of the neuromuscular junction, which is the synapse between the motor end plate of a motor neuron and the skeletal muscle fibers." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Paresthesia
data.def: "Abnormal sensations such as tingling, pricking, or numbness of the skin with no apparent physical cause." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: EMG: decremental response of compound muscle action potential to repetitive nerve stimulation
data.def: "A compound muscle action potential (CMAP) is a type of electromyography (EMG). CMAP refers to a group of almost simultaneous action potentials from several muscle fibers in the same area evoked by stimulation of the supplying motor nerve and are recorded as one multipeaked summated action potential. This abnormality refers to a greater than normal decrease in the amplitude during the course of the investigation." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The result of this test is abnormal if progressively fewer muscle fibers respond to nerve stimulation during a train of stimuli, thereby yielding a decrementing pattern in the CMAP.

data.name: Distal sensory impairment of all modalities
Atlantoaxial abnormality
data.def: "An anomaly of the atlantoaxial joint, i.e., of the joint between the first (atlas) and second (axis) cervical vertebrae." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Spinal canal stenosis
data.def: "An abnormal narrowing of the spinal canal." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Stenosis of the spinal canal can result in neurological symptoms because of compression of the spinal cord or spinal nerve roots, depending on the location of the stenosis in the vertebral column.

data.name: Coronal cleft vertebrae
data.def: "Frontal schisis (cleft or cleavage) of vertebral bodies." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Coronal cleft vertebrae result when there are two, instead of one, primary ossification centers in a vertebral body. An unossified cartilaginous brdige may be observed radiographically with the shape of a cleft. If the two ossification centers are ventral/dorsal, a coronal cleft is observed, and if the two ossification centers are left/right, than a sagittal cleft is observed.

data.name: Back pain
data.def: "An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the back." []

data.name: Vertebral segmentation defect
data.def: "An abnormality related to a defect of vertebral separation during development." [HPO:probinson, pmid:23653580, pmid:23801490]
data.comment: The vertebral column derives from somites, transient paired segments of mesoderm that surround the neural tube in the early embryo. The formation of the vertebrar involves many processes including resegmentation of the rostral and caudal regions of adjacent somites that then fuse to form vetebral elements. Disruption of these processes can a cause of severe segmentation defects of the vetebrae. The frequency of segmentation defects of the vetebra has been estimated at 0.5 of 1000 births. The range of segmentation defects includes left-right uneven formation of somites that results in hemivertebrae or wedge vertebrae. Incomplete segmentation can result in fused segments such as block vertebrae. A failure of the process of resegmentation and migration of the sclerotomal compartment can result in a failure of midline fusion, such as butterlfy vertebrae.

data.name: CNS hypomyelination
data.def: "Reduced amount of myelin in the central nervous system resulting from defective myelinogenesis." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Decreased motor nerve conduction velocity
data.def: "A type of decreased nerve conduction velocity that affects the motor neuron." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Newborn infants have values that are approximately half that of adults, and adult values are normally reached by age 3 or 4. Motor nerve conduction is evaluated by recording the compound muscle action potential (CMAP) associated with a mechanical contraction of a given muscle in response to electrical stimulation of the motor nerve fibers supplying that muscle.  The CMAP is the sum of all the action potentials occurring individually in the contracting muscle fibers.

data.name: Prolonged miniature endplate currents
data.def: "An abnormal prolongation of the miniature endplate potentials, i.e. the postsynaptic response to transmitter released from an individual vesicle at the neuromuscular junction." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Decreased size of nerve terminals
data.def: "A reduction in the size of nerve terminals." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Nerve terminals are the output region of nerves located presynaptically and (in the case of chemical synapses) containing vesicles of chemical neurotransmitters. Presynaptic nerve terminals normally are larger in diameter than the axon and have the appearance of a bud. This feature can be demonstrated by muscle biopsy.

data.name: EMG: chronic denervation signs
data.def: "Evidence of chronic denervation on electromyography." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This is a bundled term that is kept for convenience. It is preferable to annotate the precise clinical abnormalities observed.

data.name: EMG: neuropathic changes
data.def: "The presence of characteristic findings of denervation on electromyography (fibrillations, positive sharp waves, and giant motor unit potentials)." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This is a bundled term. It is preferable to annotate the precise clinical observations, but the term is kept now for convenience.

data.name: Axonal loss
data.def: "A reduction in the number of axons in the peripheral nervous system." [DDD:probinson]
data.comment: This finding can be observed upon nerve biopsy.

data.name: Decreased sensory nerve conduction velocity
data.def: "Reduced speed of conduction of the action potential along a sensory nerve." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The sensory nerve action potential (SNAP) in response to electrical stimulation is recorded from the nerve itself by means of dermal recording electrodes. The SNAP is the sum of all the action potentials generated in sensory nerve fibres by the applied electrical impulse.

data.name: Axonal regeneration
data.def: "The presence of axonal regeneration following a previous axonal lesion." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This finding is typically demonstrated by nerve biopsy. See the comment of term HP:0003378 for further information.

data.name: Elevated long chain fatty acids
data.def: "Increased concentration of long-chain fatty acid." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This feature can be measured in plasma, as well as in cultured fibroblasts of amniocytes.

data.name: EMG abnormality
data.def: "Abnormal results of investigations using electromyography (EMG)." [HPO:probinson, pmid:18751841]

data.name: EMG: myopathic abnormalities
data.def: "The presence of abnormal electromyographic patterns indicative of myopathy, such as small-short polyphasic motor unit potentials." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Abnormality of the vertebrae
data.def: "An abnormality of one or more of the vertebrae." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: A vertebra is one of 33 bony segments that form the spinal column of humans. There are 7 cervical, 12 thoracic, 5 lumbar, 5 sacral and 4 coccygeal vertebrae (the coccygeal vertebrae are fused into one coccyx bone).

data.name: Paralysis
data.def: "Paralysis of voluntary muscles means loss of contraction due to interruption of one or more motor pathways from the brain to the muscle fibers. Although the word paralysis is often used interchangeably to mean either complete or partial loss of muscle strength, it is preferable to use paralysis or plegia for complete or severe loss of muscle strength, and paresis for partial or slight loss. Motor paralysis results from deficits of the upper motor neurons (corticospinal, corticobulbar, or subcorticospinal). Motor paralysis is often accompanied by an impairment in the facility of movement." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Sensory impairment
data.def: "An abnormality of the primary sensation that is mediated by peripheral nerves (pain, temperature, touch, vibration, joint position). The word hypoesthesia (or hyesthesia) refers to a reduction in cutaneous sensation to a specific type of testing." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This term does not include abnormalities of cortical sensation such as two-point discrimination, stereognosis, and graphesthesia.

data.name: Peripheral axonal neuropathy
data.def: "An abnormality characterized by disruption of  the normal functioning of peripheral axons." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This abnormality can be assay by electromyography (EMG) or by nerve biopsy.

data.name: Segmental peripheral demyelination/remyelination
data.def: "A segmental pattern of demyelination and regeneration (remyelination) affecting peripheral nerves." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Babinski sign
data.def: "Upturning of the big toe (and sometimes fanning of the other toes) in response to stimulation of the sole of the foot. If the Babinski sign is present it can indicate damage to the corticospinal tract." [HPO:curators]
data.comment: A positive Babinski sign can indicate damage to the corticospinal tract.

data.name: Antinuclear antibody positivity
data.def: "The presence of autoantibodies in the serum that react against nuclei or nuclear components." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Antinuclear antibodies (ANAs) are found in patients with a number of different autoimmune diseases, such as systemic lupus erythematosus, Sjogren's syndrome, rheumatoid arthritis, polymyositis, scleroderma, Hashimoto's thyroiditis, juvenile diabetes mellitus, Addison disease, vitiligo, pernicious anemia, glomerulonephritis, and pulmonary fibrosis. ANAs can display various staining patterns such as homogeneous or diffuse; speckled; nucleolar; and peripheral or rim.

data.name: Disproportionate short stature
data.def: "A kind of short stature in which different regions of the body are shortened to differing extents." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Mild short stature
data.def: "A mild degree of short stature, more than -2 SD but not more than -3 SD from mean corrected for age and sex." [DDD:hfirth]

data.name: Proportionate short stature
data.def: "A kind of short stature in which different regions of the body are shortened to a comparable extent." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Severe short stature
data.def: "A severe degree of short stature, more than -4 SD from the mean corrected for age and sex." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The term severe short stature is to be preferred over dwarfism, which has been used in the past to refer to individuals with an adult height under 4 feet 10 inches (147 cm).

data.name: Decreased methionine synthase activity
data.def: "A reduction in methionine synthase activity." [HPO:probins]
data.comment: Cobalamin-dependent methionine synthase catalyzes the transfer of a methyl group from N5-methyltetrahydrofolate to homocysteine, producing tetrahydrofolate and methionine, i.e., (6S)-5-methyl-5,6,7,8-tetrahydrofolate + L-homocysteine = (6S)-5,6,7,8-tetrahydrofolate + L-methionine.

data.name: Increased serum pyruvate
data.def: "An increased concentration of pyruvate in the blood." [HPO:gcarletti]
data.comment: An abnormal increase in the concentration of pyruvate in the blood. Pyruvate is involved in energy metabolism, forming part of glycolysis and the citric acid cycle.

data.name: Subsarcolemmal accumulations of abnormally shaped mitochondria
data.def: "An abnormally increased number of mitochondria in the cytoplasma adjacent to the sarcolemma (muscle cell membrane), whereby the mitochondria also possess an abnormal morphology." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This finding can be demonstrated by electron microscopy. This finding is typical of mitochondrial myopathies.

data.name: Abnormality of connective tissue
data.def: "Any abnormality of the soft tissues, including both connective tissue (tendons, ligaments, fascia, fibrous tissues, and fat)." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Difficulty climbing stairs
data.def: "Reduced ability to climb stairs." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Muscle stiffness
data.def: "A condition in which muscles cannot be moved quickly without accompanying pain or spasm." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Type 2 muscle fiber atrophy
data.def: "Atrophy (wasting) affecting primary type 2 muscle fibers. This feature in general can only be observed on muscle biopsy." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This finding can be demonstrated by muscle biopsy.

data.name: Muscle fiber splitting
data.def: "Fiber splitting or branching is a common finding in human and rat skeletal muscle pathology. Fiber splitting refers to longitudinal halving of the complete fiber, while branching originates from a regenerating end of a necrotic fiber as invaginations of the sarcolemma. In fiber branching, one end of the fiber remains intact as a single entity, while the other end has several branches." [pmid:6123177]

data.name: Increased variability in muscle fiber diameter
data.def: "An abnormally high degree of muscle fiber size variation. This phenotypic feature can be observed upon muscle biopsy." [HPO:curators]
data.comment: This finding can be demonstrated by muscle biopsy.

data.name: Muscular dystrophy
data.def: "The term dystrophy means abnormal growth. However, muscular dystrophy is used to describe primary myopathies with a genetic basis and a progressive course characterized by progressive skeletal muscle weakness and wasting, defects in muscle proteins, and histological features of muscle fiber degeneration (necrosis) and regeneration. If possible, it is preferred to use other HPO terms to describe the precise phenotypic abnormalities." [HPO:probinson, Neuromics:vstraub]
data.comment: Muscular dystrophy can be demonstrated by muscle biopsy.

data.name: Hypobetalipoproteinemia
data.def: "An decreased concentration of low-density lipoprotein cholesterol in the blood." [HPO:gcarletti]
data.comment: Beta-lipoprotein cholesterol is a synonym for low-density lipoprotein (LDL) cholesterol.

data.name: Elevated erythrocyte sedimentation rate
data.def: "The presence of a folate sensitive fragile site at chromosome Xq28." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Fragile sites can be defined as heritable specific loci on human chromosomes that exhibit non-random gaps, constrictions or breaks when chromosomes are exposed to specific cell culture conditions. Over 120 different fragile sites have been identified in the human genome. Some of these sites are sensitive to folate, that is, they can be induced by a culture medium deficient in folic acid and thymidine, and hence a medium with lowered levels of dTTP or dCTP, two immediate components of DNA, or by a medium enriched either in methotrexate, an inhibitor of folate metabolism, or in fluorodeoxyuridine, an inhibitor of thymidylate synthesis. The folate-dependent fragile phenotype occurs if more than a critical number of CCG/CGG repeats are present (e.g., > 230 repeats for FRAXA).

data.name: Increased total bilirubin
data.def: "Increased concentration of total (conjugated and unconjugated) bilirubin in the blood." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Deficiency of glucose-6-phosphate isomerase (EC 5.3.1.9).

data.name: Positive regitine blocking test
data.def: "A positive response to the regitine blocking test consisting of a substantial reduction in blood pressure following administration of regitine, indicative of the presence of increased levels of epinephrine and norepinephrine in the circulation, which is seen in pheochromocytoma-associated hypertension." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Regitine produces an alpha-adrenergic block of relatively short duration. In the regitine blocking test, regitine is injected rapidly and bood pressure is recorded immediately after injection, at 30-second intervals for the first 3 minutes, and at 60-second intervals for the next 7 minutes. A positive response to the reginitine blocking test is present when the blood pressure is reduced more than 35 mmHg systolic and 25 mmHg diastolic. A typical positive response is a reduction in pressure of 60 mmHg systolic and 25 mmHg diastolic. A positive response is suggestive of pheochromocytoma and should generally be confirmed by other diagnostic procedures such as measurement of urinary catecholamines or their metabolites.

data.name: Congenital onset
data.def: "A phenotypic abnormality that is present at birth." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Congenital onset literally means present at birth. Congenital abnormalities are thus generally acquired during fetal development. Congenital abnormalities are often but not always hereditary in nature. Whether a disease manifestation is diagnosed to be intrauterine or congenital may depend on the time at which diagnostic procedures are performed. Thus, most congenital abnormalities are also intrauterine.

data.name: Adult onset
data.def: "Onset of disease manifestations in adulthood, defined here as at the age of 16 years or later." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Late onset
data.def: "A type of adult onset with onset of symptoms after the age of 60 years." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Insidious onset
data.def: "Gradual, very slow onset of disease manifestations." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Infantile onset
data.def: "Onset of signs or symptoms of disease between 28 days to one year of life." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Onset of signs or symptoms of disease within the first 24 months of life.

data.name: Antiphospholipid antibody positivity
data.def: "The presence of circulating autoantibodies to phospholipids." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This group of autoantibodies comprises anticardiolipin, antiphosphatidylinositol, atiphosphatidylglycerol, and antiphosphatidylserine antibodies.

data.name: Juvenile onset
data.def: "Onset of signs or symptoms of disease between the age of 5 and 15 years." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Increased concentration of trimethylamine, an organic amino compound with an oder characterized as that of rotting fish, in the urine. Trimethylaminuria is generally caused by impaired oxidation of trimethylamine into the odorless compound trimethylamine N-oxide.

data.name: Neonatal onset
data.def: "Onset of signs or symptoms of disease within the first 28 days of life." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Type I transferrin isoform profile
data.def: "Abnormal transferrin isoform profile consistent with a type I congenital disorder of glycosylation. In the traditional nomenclature for congenital disorders of glycosylation, absence of entire glycans was designated type I, and loss of one or more monosaccharides as type II." [HPO:probinson, pmid:15105360, pmid:22516080]
data.comment: There are several methods in use with which this feature can be diagnosed. Using HPLC analysis an increased asialo- and disialotransferrin and reduced tetrasialotransferrin are observed. Using immunoaffinity column analysis, the mono-oligosaccharide/di-oligosaccharide transferrin ratio, and/or the a-oligosaccharide/di-oligosaccharide transferrin ratio are abnormal.

data.name: Prolonged partial thromboplastin time
data.def: "Increased time to coagulation in the partial thromboplastin time (PTT) test, a measure of the intrinsic and common coagulation pathways. Phospholipid, and activator, and calcium are mixed into an anticoagulated plasma sample, and the time is measured until a thrombus forms." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Sulfite oxidase is responsible for the oxidation of sulfite to sulfate and is the terminal enzyme in the oxidative degradation pathway of sulfur-containing amino acids.

data.name: Foam cells
data.def: "The presence of foam cells, which cells in an atheroma that can be derived from either macrophages or smooth muscle cells that have taken up modified low density lipoprotein particles and thereby take on a foamy appearance." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Foam cells may contain polymorphic cytoplasmic inclusions consisting of lamellar osmiophilic membranes on electron microscopy.

data.name: Onset
data.def: "The age group in which disease manifestations appear." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Adolescent is defined by WHO as a person between 10-19 years of age.

data.name: Centrally nucleated skeletal muscle fibers
data.def: "An abnormality in which the nuclei of sarcomeres take on an abnormally central localization (or in which this feature is found in an increased proportion of muscle cells)." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Normally, the nuclei of muscle cells are located peripherally, immediately under the plasma membrane (sarcolemma).

data.name: Decreased activity of cytochrome C oxidase in muscle tissue
data.def: "An abnormally reduced activity of the enzyme cytochrome C oxidase in muscle tissue." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This abnormality can be assayed by muscle biopsy. Cytochrome C oxidase is an enzyme of the respiratory electron transport chain of mitochondria that is located in the mitochondrial membrane.

data.name: Multiple mitochondrial DNA deletions
data.def: "The presence of multiple deletions of mitochondrial DNA (mtDNA)." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This feature can be demonstrated by muscle biopsy.

data.name: Distal amyotrophy
data.def: "Muscular atrophy affecting muscles in the distal portions of the extremities." [HPO:curators]
data.comment: Most polyneuropathies affect distal lower extremity miuscles early on. Polyneuropathies are roughly symmeetric in distribution and tend to affect nerves in a length-dependent manner, with the longest nerves first (stocking-glove distribution).

data.name: Generalized amyotrophy
data.def: "Generalized (diffuse, unlocalized) amyotrophy (muscle atrophy) affecting multiple muscles." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Proximal muscle weakness
data.def: "A lack of strength of the proximal muscles." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Removed logical definition that used anonymous class. Outstanding term request in UBERON for proximal muscle organ.

data.name: Calf muscle pseudohypertrophy
data.def: "Enlargement of the muscles of the calf due to their replacement by connective tissue or fat." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Pseudohypertrophy of the calf musculature is commonly seen in certain muscular dystrophies but also with spinal muscular atrophy and other denervating conditions.

data.name: Exercise-induced muscle cramps
data.def: "Sudden and involuntary contractions of one or more muscles brought on by physical exertion." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Skeletal muscle hypertrophy
data.def: "Hypertrophy (increase in size) of muscle cells (as opposed to hyperplasia, which refers to an increase in the number of muscle cells)." [HPO:curators]
data.comment: Increased muscle bulk based on clinical observation.

data.name: Muscle fiber necrosis
data.def: "Abnormal cell death involving muscle fibers usually associated with break in, or absence of, muscle surface fiber membrane and resulting in irreversible damage to muscle fibers." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Myofibrillar myopathy
data.def: "Myofibrillar structural changes characterized by abnormal intracellular accumulation of the intermediate filament desmin and other proteins." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This feature is demonstrated by muscle biopsy.

data.name: Exercise-induced myalgia
data.def: "The occurrence of an unusually high amount of muscle pain following exercise." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This is a bundled term that should not be used for future annotations.

data.name: Congenital muscular dystrophy
data.def: "Myotonia that occurs after a period of rest and decreases with continuing exercise." [HPO:probinson, pmid:7678441]

data.name: Genetic anticipation
data.def: "A mode of inheritance in which the severity of a disorder increases or the age of onset decreases as the disorder is passed from one generation to the next." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This mode of inheritance is characteristic of trinucleotide and some other repeat disorders.

data.name: Sporadic
data.def: "Cases of the disease in question occur without a previous family history, i.e., as isolated cases without being transmitted from a parent and without other siblings being affected." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Increased muscle fatiguability
data.def: "An abnormal, increased fatiguability of the musculature." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Calcinosis
data.def: "Formation of calcium deposits in any soft tissue." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This feature can be demonstrated by lymphography.

data.name: Nevus
data.def: "A nevus is a type of hamartoma that is a circumscribed stable malformation of the skin." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The word Nevus derives from the Latin word Knee-vus meaning birthmark or mole.

data.name: Periodic paralysis
data.def: "Episodes of muscle weakness." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Pili torti
data.def: "Pili (from Latin pilus, hair) torti (from Latin tortus, twisted) refers to short and brittle hairs that appear flattened and twisted when viewed through a microscope." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Excessive salivation
data.def: "Excessive production of saliva." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Nemaline bodies
data.def: "Nemaline rods are abnormal bodies that can occur in skeletal muscle fibers. The rods can be observed on histological analysis of muscle biopsy tissue or upon electron microscopy, where they appear either as extensions of sarcomeric Z-lines, in random array without obvious attachment to Z-lines (often in areas devoid of sarcomeres) or in large clusters localized at the sarcolemma or intermyofibrillar spaces." [HPO:curators, PMID:11333380]
data.comment: This finding can be demonstrated by muscle biopsy, which shows nemaline bodies (rods) on Gomori trichrome staining.

data.name: Muscle abnormality related to mitochondrial dysfunction
Type 1 muscle fiber predominance
data.def: "An abnormal predominance of type I muscle fibers (in general, this feature can only be observed on muscle biopsy)." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This finding is demonstrated by muscle biopsy.

data.name: Rimmed vacuoles
data.def: "Presence of abnormal vacuoles (membrane-bound organelles) in the sarcolemma. On histological staining with hematoxylin and eosin, rimmed vacuoles are popcorn-like clear vacuoles with a densely blue rim. The vacuoles are often associated with cytoplasmic and occasionally intranuclear eosinophilic inclusions." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Rimmed vacuoles are characteristic for inclusion-bosy myositis, but are also seen an a number of other diseases. This term implies that rimmed vacuoles are found histologically. In some cases, the majority of muscle fibers are involved, but in others, rimmed vacuoles can be found in only a minority of fibers.

data.name: Neonatal death
data.def: "Death within the first 28 days of life." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Phenotypic variability
data.def: "A variability of phenotypic features." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This term can be applied to disease entities but not to individuals. It may be made obsolete in future versions of the HPO.

data.name: Death in childhood
data.def: "Death in during childhood, defined here as between the ages of 2 and 10 years." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Stillbirth
data.def: "Death of the fetus in utero after at least 20 weeks of gestation." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Variable expressivity
data.def: "A variable severity of phenotypic features." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This term can be applied to disease entities but not to individuals. It may be made obsolete in future versions of the HPO.

data.name: Incomplete penetrance
data.def: "A situation in which mutation carriers do not show clinically evident phenotypic abnormalities." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This term can be applied to disease entities but not to individuals. It may be made obsolete in future versions of the HPO.

data.name: Abnormality of the radial head
data.def: "An injury of the wrist with displacement of any of the eight carpal bones." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Sclerosis of hand bone
data.def: "Osteosclerosis affecting one or more bones of the hand." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Midline defect of the nose
data.def: "This term groups together three conditions that presumably represent different degrees of severity of a midline defect of the nose or nasal tip." [HPO:sdoelken]

data.name: Duplication of hand bones
data.def: "A partial dislocation of some or all of the small joints of the hand." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Narrow palm
data.def: "For children from birth to 4 years of age, the palm width is more than 2 SD below the mean; for children from 4 to 16 years of age the palm width is below the 5th centile; or, the width of the palm appears disproportionately narrow for its length." [pmid:19125433]
data.comment: Palm width is measured across the palm at the level of the MCPJ (radial aspect of the F2 MCPJ to the ulnar aspect of the F5 MCPJ). Norms are specified in [Hall et al., 2007]. Caution is advised for the subjective assessment as the breadth may be in the normal range with disproportionately increased length, which appears narrow. This finding may be associated with elongated/slender limbs in general, but that finding does not bear on the coding of this feature. Proximal narrowing may indicate small thenar or hypothenar eminences. This term replaces "narrow hands" as that term may leave the impression that it includes the thumb, which it does not.

data.name: Abnormality of the gastric mucosa
data.def: "An abnormality of the gastric mucous membrane." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the biliary system
data.def: "An abnormality of the biliary system." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the abdominal wall
data.def: "The presence of any abnormality affecting the abdominal wall." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of muscle fibers
data.def: "Any abnormality of the skeletal muscle cell. Muscle fibers are subdivided into two types. Type I fibers are fatigue-resistant and rich in oxidative enzymes (they stain light with the myosin ATPase reaction), and type II fibers are fast-contracting, fatigue-prone, and rich in glycolytic enzymes (these fibers stain darkly). Normal muscle tissue has a random distribution of type I and type II fibers." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Skeletal muscle fibers are cylindrical multinucleated muscle cells. This feature is meant to group abnormalities appreciated by histology, electron microscopy, and similar methods that allow individual cells to be visualized.

data.name: Involuntary movements
data.def: "Involuntary contractions of muscle leading to involuntary movements of extremities, neck, trunk, or face." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the endocardium
data.def: "An abnormality of the endocardium." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormal anatomic location of the heart
Ventricular preexcitation
data.def: "An abnormality in which the cardiac ventricles depolarize too early as a result of an abnormality of cardiac conduction pathways such as an accessory pathway." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Pre-excitation syndromes are generally caused by accelerated conduction along an accessory pathway, but in some cases there is accelerated conduction through the normal AV node.

data.name: Hypoaldosteronism
data.def: "Abnormally reduced levels of aldosterone." [DDD:spark, HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Aldosterone is a hormone that is produce by the adrenal cortex and that acts on the distal tubules and collecting ducts to favor retention of sodium excretion of potassium, and increased water retention, thereby tending to increase blood pressure. Aldosterone is sometimes called a mineralocorticoid because of its influence on sodium homeostasis.

data.name: Short stature
data.def: "A height below that which is expected according to age and gender norms. Although there is no universally accepted definition of short stature, many refer to \"short stature\" as height more than 2 standard deviations below the mean for age and gender (or below the 3rd percentile for age and gender dependent norms)." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Abnormality of body weight
data.def: "An abnormal increase or decrease of weight or an abnormal distribution of mass in the body." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Cachexia
data.def: "Severe weight loss, wasting of muscle, loss of appetite, and general debility related to a chronic disease." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the vitreous humor
data.def: "An anomaly of the vitreous body." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The vitreous humor is the clear gel that fills the space between the lens and the retina.

data.name: Abnormality of the anterior segment of the eye
data.def: "An abnormality of the anterior segment of the eye." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The anterior segment comprises the structures in front of the vitreous humour: the cornea, iris, ciliary body, and lens.

data.name: Abnormality of the posterior segment of the eye
data.comment: The posterior segment comprises the anterior hyaloid membrane and all of the optical structures behind it: the vitreous humor, retina, choroid, and optic nerve.

data.name: Dermal atrophy
data.def: "Partial or complete wasting (atrophy) of the skin." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of amino acid metabolism
data.def: "Abnormality of an amino acid metabolic process." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This finding can be demonstrated by nerve biopsy (e.g., sural nerve biopsy).

data.name: Abnormality of aromatic amino acid family metabolism
data.def: "An abnormality of a aromatic amino acid family metabolic process." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of sulfur amino acid metabolism
data.def: "An abnormality of a sulfur amino acid metabolic process." [HPO:gcarletti]
data.comment: Cysteine and methionine contain a sulfur atom.

data.name: Abnormality of the vitamin B12 metabolism
Abnormality of glycosphingolipid metabolism
data.def: "An abnormality of glycosphingolipid metabolism." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Glycosphingolipids are a subtype of glycolipids containing the amino alcohol sphingosine. A glycosphingolipid is a carbohydrate-containing derivative of a sphingoid or ceramide. It is understood that the carbohydrate residue is attached by a glycosidic linkage to O-1 of the sphingoid.

data.name: Abnormality of ganglioside metabolism
data.def: "Abnormality of ganglioside metabolism." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: A ganglioside is composed of a glycosphingolipid with one or more sialic acids linked on the sugar chain.

data.name: Abnormality of bone mineral density
data.def: "This term applies to all changes in bone mineral density which (depending on severity) can be seen on x-rays as a change in density and or structure of the bone. Changes may affect all bones of the organism, just certain bones or only parts of bones and include decreased mineralisation as may be seen in osteoporosis or increased mineralisation and or ossification as in osteopetrosis, exostoses or any kind of atopic calicfications of different origin and distribution. The overall amount of mineralization of the bone-organ can be measured as the amount of matter per cubic centimeter of bones, usually measured by densitometry of the lumbar spine or hip. The measurements are usually reported as g/cm3 or as a Z-score (the number of standard deviations above or below the mean for the patient's age and sex). Note that measurement with this method does not reflect local changes in other bones, and as such might not be correct with regard the hole bone-organ." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Reduced bone mineral density
data.def: "A reduction of bone mineral density, that is, of the amount of matter per cubic centimeter of bones." [HPO:sdoelken]

data.name: Abnormality of pyrimidine metabolism
data.def: "An abnormality of a pyrimidine base metabolic process." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of carboxylic acid metabolism
data.def: "An abnormality of the metabolism of a carboxylic acid." [HPO:gcarletti]

data.name: Abnormality of lysosomal metabolism
data.def: "An abnormality of proteoglycan metabolism." [HPO:gcarletti]
data.comment: A major lysosomal function is the breakdown and recycling of macromolecules and organelles into basic precursors.

data.name: Abnormality of fatty-acid metabolism
data.def: "An abnormality of fatty acid metabolism." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: A fatty acid is an aliphatic monocarboxylic acid derived from or contained in esterified form. Natural fatty acids commonly have a chain of 4 to 28 carbons (usually unbranched and even-numbered), which may be saturated or unsaturated. R-COOH. Fatty acids are usually derived from triglycerides or phospholipids.

data.name: Abnormality of acid-base homeostasis
data.def: "An abnormality of the balance or maintenance of the balance of acids and bases in bodily fluids, resulting in an abnormal pH." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of calcium homeostasis
data.def: "An abnormality of calcium ion homeostasis." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of nitrogen compound homeostasis
data.def: "The presence of an abnormal concentration of nitrogen compounds." [HPO:gcarletti]
data.comment: Ammonia (NH3), one of the most clinically important nitrogen compounds in human metabolism, is a substance containing nitrogen resulting from the catabolism of protein. It is converted to the less toxic substance urea prior to excretion in urine.

data.name: Abnormality of glycolysis
data.def: "An abnormality of glycolysis." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of temperature regulation
data.def: "An abnormality of temperature homeostasis." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This category is meant to contain biochemical abnormalities indicative of abnormal protein sugar modifications.

data.name: Abnormality of glycosaminoglycan metabolism
data.def: "Abnormality of glycosaminoglycan metabolism." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: A glycosaminoglycan is any polysaccharide containing a substantial proportion of aminomonosaccharide residues. Glycosaminoglycan (GAG) are long unbranched polysaccharides consisting of a repeating disaccharide unit.
