Among the most common GAGs are chondroitin sulfate, dermatan sulfate, chondroitin sulfate, keratan sulfate, heparan sulfate, and hyaluronan.

data.name: Focal dystonia
data.def: "A type of dystonia that is localized to a specific part of the body." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Hemiplegia/hemiparesis
data.def: "Loss of strength in the arm, leg, and sometimes face on one side of the body. Hemiplegia refers to a severe or complete loss of strength, whereas hemiparesis refers to a relatively mild loss of strength." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Neoplasm of the nervous system
data.def: "A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the nervous system." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Neuroblastic tumors
data.comment: Along with neuroblastomas, ganglioneuromas and ganglioneuroblastomas are collectively known as neuroblastic tumors.

data.name: Abnormality of the anus
data.def: "Abnormality of the anal canal." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The anal canal is continuous proximally with the rectum and distally terminates with the anus.

data.name: Abnormality of alkaline phosphatase activity
data.def: "An abnormality of alkaline phosphatase activity." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Note that the alkaline phosphatase family has four isoenzymes in humans, each of which additionally can have different isoforms. The primary clinical importance of measuring alkaline phosphatase is to check the possibility of bone disease or liver disease.

data.name: Hypoplastic left heart
data.def: "Underdevelopment of the left side of the heart. May include atresia of the aortic or mitral orifice and hypoplasia of the ascending aorta." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Protracted diarrhea
data.def: "Truncus arteriosus (single great artery leaving the base of the heart, giving rise to the coronary, pulmonary, and systemic arteries) with a short pulmonary trunk arises from the truncus arteriosus, giving rise to both pulmonary arteries." [DDD:dbrown, HPO:probinson]
data.comment: According to the Van Praagh classification (pmid:2856609). The Van Praagh classification additionally specifies the presence (subtype A) or absence (subtype B) of a ventricular septal defect.

data.name: Malnutrition
data.def: "A kind of congenital defect of the anterior abdominal wall in which the intestines are evident through the thin, lax, and protruding abdominal wall in affected infants." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Wrinkly folds of skin covering the abdomen as a result of partial or complete lack of abdominal muscles.

data.name: Ectopic anus
data.def: "Abnormal displacement or malposition of the anus." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Peptic ulcer
data.def: "An ulcer of the gastrointestinal tract." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: A peptic ulcer is defined as an erosion of the mucosa of the gastrointestinal tract, and can occur as esophageal ulcer, gastric ulcer, duodenal ulcer, and Meckel's Diverticulum ulcer.

data.name: Abnormality of the pylorus
data.def: "An abnormality of the pylorus." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the nipple
data.def: "An abnormality of the nipple." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Obstruction of the intestine is known as ileus.

data.name: Thrombophlebitis
data.def: "Inflammation of a vein associated with venous thrombosis (blood clot formation within the vein)." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Vascular intermittent claudication caused by peripheral arterial disease most often related to severe atherosclerosis.

data.name: Arterial thrombosis
data.def: "The formation of a blood clot inside an artery." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Flat forehead
data.def: "A forehead with abnormal flatness." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Normal systolic blood pressure is less than 120 mmHg in adults.

data.name: Recurrent viral infections
data.def: "Increased susceptibility to viral infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of viral infection." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Severe combined immunodeficiency
data.def: "Severe combine immunodeficiency (SCID) is a primary immune deficiency that is characterized by a severe defect in both the T- and B-lymphocyte systems." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Abnormality of the middle ear ossicles
data.def: "An abnormality of the middle-ear ossicles (three small bones called malleus, incus, and stapes) that are contained within the middle ear and serve to transmit sounds from the air to the fluid-filled labyrinth (cochlea)." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Congenital, generalized hypertrichosis
data.def: "A confluent, generalized overgrowth of silvery blonde to gray lanugo hair at birth." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Hypertrichosis refers to excessive, abnormal hairiness.

data.name: Beaking of vertebral bodies
data.def: "Anterior tongue-like protrusions of the vertebral bodies." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Increased vertebral height
data.def: "Increased top to bottom height of vertebral bodies." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Biconcave vertebral bodies
data.def: "Exaggerated concavity of the anterior or posterior surface of the vertebral body, i.e., the upper and lower vertebral endplates are hollowed inward." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This finding has been called fish or codfish vertebra because of the characteristic biconcave form of fish vertebral bodies.

data.name: Absent or minimally ossified vertebral bodies
data.def: "Three ossification sites are present in typical vertebral bodies (C3-L5): a single ossification center in the vertebral body, and one each in the two neural arches. This term applies if there are additional vertebral ossification centers present during the development and maturation of the spine." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Decreased facial expression
data.def: "A reduced degree of voluntary and involuntary facial movements involved in responded to others or expressing emotions." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This feature can be found in pregnancies with fetuses affected by a range of abnormalities including for instance encephalocele.

data.name: Renal malrotation
data.def: "An abnormality of the normal developmental rotation of the kidney leading to an abnormal orientation of the kidney." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The final kidney position in the renal fossa results from the rotation of the kidney with an orientation of the renal pelvis to the medial and the renal calyces to the lateral. Malrotation of the kidney can lead to orientation of the renal pelvis anteriorly, posteriorly and laterally. In most cases, renal malrotation does not cause any symptoms, but, hydronephrosis or stone formation can be observed as complications of renal malformation.

data.name: Hyperechogenic kidneys
data.def: "An increase in amplitude of waves returned in ultrasonography of the kidney, which is generally displayed as increased brightness of the signal." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Calcium nephrolithiasis
data.def: "The presence of calcium-containing calculi (stones) in the kidneys." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The overwhelming majority of renal calculi contain calcium.

data.name: Renal cortical microcysts
data.def: "Cysts of microscopic size confined to the cortex of the kidney." [Eurenomics:ewuehl]
data.comment: An impairment in renal concentrating ability can be easily recognized by the maximum concentrating ability (Umax) as determined by the urine osmolality reached after a fixed period of dehydration. Inability to maximally concentrate the urine is related to one or both of two basic tubular defects: 1) a failure of maximal free-water generation by the diluting segment in the ascending limb of Henle's loop; and 2) a failure of the distal tubular epithelium to achieve maximum permeability to water during water deprivation.

data.name: Abnormality of the renal collecting system
data.def: "An abnormality of the renal collecting system." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: All portions of all glomeruli are affected.

data.name: Atrial flutter
data.def: "A type of atrial arrhythmia characterized by atrial rates of between 240 and 400 beats per minute and some degree of atrioventricular node conduction block. Typically, the ventricular rate is half the atrial rate. In the EKG; atrial flutter waves are observed as sawtooth-like atrial activity. Pathophysiologically, atrial flutter is a form of atrial reentry in which there is a premature electrical impulse creates a self-propagating circuit." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Atrial flutter can lead to palpitations, fatigue, dyspnea, and chest pain.  Atrial flutter can be paroxysmal or persistent.

data.name: Supraventricular tachycardia
data.def: "Supraventricular tachycardia (SVT) is an abnormally increased heart rate (over 100 beats per minute at rest) with origin above the level of the ventricles." [DDD:dbrown, HPO:probinson]
data.comment: A narrow complex (QRS width less than 120 milliseconds) reflects rapid activation of the ventricles via the normal conduction pathway, i.e. His-Purkinje system, which in turn suggests that the tachycardia originated above the AV node and is thus supraventricular.

data.name: Paroxysmal atrial fibrillation
data.def: "Episodes of atrial fibrillation that typically last for several hours up to one day and terminate spontaneously." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Gastrointestinal obstruction
data.def: "Polyp-like protrusions which are histologically hamartomas located in the stomach." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Malrotation results not only in the malposition of the bowel but also in the malfixation of the mesentery. The normally broad mesenteric attachment is shortened to a narrow pedicle that predisposes the patient to the complication of midgut volvulus.

data.name: Impairment of galactose metabolism
data.def: "An impairment of galactose metabolism." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of magnesium homeostasis
data.def: "An abnormality of magnesium ion homeostasis." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Hyperphenylalaninemia
data.def: "An increased concentration of L-phenylalanine in the blood." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Venous thrombosis
data.def: "Formation of a blood clot (thrombus) inside a vein, causing the obstruction of blood flow." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Pulmonary artery atresia means that unoxygenated blood in the right ventricle can not be effectively pumped into the lung for oxygenation.

data.name: Arteriovenous fistula
data.def: "A separation (dissection) of the layers of the extracranial portion of the internal carotid artery wall." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: High-frequency hearing impairment
data.def: "A type of hearing impairment affecting primarily the higher frequencies of sound (3,000 to 6,000 Hz)." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: High frequency hearing impairment often involves loss of ability to hear consonants such as s, f, t, and z, even though vowels can be heard normally.

data.name: Abnormal nasal morphology
data.def: "Underdevelopment of the nasal septum." [HPO:curators]
data.comment: This is a category for overall abnormal morphology that may be replaced later with more exact descriptions.

data.name: Abnormality of the vertebral endplates
data.def: "Any abnormality of the vertebral end plates, which are the top and bottom portions of the vertebral bodies that interface with the vertebral discs." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Abnormality of the sacrum
data.def: "An abnormality of the sacral bone." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the intervertebral disk
data.def: "An abnormality of the intervertebral disk." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Any abnormality of the fibrocartilaginous structures that are located between adjacent vertebral bodies.

data.name: Abnormality of the Achilles tendon
data.def: "An abnormality of the Achilles tendon." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Atrial fibrillation
data.def: "An atrial arrhythmia characterized by disorganized atrial activity without discrete P waves on the surface EKG, but instead by an undulating baseline or more sharply circumscribed atrial deflections of varying amplitude an frequency ranging from 350 to 600 per minute." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The ventricular response to atrial fibrillation is irregularly irregular because of the large number of atrial impulses that transit the atrioventricular node, making the ventricle partially refractory to further impulses. Atrial fibrillation can cause a number of manifestations including excessive ventricular response with angina pectoris or hypotension in susceptible individuals, syncope, systemic embolization, fatigue, or anxiety. These features should be coded separately.

data.name: Supraventricular arrhythmia
data.def: "A type of arrhythmia that originates above the ventricles, whereby the electrical impulse propagates down the normal His Purkinje system similar to normal sinus rhythm." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Supraventricular arrhythmia includes atrial arrhythmias (atrial tachycardia, atrial flutter, atrial fibrillation), atrioventricular nodal reentrant tachycardia, junctional ectopic tachycardia, atrioventricular reentrant tachycardia (Wolf-Parkinson-White Syndrome), orthodromic or antidromic. Supraventricular arrhythmia is distinct from ventricular tachycardia, which originates in the ventricles.

data.name: Arterial tortuosity
data.def: "Abnormal tortuous (i.e., twisted) form of arteries." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Abnormality of cardiac atrium
data.def: "An abnormality of a cardiac atrium." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Normal diastolic blood pressure is less than 80 mmHg.

data.name: Abnormal atrioventricular conduction
data.def: "Abnormal calcification of a cardiac valve." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The distinctive feature of APVS is the airway obstruction caused by tracheobronchial compression that results from massive dilatation of the main pulmonary artery (PA) and its first- and second-order branches. Consequential tracheomalacia and bronchomalacia determine the timing and severity of respiratory compromise, as well as the morbidity and mortality of these patients.

data.name: Tricuspid regurgitation
data.def: "Failure of the tricuspid valve to close sufficiently upon contraction of the right ventricle, causing blood to regurgitate (flow backward) into the right atrium." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This term should not be applied to Ebstein's anomaly of the tricuspid valve (see HP:0010316).

data.name: Intestinal obstruction
data.def: "Blockage or impairment of the normal flow of the contents of the intestine towards the anal canal." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Esophageal perforation can lead to retained gastric contents, saliva, bile, and other substances entering the mediastinum, resulting in mediastinitis, which in turn may lead to sepsis.

data.name: Bowel diverticulosis
data.def: "The presence of multiple diverticula of the intestine." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This feature can be ascertained by immunoassay of gastric juices.

data.name: Thoracic hypoplasia
data.def: "Aplasia (congenital absence) of the pectoralis minor on only one side of the chest." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Dysplasia is defined in MPATH as a distortion or deficiency of the tissue or cellular architecture.

data.name: Abnormality of the gallbladder
data.def: "An abnormality of the gallbladder." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Spontaneous abortion
data.def: "A pregnancy that ends at a stage in which the fetus is incapable of surviving on its own, defined as the spontaneous loss of a fetus before the 20th week of pregnancy." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Prominent nasolabial fold
data.def: "Exaggerated bulkiness of the crease or fold of skin running from the lateral margin of the nose, where nasal base meets the skin of the face, to a point just lateral to the corner of the mouth (cheilion, or commissure)." [pmid:19125428]

data.name: Depressed nasal bridge
data.def: "Posterior positioning of the nasal root in relation to the overall facial profile for age." [pmid:19152422]
data.comment: The adjective "depressed" here does not indicate an active process but a status. A depressed nasal bridge can occur irrespective of the width of the nasal bridge, and the width should be assessed independently. In infancy, the nasal bridge is relatively more posterior than in the older person. The term depressed nasal bridge should only be used when the bridge is more posterior than is typical for age and ethnic background.

data.name: Abnormality of the nares
data.def: "Abnormality of the nostril." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Cerebral venous thrombosis
data.def: "Formation of a blood clot (thrombus) inside a cerebral vein, causing the obstruction of blood flow." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Note that the ligamentum arteriosum, which develops from the ductus arteriosus, is attached to the superior surface of the pulmonary artery and the inferior surface of the aortic arch.

data.name: Capillary hemangiomas
data.def: "The presence of a capillary hemangiomas, which are hemangiomas with small endothelial spaces." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of complement system
data.def: "An abnormality of the complement system." [HPO:probinson, pmid:19388161]
data.comment: The complement system represents a family of over 25 serum proteins and cell surface receptors that act in a cascade manner leading to innate functions such as inflammation and enhancement of adaptive immunity. Three general pathways, i.e. classical, lectin and alternative, activate the complement system.

data.name: Abnormality of the carotid arteries
data.def: "Underdevelopment of the urinary bladder." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Inspiratory stridor
data.def: "Inspiratory stridor is a high pitched sound upon inspiration that is generally related to laryngeal abnormalities." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Abnormality of humoral immunity
data.def: "An abnormality of the humoral immune system, which comprises antibodies produced by B cells as well as the complement system." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Combined immunodeficiency
data.def: "Increased susceptibility to protozoan infections, as manifested by recurrent episodes of protozoan infection." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Recurrent gram-negative bacterial infections
data.def: "Increased susceptibility to infection by gram-negative bacteria, as manifested by a medical history of repeated or frequent infections by these agents." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Gram-negative bacteria have a unique outer membrane, a thinner layer of peptidoglycan compared to gram-positive bacteria, and a periplasmic space between the cell wall and the membrane.

data.name: Abnormality of the epiglottis
data.def: "An abnormality of the epiglottis." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Bone marrow hypocellularity
data.def: "A reduced number of hematopoietic cells present in the bone marrow." [DDD:wouwehand, HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Kininogen is cleaved into the following 6 chains: 1) Kininogen-1 heavy chain; 2) T-kinin; 3) Bradykinin; 4) Lysyl-bradykinin; 5) Kininogen-1 light chain; and 6) Low molecular weight growth-promoting factor.

data.name: Abnormality of the zygomatic arch
data.def: "An abnormality of the zygomatic arch, also known as the cheek bone." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The zygomatic arch is formed by the zygomatic process of temporal bone and the temporal process of the zygomatic bone.

data.name: Abnormality of bone marrow cell morphology
data.def: "An anomaly of the form or number of cells in the bone marrow." [DDD:wouwehand, HPO:probinson]

data.name: Tubulointerstitial fibrosis
data.def: "Fibrosis that involves the tubules and interstitial tissue of the kidney." [HPO:probinson, pmid:19144691]
data.comment: This finding is usually shown by renal biopsy. Fibrosis involves an excess accumulation of extracellular matrix and usually results in loss of function when normal tissue is replaced with scar tissue.

data.name: Hypopigmentation of hair
data.def: "Telangiectases (small dilated blood vessels) located near the surface of the skin in a butterfly midface distribution." [HPO:curators]
data.comment: Giant melanosomes can be seen in cafe-au-lait spots and other melanocytic disorders. Giant melanosome and giant melanosome are synonymous. Macromelanosomes can be detected by electron microscopy of the skin.

data.name: Abnormality of the tracheobronchial system
data.def: "Large hypermelanotic macules with jagged borders." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This type of lesionk is observed in McCune Albright syndrome. The cafe-au-lait macules are larger than those seen in neurofibromatosis, and have more irregular borders. The borders of these macules have been compared to the coast of Maine, whereas the cafe-au-lait spots in neurofibromatosis type 1 have been compared to the coast of California.

data.name: Accelerated skeletal maturation
data.def: "An abnormally increased rate of skeletal maturation. Accelerated skeletal maturation can be diagnosed on the basis of an estimation of the bone age from radiographs of specific bones in the human body." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Positional foot deformity
data.def: "A foot deformity resulting due to an abnormality affecting the muscle and soft tissue. In contrast if the bones of the foot are affected the term structural foot deformity applies." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This feature is characteristic of metachondromatosis (MIM:156250).

data.name: Multiple prenatal fractures
data.def: "The presence of bone fractures in the prenatal period that are diagnosed at birth or before." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Abnormal cervical curvature
data.def: "The presence of an abnormal curvature of the cervical vertebral column." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The term metaphyseal chondrodysplasia is usually used to describe a disease but is often also used to describe the corresponding phenotypic appearance. This use is retained in the HPO for convenience, but if possible a precise phenotypic description is preferred.

data.name: Abnormal metacarpal morphology
data.def: "Irregularly shaped metacarpal bones of varying degree." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Abnormal hand morphology
data.def: "Any structural anomaly of the hand." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This is a category to be used for general descriptions of hand dysmorphology. In time, it should be replaced by more accurate descriptions.

data.name: Abnormal respiratory motile cilium morphology
data.def: "Abnormal arrangement of the structures of the axoneme, which is the cytoskeletal structure that forms the inner core of the motile cilium and displays a canonical 9 + 2 microtubular pattern of motile cilia studded with dynein arms." [HPO:probinson, MP:0011050]
data.comment: On T1-weighted magnetic resonance imaging, the signal intensity of the normal renal cortex is typically higher than medulla, resulting in easily visualized corticomedullary differentiation (CMD). Loss of CMD can be seen in disorders such as glomerulonephritis, acute tubular necrosis, end-stage chronic renal failure, obstructive hydronephrosis, and acute allograft rejection.

data.name: Breathing dysregulation
data.def: "Abnormal shortening of the larynx in the anteroposterior (front to back) axis." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Manifestations may appear at any age (hoarse or weak voice and frequent upper respiratory infections) but onset usually occurs during infancy (respiratory distress, stridor and an unusual cry).

data.name: Limitation of neck motion
data.def: "An elevation of alpha-feto protein in the maternal serum." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Ureteral obstruction
data.def: "Obstruction of the flow of urine through the ureter." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: With age and increased vertical growth of the neck, excess nuchal skin may disappear and the neck may become broad or webbed. If the skin folds are vertical or paravertical, the term Neck webbing should be used.

data.name: Deep palmar crease
data.def: "Excessively deep creases of the palm." [pmid:19125433]

data.name: Elevated alpha-fetoprotein
data.def: "An increased concentration of alpha-fetoprotein." [HPO:gcarletti]
data.comment: An elevation of alpha-feto protein, which is produced by the fetal liver and the yolk sac and may be increased in the serum of pregnant women with a fetus with some types of developmental anomaly such as open neural tube defects and omphalocele.

data.name: Advanced eruption of teeth
data.def: "Premature tooth eruption, which can be defined as tooth eruption more than 2 SD earlier than the mean eruption age." [HPO:ibailleulforestier, pmid:19125428]
data.comment: There are established norms for the timing of eruption in both deciduous and permanent teeth [Garn and Rohmann, [1966]; Lunt and Law, [1974]; McDonald et al. [2004]]. Eruption is defined by the appearance of a tooth that has pierced the gum.

data.name: Abnormality of dental eruption
data.def: "An abnormality of tooth eruption." [HPO:ibailleulforestier]
data.comment: The average ages for eruption of the primary teeth are: 6 months: lower central incisor, 7 months: upper central incisor, 8 months: upper lateral incisor, 9 months: lower lateral incisor, 12 months first molars, 18 months, canines, 2 years, second molars.

data.name: Hypoplasia of dental enamel
data.def: "Developmental hypoplasia of the dental enamel." [HPO:ibailleulforestier, pmid:18499550]
data.comment: Note that the term enamel dysplasia was previously used for this feature but is no longer recommended.

data.name: Single median maxillary incisor
data.def: "The presence of a single, median maxillary incisor, affecting both the primary maxillary incisor and the permanent maxillary incisor." [pmid:19125428]
data.comment: If a single maxillary central incisor is present but not positioned in the midline, this could be hypodontia, but this cannot be evaluated without a radiograph.

data.name: Premature loss of primary teeth
data.def: "Loss of the primary (also known as deciduous) teeth before the usual age." [HPO:sdoelken]
data.comment: The primary teeth are usually shed and replaced by the permanent teeth, usually by the age of six years. With premature loss of primary teeth, there is a delay between the loss of the primary teeth and the eruption of the permanent teeth.

data.name: Persistence of primary teeth
data.def: "Persistence of the primary teeth beyond the age by which they normally are shed and replaced by the permanent teeth." [HPO:ibailleulforestier]
data.comment: The primary teeth are usually shed and replaced by the permanent teeth, usually by the age of six years. Persistence of primary teeth may be related to agenesis of the permanent teeth. Molar primary teeth may be persistent because of the agenesis of the premolars.

data.name: Agenesis of permanent teeth
data.def: "A congenital defect characterized by the absence of one or more permanent teeth, including oligodontia, hypodontia, and adontia of the of permanent teeth." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Broad femoral neck
data.def: "An abnormally wide femoral neck (which is the process of bone, connecting the femoral head with the femoral shaft)." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Note that compact bone and cortical bone are synonymous.

data.name: Abnormality of the alveolar ridges
data.def: "Any abnormality of the alveolar ridges (on the upper or lower jaws). The alveolar ridges contain the sockets (alveoli) of the teeth." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the dental pulp
data.def: "An abnormality of the dental pulp." [HPO:ibailleulforestier]

data.name: Premature loss of teeth
data.def: "Premature loss of teeth not related to trauma or neglect." [HPO:ibailleulforestier]

data.name: Abnormality of primary teeth
data.def: "Any abnormality of the primary tooth." [HPO:ibailleulforestier]
data.comment: Primary teeth are also called temporary teeth or deciduous teeth.

data.name: Abnormality of dental morphology
data.def: "An abnormality of the morphology of the tooth." [HPO:ibailleulforestier]

data.name: Abnormal number of teeth
data.def: "The presence of an altered number of of teeth." [HPO:ibailleulforestier]
data.comment: Humans usually have 20 primary teeth (also called deciduous teeth) and 32 permanent teeth. This term comprises anomalies with too many or too few teeth.

data.name: Abnormality of the dental root
data.def: "An abnormality of the dental root." [HPO:ibailleulforestier]

data.name: Alveolar proteinosis
data.def: "Abnormal accumulation of surfactant-like, periodic acid-schiff-positive lipoproteinaceous material in macrophages within the alveolar spaces and distal bronchioles. This results in gas exchange impairment leading to dyspnea and alveolar infiltrates." [HPO:probinson, pmid:22891182]
data.comment: The laryngeal stridor sound is usually heard during inspiratory phase, also called inspiratory stridor, and may accompanied by inspiratory difficulty in breathing.  It may be due to abnormal flaccidity of the epiglottis or arytenoids.

data.name: Chronic lung disease
data.def: "According to the definitions of the American and British Thoracic Societies, including pulmonary functional tests, X-rays, and CT scans for items such as fibrosis, bronchiectasis, bullae, emphysema, nodular or lymphomatous abnormalities." [IMM:tkuijpers]
data.comment: Associated clinical manifestations often include fever, cough, and shortness of breath.

data.name: Interstitial pulmonary disease
data.def: "Abnormality of the lung parenchyma extending to the pulmonary interstitium and leading to diffuse pulmonary fibrosis." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Obstructive lung disease
data.def: "Obstruction of conducting airways of the lung." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Acute hepatic failure
data.def: "Hepatic failure refers to the inability of the liver to perform its normal synthetic and metabolic functions, which can result in coagulopathy and alteration in the mental status of a previously healthy individual. Hepatic failure is defined as acute if there is onset of encephalopathy within 8 weeks of the onset of symptoms in a patient with a previously healthy liver." [HPO:curators]
data.comment: Extrapulmonary sequestra nearly all appear on the left side.

data.name: Lipid accumulation in hepatocytes
data.def: "Hyperplasia of the biliary tree, as manifested by increased size of bile ducts, dilated lumen, and histologically by an increased number of epithelial cells or hyperplasia." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Complex III, also known as ubiquinol-cytochrome c oxidoreductase or cytochrome bc1 complex, is a multisubunit integral membrane complex of the mitochondrial transport chain, which catalyzes electron transfer from ubiquinol to cytochrome c and couples this process to electrogenic translocation of protons across the mitochondrial inner membrane. Mitochondrial complex III is integrated in the inner mitochondrial membrane.

data.name: Viral hepatitis
data.def: "Inflammation of the liver due to infection with a virus." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Increased hepatocellular lipid droplets
data.def: "An abnormal increase in the amount of intracellular lipid droplets in hepatocytes." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Lipid droplets, rich in triglycerides and cholesterol esters, are cellular ipid storage organelles.

data.name: Subacute progressive viral hepatitis
data.def: "The presence of reduced numbers of  intrahepatic bile duct than normal." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Glycogen acts as secondary long-term energy storage in the liver and other organs. Its intracellular concentration can be increased in some disease states such as obesity.

data.name: Thoracic dysplasia
data.def: "More than one fracture of the ribs." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Thin clavicles
data.def: "Abnormally reduced diameter (cross section) of the clavicles." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Reduced systolic function
data.def: "An abnormal morphology of the ribs consisting of shorted, abnormally curved ribs. On posteroanterior chest radiography, the ribs show a curvature resembling that of a coat hanger (clothes hanger)." [HPO:probinson, pmid:12712270, pmid:21607596]
data.comment: The coat hanger abnormality of the ribs is said to be a useful diagnostic marker of paternal uniparental disomy of chromosome 14.

data.name: Ventricular extrasystoles
data.def: "Premature ventricular contractions (PVC) or ventricular extrasystoles are premature contractions of the heart that arise in response to an impulse in the ventricles rather than the normal impulse from the sinoatrial (SA) node." [HPO:curators]
data.comment: A granuloma is a compact (organized) collection of mature mononuclear phagocytes (macrophages and/or epithelioid cells) which may or may not be accompanied by accessory features such as necrosis or the infiltration of other inflammatory leukocytes (Adams DO. The granulomatous inflammatory response. Am J Pathol 1976:84:163-192).

data.name: Atrioventricular canal defect
data.def: "A defect of the atrioventricular septum of the heart." [HPO:probinson, pmid:12632326]
data.comment: During atrioventricular valvuloseptal morphogenesis, the endocardial cushions expand as they are infiltrated by extracellular matrix secreted from the surrounding myocardium. The cushions then fuse and are remodeled to form the atrioventricular valves and septa. Failure of this process results in AVSD, with the degree of severity dependent on the stage at which the developmental failure occurs. AVSD are a spectrum of cardiac malformations that result in a persistent common atrioventricular canal.

data.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the lungs
data.def: "Acute occurrence of a dissection (tear within the tunica intima and entry of blood into the tunica media) of a coronary artery without an obvious triggering factor." [HPO:probinson, pmid:20448134]
data.comment: Ventricular aneurysms may have rim of calcium in the affected regions of the ventricular wall (which can become fibrotic). Thromboembolism is a potential complication. Ventricular aneurysms can be diagnosed by ventriculography.

data.name: Abnormality of the coronary arteries
data.def: "An abnormality of the coronary arteries." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the atrioventricular valves
data.def: "An abnormality of an atrioventricular valve." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the clavicles
data.def: "Absence or underdevelopment of the clavicles (collar bones)." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia involving bones of the thorax
Cerebral hypomyelination
data.def: "Reduced amount of myelin in the nervous system resulting from defective myelinogenesis in the white matter of the central nervous system." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the  cerebellar vermis
data.def: "Absence or underdevelopment of the vermis of cerebellum." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Cranial nerve paralysis
data.def: "A form of lissencephaly in which the cortex is thickened and has four more or less disorganized layers rather than six normal layers resulting from incomplete neuronal migration during brain development." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Severe muscular hypotonia
data.def: "A severe degree of muscular hypotonia characterized by markedly reduced muscle tone." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Acute encephalopathy
data.def: "Absence of the knee jerk reflex, which can normally be elicited by tapping the patellar tendon with a reflex hammer just below the patella." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This term needs to be made obsolete or revised.

data.name: Cerebellar vermis atrophy
data.def: "Wasting (atrophy) of the vermis of cerebellum." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This sign can be visualized with brain MRI.

data.name: Impaired distal vibration sensation
data.def: "A decrease in the ability to perceive vibration in the distal portions of the limbs." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Intellectual disability, progressive
data.def: "The term progressive intellectual disability should be used if intelligence decreases/deteriorates over time." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormal aggressive, impulsive or violent behavior
data.def: "Curvilinear intracellular accumulation of autofluorescent lipopigment storage material within axons." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Dilation of lateral ventricles
data.def: "Hypoplasia of the cerebellum, pontine nuclei, and inferior olivary nucleus." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormal auditory evoked potentials
data.def: "An abnormality of the auditory evoked potentials, which are used to trace the signal generated by a sound, from the cochlear nerve, through the lateral lemniscus, to the medial geniculate nucleus, and to the cortex." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Auditory brainstem response audiometry typically uses a click stimulus that generates a response from the basilar region of the cochlea.

data.name: Acute necrotizing encephalopathy
data.def: "The presence of calcium deposition in the choroid plexus." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder
data.def: "Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) manifests at age 2-3 years or by first grade at the latest. The main symptoms are distractibility, impulsivity, hyperactivity, and often trouble organizing tasks and projects, difficulty going to sleep, and social problems from being aggressive, loud, or impatient." [HPO:curators]
data.comment: The fourth cranial nerve crosses as it exits the midbrain dorsally and may be injured along its course through the intracranial space, cavernous sinus, superior orbital fissure, or orbit.

data.name: Pain insensitivity
data.def: "Inability to perceive painful stimuli." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Cerebellar dysplasia
data.def: "The presence of developmental dysplasia of the cerebellum." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Saccular aneurysms are often said to have a berry-shaped appearance, whence the name.

data.name: Proximal amyotrophy
data.def: "Amyotrophy (muscular atrophy) affecting the proximal musculature." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Proximal amyotrophy usually has a roughly symmetric distribution.

data.name: Sensorimotor neuropathy
data.def: "Neurodegeneration involving the globus pallidus,a part of the basal ganglia that is involved in the regulation of voluntary movement." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This is a bundled term used to refer to the symptomatology associated with the Guillain-Barre syndrome.

data.name: Motor polyneuropathy
data.def: "Episodic bouts of involuntary movements with dystonic, choreic, ballistic movements, or a combination thereof. There is no loss of consciousness during the attacks." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Periventricular gray matter heterotopia can be seen for example in patients with Smith-Lemli-Opitz-Syndrome.

data.name: Peripheral hypomyelination
data.def: "Reduced amount of myelin in the nervous system resulting from defective myelinogenesis in the peripheral nervous system." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This finding can be demonstrated by nerve biopsy.

data.name: Lower limb amyotrophy
data.def: "Muscular atrophy affecting the lower limb." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Facial paralysis can be caused by compression of the facial nerve.

data.name: Abnormal pyramidal signs
data.def: "Functional neurological abnormalities related to dysfunction of the pyramidal tract." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Presence of these signs can indicate affection of the corticospinal (pyramidal) tracts.

data.name: Cerebral dysmyelination
data.def: "Defective structure and function of myelin sheaths of the white matter of the brain." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Midbrain and mesencephalon are synonymous.

data.name: Spinal muscular atrophy
data.def: "Muscular weakness and atrophy related to loss of the motor neurons of the spinal cord and brainstem." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment:
MERGED COMMENT:
TARGET COMMENT: This feature can be assayed using electromyography (EMG).
--------------------
SOURCE COMMENT: This feature is assayed with sural nerve biopsy and is generally taken to be indicative of neuropathy in other peripheral nerves.

data.name: CNS demyelination
data.def: "A loss of myelin from nerve fibers in the central nervous system." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: CNS demyelination affects the white matter, which consists mostly of axons with their envelope of myelin, along with two types of neuroglia: oligo-dendrocytes and astrocytes.

data.name: Impaired pain sensation
data.def: "Reduced ability to perceive painful stimuli." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis
data.def: "A type of tremors that is triggered by holding an arm in a fixed position." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Focal seizures
data.def: "Seizures of which initial semiology indicates, or is consistent with, initial activation of only part of one cerebral hemisphere." [HPO:jalbers]
data.comment: Partial seizures can be classified as simple (consciousness is maintained) or complex (consciousness is impaired or lost).

data.name: Atrophy/Degeneration affecting the central nervous system
Motor neuron atrophy
data.def: "Wasting involving the motor neuron." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the septum pellucidum
data.def: "An abnormality of the septum pellucidum, which is a thin, triangular, vertical membrane separating the lateral ventricles of the brain." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the choroid plexus
data.def: "An abnormality of the choroid plexus, which is the area in the cerebral ventricles in which cerebrospinal fluid is produced by modified ependymal cells." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The choroid plexus is a structure in the ventricles of the brain where cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) is produced.

data.name: Aplasia cutis congenita of scalp
data.def: "A developmental defect resulting in the congenital absence of skin on the scalp." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Irregular hyperpigmentation
data.def: "Developmental hypoplasia of the apocrine sweat glands in the region of the axilla." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Discoid lupus erythematosus
data.def: "Naevus flammeus localised in the skin of the forehead." [HPO:sdoelken]

data.name: Congenital ichthyosiform erythroderma
data.def: "An ichthyosiform abnormality of the skin with congenital onset." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Generalized hyperpigmentation
data.def: "The presence of multiple leiomyomas of the skin." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Partial albinism
data.def: "Absence of melanin pigment in various areas, which is found at birth and is permanent. The lesions are known as leucoderma and are often found on the face, trunk, or limbs." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormal dermatoglyphics
data.def: "An abnormality of dermatoglyphs (fingerprints), which are present on fingers, palms, toes, and soles." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Epidermolytic hyperkeratosis can refer to the disease caused by mutations in the genes keratin 1 or keratin 10, but is here used to refer to the characteristic skin manifestations as a phenotypic feature.

data.name: Congenital nonbullous ichthyosiform erythroderma
data.def: "The term collodion baby applies to newborns who appear to have an extra layer of skin (known as a collodion membrane) that has a collodion-like quality. It is a descriptive term, not a specific diagnosis or disorder (as such, it is a syndrome). Affected babies are born in a collodion membrane, a shiny waxy outer layer to the skin. This is shed 10-14 days after birth, revealing the main symptom of the disease, extensive scaling of the skin caused by hyperkeratosis. With increasing age, the scaling tends to be concentrated around joints in areas such as the groin, the armpits, the inside of the elbow and the neck. The scales often tile the skin and may resemble fish scales." [HPO:sdoelken]

data.name: Prematurely aged appearance
data.def: "Telangiectases (small dilated blood vessels) with a diffuse localization." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Recurrent staphylococcal infections
data.def: "Hyperkeratosis affecting the palm of the hand and the sole of the foot in areas exposed to friction." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Follicular hyperkeratosis
data.def: "A skin condition characterized by excessive development of keratin in hair follicles, resulting in rough, cone-shaped, elevated papules resulting from closure of hair follicles with a white plug of sebum." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Hypohidrosis or hyperhidrosis
data.def: "Piebaldism is characterized by stable and persistent, well-circumscribed depigmented patches present at birth affecting the skin of the face, trunk, and extremities in a symmetrical distribution." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Plantar hyperkeratosis
data.def: "Hyperkeratosis affecting the sole of the foot." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Dyschromatopsia
data.def: "A form of colorblindness in which only two of the three fundamental colors can be distinguished due to a lack of one of the retinal cone pigments." [DDD:ncarter]
data.comment: Nonarteritic anterior ischemic optic neuropathy is caused by infarction of the laminar or retrolaminar portion of the optic nerve head supplied by the short posterior ciliary arteries. Clinically NAION is characterized by sudden, usually painless, loss of vision in one or both eyes. Examination findings include decreased visual acuity, a visual field defect, decreased colour vision, a relative afferent pupillary defect, and optic disc swelling.

data.name: Congenital stationary night blindness
data.def: "A nonprogressive (i.e., stationary) form of difficulties with night blindness with congenital onset." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Congenital stationary night blindness is prinicipally the result of dysfunction of the rod photoreceptors.

data.name: Punctate cataract
data.def: "A type of cataract with punctate opacities of the lens." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Hypoplasia of the iris
data.def: "Congenital underdevelopment of the iris." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Lacrimal duct stenosis
data.def: "Narrowing of a tear duct (lacrimal duct)." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormal pupillary function
data.def: "A functional abnormality of the pupil." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: It is preferable to describe the functional defect precisely.

data.name: Absent rod-and cone-mediated responses on ERG
data.def: "Absence of the combined rod-and-code response on electroretinogram." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Anterior segment dysgenesis
data.def: "Abnormal development (dysgenesis) of the anterior segment of the eye globe. These structures are mainly of mesenchymal origin." [DDD:ncarter]
data.comment: In anterior segment mesenchymal ocular dysgenesis (ASMOD), multiple tissues are affected, including the iris, cornea, and lens as well as the Schlemm's canal and trabecular meshwork drainage structures located at the anterior segment angle where the iris and cornea meet. These abnormalities may result from a primary defect in the migration and/or differentiation of the mesenchymal cells that contribute to development of the cornea, iris, and drainage structures.

data.name: Iris hypopigmentation
data.def: "An abnormal reduction in the amount of pigmentation of the iris." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: WIth intraocular melanoma, the melanoma originates from melanocytic cells in the uveal layer, comprising the iris, ciliary body, and choroid.

data.name: Bony spicule pigmentary retinopathy
data.def: "A term for the pigmented cells within the retina in retinitis pigmentosa because of their resemblance to the nucleated cells within the lacuna of bone." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Macular dystrophy
data.def: "Macular dystrophy is a nonspecific term for premature retinal cell aging and cell death, generally confied to the macula in which no clear extrinsic cause is evident." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Opacification of the corneal stroma
data.def: "Reduced transparency of the stroma of cornea." [DDD:gblack]

data.name: Impaired smooth pursuit
data.def: "An impairment of the ability to track objects with the ocular smooth pursuit system, a class of rather slow eye movements that minimizes retinal target motion." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Posterior subcapsular cataract
data.def: "A type of cataract affecting the posterior pole of lens immediately adjacent to ('beneath') the Lens capsule." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The central lesion is demonstrable by fluorescein angiography.

data.name: Monochromacy
data.def: "Complete color blindness, a complete inability to distinguish colors. Affected persons cannot perceive colors, but only shades of gray." [DDD:gblack]
data.comment: Rod monochromacy is the condition of having only rods in the retina. A rod monochromat is truly unable to see any color and can see only shades of grey.

data.name: Hypopigmentation of the fundus
data.def: "Decreased amount of pigmentation of the retina." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Saccades are rapid eye movements that align the fovea with the target.

data.name: Corneal opacity
data.def: "A reduction of corneal clarity." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Paralysis of the internal ocular muscles, the iris and ciliary apparatus.

data.name: Retinal dysplasia
data.def: "The presence of developmental dysplasia of the retina." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This feature is a  congenital developmental anomaly of the retina characterized by abnormal growth and differentiation. The retina contains numerous tubular structures and rosettes. Retinal dysplasia (synonym: retinal dysgenesis) is often accompanied by retinal detachment and micropthalmos, but the latter features should be coded separately.

data.name: Peripheral visual field loss
data.def: "Loss of peripheral vision with retention of central vision, resulting in a constricted circular tunnel-like field of vision." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Flashes will elicit an a-wave with an initial negative deflection followed by a b-wave with positive deflection. This feature refers to a reduction in the amplitude primarily of the b-wave.

data.name: Abnormality of macular pigmentation
data.def: "Abnormality of macular or foveal pigmentation." [DDD:ncarter]

data.name: Peripheral opacification of the cornea
data.def: "Reduced transparency of the peripheral region of the cornea." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormal iris pigmentation
data.def: "Abnormal pigmentation of the iris." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the line of Schwalbe
data.def: "An abnormality of the line of Schwalbe." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Schwalbe's line is the anatomical line found on the posterior surface of the cornea, delineating the outer limit of the corneal endothelium layer.

data.name: Abnormality of the palpebral fissures
data.def: "An anomaly of the space between the medial and lateral canthi of the two open eyelids." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: There are six extraocular muscles that control the movements of the eye.

data.name: Abnormality of the retinal pigment epithelium
data.def: "An abnormality of the retinal pigment epithelium. Much of the pigmentary change that occurs in diseases of the retina takes place in the RPE (which is pigmented) rather than in the retina (which is transparent). The main purpose of the RPE is to insulate and support the overlying neural retina." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the iris
data.def: "Absence or underdevelopment of the iris." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia affecting the uvea
data.def: "Absence or underdevelopment of the uvea, the pigmented middle layer of the eye consisting of the iris and ciliary body together with the choroid." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia affecting the anterior segment of the eye
data.def: "Absence or underdevelopment of the anterior segment of the eye." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the lens
data.def: "Absence or underdevelopment of the lens." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Ichthyosis
data.def: "An abnormality of the skin characterized the presence of excessive amounts of dry surface scales on the skin resulting from an abnormality of keratinization." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The ichthyoses are a group of skin diseases characterized by drying and scaling of skin with the accumulation of thick scales and cracks that may be painful or bleed. The abnormality in ichthyosis lies in am imbalance in the normal lifecycle of skin in which growth is matched with dying and shedding of skin cells. In ichthyosis, skin cells reproduce at a rate faster than dead skin cells can be shed or reproduce at a normal rate with a reduction in the rate of shedding. Either abnormality leads to a build up of dry and scaly skin. Note that this term refers to the morphological abnormality of the skin and not the disorder.

data.name: Abnormal blistering of the skin
data.def: "The presence of one or more bullae on the skin, defined as fluid-filled blisters more than 5 mm in diameter with thin walls." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: A bulla is a large vesicle described as a rounded or irregularly shaped blister containing serous or seropurulent fluid, equal to or greater than 10mm.

data.name: Neoplasm of the skin
data.def: "A tumor (abnormal growth of tissue) of the skin." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Sparse hair
data.def: "Reduced density of hairs." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This term applies if the number of hair shafts per unit area is reduced. The term fine hair is used to describe hair with a reduced diameter.

data.name: Deformed tarsal bones
data.def: "Limitation of the ability to bend the toes." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This description is based on the width of the gap between the toes. It is usually used when the width of the toes remains normal rather than to describe a situation where the toes are thin or narrow. This term should not be used for the situation where the finding is limited to a gap between T1,2 (see Sandal gap).

data.name: Mildly elevated creatine phosphokinase
data.def: "An abnormal reduction in amplitude of the signal opf electro-oculography (EOG), which is a technique for measuring the resting potential of the retina." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: 'has part' some \n('increased amount' and ('inheres in' some blood) and (towards some IMR_0002602) and ('has modifier' some 'mild intensity') and ('has modifier' some abnormal))

data.name: Thyroid dysgenesis
data.def: "No secondary sexual characteristics are present at puberty." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This feature is common in Beckwith Wiedemann syndrome.

data.name: Primary gonadal insufficiency
data.def: "The congenital absence of the thyroid gland." [HPO:probinson, pmid:2918525]

data.name: Primary adrenal insufficiency
data.def: "Insufficient production of steroid hormones (primarily cortisol) by the adrenal glands as a result of a primary defect in the glands themselves." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Deficiency of both glucocorticoids and mineralocorticoids.

data.name: Premature ovarian failure
data.def: "Premature ovarian failure is characterized by amenorrhea, hypoestrogenism, and elevated serum gonadotropin levels in women younger than 40 years." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: An absolute increase in the mass of the parenchymal cells of the parathyroid gland leading to an enlargement of the parathyroid glands.

data.name: Adrenal hyperplasia
data.def: "Enlargement of the adrenal gland." [DDD:spark]

data.name: Decreased serum progesterone
data.def: "An elevated concentration of follicle-stimulating hormone in the blood." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: A stretching and widening of the lymphatic vessels of the thyroid gland.

data.name: Pseudohypoaldosteronism
data.def: "A state of renal tubular unresponsiveness or resistance to the action of aldosterone." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Pseudohypoaldosteronism is characterized by hyperkalemia, metabolic acidosis, and normal glomerular filtration rate. This term refers to the phenotypic finding of pseudohypoaldosteronism rather than the disease of idiopathic pseudohypoaldosteronism.

data.name: Abnormal rod and cone electroretinograms
data.def: "An abnormality of the combined rod-and-code response on electroretinogram." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The dark-adapted 3.0 ERG can be used to elicit a combined rod-cone response.

data.name: Abnormality of the calcaneus
data.def: "An abnormality of the calcaneus, also known as the heel bone, one of the or heel bone, one of the components of the tarsus of the foot which make up the heel." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the talus
data.def: "An abnormality of the talus." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Puberty and gonadal disorders
data.def: "Any abnormal process of ossification of the metatarsal bones, which normally are each ossified from two centers: one for the body, and one for the head (metatarsal II,III,IV, and V) and one for the body and one for the base (metatarsal I). The ossification process begins in the center of the body about the ninth week, and extends toward either extremity. The center for the base of the first metatarsal appears about the third year, and the centers for the heads of the other bones between the fifth and eighth years. They join the bodies between the eighteenth and twentieth years." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the nails
data.def: "Aplasia or developmental hypoplasia of the nail." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the toenails
data.def: "An anomaly of the toenail." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Nail dystrophy
data.def: "Onychodystrophy (nail dystrophy) refers to nail changes apart from changes of the color (nail dyschromia) and involves partial or complete disruption of the various keratinous layers of the nail plate." [pmid:19675700]
data.comment: Onychodystrophy is a widely used, yet rarely defined term. Onychodystrophy can be caused by congenital nail diseases, systemic disorders, fungal and nonfungal infections, various noninfectious inflammatory dermatologic diseases of the nail unit and tumors. Onychodystrophy can also occur secondarily to systemic drug use.

data.name: Vertebral hypoplasia
data.def: "Small, underdeveloped vertebral bodies." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Vertebral wedging
data.def: "An abnormal shape of the vertebral bodies whereby the vertebral bodies are thick on one side and taper to a thin edge at the other." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Vertebral clefting
data.def: "Schisis (cleft or cleavage) of vertebral bodies." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Cleft vertebrae result when there are two, instead of one, primary ossification centers in a vertebral body. An unossified cartilaginous brdige may be observed radiographically with the shape of a cleft. If the two ossification centers are ventral/dorsal, a coronal cleft is observed, and if the two ossification centers are left/right, than a sagittal cleft is observed.

data.name: Vertebral arch anomaly
data.def: "A morphological abnormality of the vertebral arch, i.e., of the  posterior part of a vertebra." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: A vertebral arch is the posterior part of a vertebra and forms the canal through which the spinal cord passes. A vetebral arch consists of (i) a pair of vertebral pedicles (FMA:11950), which are short thick processes that extend from the vertebral body to connect the body to the vertebral arch; (ii) a pari of vertebral laminae (broad plates that extending dorsally and medially from the pedicles fusing with one another to complete the roof of the vertebral arch); (iii) the spinous process (a process that is directed backward and downward from the junction of the laminae and to which muscles and ligaments attach); (iv) two superior articular processes and two inferior articular processes that articulate between two adjacent vertebrae); and (v) two transverse processes that extend at either side from the point where the lamina joins the pedicle, between the superior and inferior articular processes and allow the attachment of muscles and ligaments.

data.name: C1-C2 vertebral abnormality
data.def: "Any abnormality of the atlas and the axis." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The atlas is the first cervical vertebral body and the axis is the second vertebral body.

data.name: Narrow vertebral interpedicular distance
data.def: "A reduction of the distance between vertebral pedicles, which are the two short, thick processes, which project backward, one on either side, from the upper part of the vertebral body, at the junction of its posterior and lateral surfaces." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the vertebrae
data.def: "A bilateral type of conductive hearing impairment." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the sacrum
data.def: "Aplasia or developmental hypoplasia of the sacral bone." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Congenital sensorineural hearing impairment
data.def: "A type of hearing impairment caused by an abnormal functionality of the cochlear nerve with congenital onset." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: They are usually linear to a narrow oval in shape and may be single or multiple.

data.name: Abnormally folded helix
data.def: "A type of hearing impairment affecting primarily the low frequencies of sound (125 Hz to 1000 Hz)." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: This term is used for Auriculocondylar syndrome (MIM:602483). Not clear if there is a clean delineation against cleft helix.

data.name: Microtia
data.def: "Underdevelopment of the external ear." [HPO:probinson, pmid:19152421, pmid:3270622]
data.comment: The definitions of microtia follow a widely used, surgically based, classification of ear anomalies outlined by Weerda 1988. As microtia indicates at least both decreased length and width, and in more severe forms it includes abnormal shape of structures, all forms are acknowledged to be bundled terms, but are retained here because they are well established.

data.name: Cochlear malformation
data.def: "The presence of a malformed cochlea." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: A cochlear malformation may include a membranous abnormality, a bony abnormality, or a combination of the two.

data.name: Hypoplastic superior helix
data.def: "Complete lack of functioning of the vestibular apparatus." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: External ear malformation
data.def: "A malformation of the auricle of the ear." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Hypoplastic helices
data.def: "Underdevelopment of the helix, i.e., of the outer rim of the pinna." [HPO:curators]
data.comment: A neurosensory hearing loss with a deficit of 21-40 dB.

data.name: Morphological abnormality of the middle ear
data.def: "An abnormality of the morphology or structure of the middle ear." [DDD:mbitner-glidicz]
data.comment: Conductive hearing impairment with 21-40 dB deficit.

data.name: Bilateral sensorineural hearing impairment
data.def: "A bilateral form of sensorineural hearing impairment." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormal spermatogenesis
data.def: "Incomplete maturation or aberrant formation of the male gametes." [HPO:probinson, MP:0001156]
data.comment: Renotubular dysgenesis is generally accompanied by early onset and persistent oligohydramnios that leads to the Potter sequence.

data.name: Calcium oxalate nephrolithiasis
data.def: "The presence of calcium- and oxalate-containing calculi (stones) in the kidneys." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Renal hypoplasia/aplasia
data.def: "Absence or underdevelopment of the kidney." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The cause of congenital megaloureter is thought to be aperistalsis of the distal ureter, leading to dilatation. The defect in peristalsis may be due to faulty development of muscle layers of ureter, that is, there is a functional, not a mechanical cause of obstruction.

data.name: Aplasia/hypoplasia of the uterus
data.def: "Absence or developmental hypoplasia of the uterus." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the ear
data.def: "The presence of aplasia or developmental hypoplasia of the ear." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Embryologically, the trachea and esophagus share a common lumen until they are separated by the development of the tracheoesophageal septum. Failure of this fusion and incomplete development of the tracheoesophageal septum may lead to congenital abnormalities such as isolatedlaryngeal cleft, tracheoesophageal fistula, and esophageal atresia, depending on the severity of the abnormality. Patients with laryngeal cleft may present with feeding difficulty, chronic cough, stridor, pneumonia or respiratory distress, depending on the size of the cleft.

data.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the external ear
data.def: "The presence of aplasia or developmental hypoplasia of all or part of the external ear." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the prostate
data.def: "An abnormality of the prostate." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the vocal cords
data.def: "An abnormality of the vocal cord." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The vocal cords, also known as the vocal folds, represent a subdivision of the larynx, and consist of twin infoldings of mucous membrane stretched horizontally across the larynx.

data.name: Hypoplastic pelvis
data.def: "Underdevelopment of the bony pelvis." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Additionally, the ossification center of the capital femoral epiphysis appears at the end of the first year after birth. This is not what this term refers to.

data.name: Severe postnatal growth retardation
data.def: "Severely slow or limited growth after birth, being four standard deviations or more below age- and sex-related norms." [DDD:hfirth]

data.name: Feeding difficulties in infancy
data.def: "Impaired feeding performance of an infant as manifested by difficulties such as weak and ineffective sucking, brief bursts of sucking, and falling asleep during sucking. There may be difficulties with chewing or maintaining attention." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Disproportionate short-limb short stature
data.def: "A type of disproportionate short stature characterized by a short limbs but an average-sized trunk." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: A type of dwarfism (marked short stature with adult height below 147 cm) in which the limbs are disproportionatley affected. Note that brachymelia is a general term refering to shortening of the limbs. Micromelia refers to the shortening of entire limbs (in contrast to rhizomelia, mesomelia, and acromelia, which refer to shortening of the proximal, middle, or distal portions of the limbs).

data.name: Adipose tissue loss
data.def: "A loss of adipose tissue." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Postnatal growth retardation
data.def: "Slow or limited growth after birth." [DDD:hfirth]

data.name: Neonatal short-limb short stature
data.def: "A type of short-limbed dwarfism that is manifest beginning in the neonatal period." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Generalized neonatal hypotonia
data.def: "Muscular hypotonia (abnormally low muscle tone) manifesting in the neonatal period and affecting the entire musculature." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Muscular hypotonia of the trunk
data.def: "Muscular hypotonia (abnormally low muscle tone) affecting the musculature of the trunk." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Distal lower limb amyotrophy
data.def: "Muscular atrophy of distal leg muscles." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Distal lower limb muscle atrophy is commonly due to peripheral neuropathy.

data.name: Infantile muscular hypotonia
data.def: "Muscular hypotonia (abnormally low muscle tone) manifesting in infancy." [HPO:curators]
data.comment: This term should not be used for new annotations. Instead, state the type of onset of hypotonia more exactly.

data.name: Decreased activity of mitochondrial respiratory chain
data.def: "Decreased activity of the mitochondrial respiratory chain." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Hypoplasia of the musculature
data.def: "Underdevelopment of the musculature." [HPO:sdoelken]

data.name: Increased connective tissue
data.def: "The presence of an abnormally increased amount of connective tissue." [HPO:curators]
data.comment: This may be associated with protuberance of the abdomen.

data.name: Difficulty running
data.def: "Reduced ability to run." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Increased muscle lipid content
data.def: "An abnormal accumulation of lipids in skeletal muscle." [HPO:probinson, pmid:20691590]
data.comment: Increased neutral lipid content may be observed on muscle biopsies specimen with the specific staining of Sudan black or oil red O techniques by optic microscopy.

data.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia involving the pelvis
data.def: "A type of malocclusion in which there is a gap between the anterior teeth (incisors)." [HPO:ibailleulforestier]
data.comment: Submucous cleft lip may lead to increased nasal resonance.

data.name: Aplasia/hypoplasia involving the skeleton
data.def: "Absence (due to failure to form) or underdevelopment of one or more components of the skeleton." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormal axial skeleton morphology
data.def: "An abnormality of the axial skeleton, which comprises the skull, the vertebral column, the ribs and the sternum." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Aplasia/hypoplasia affecting bones of the axial skeleton
data.def: "Absence (due to failure to form) or underdevelopment of bones of the axial skeleton." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of adipose tissue
data.def: "An abnormality of adipose tissue20110), which is loose connective tissue composed of adipocytes." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Lipodystrophy
data.def: "Degenerative changes of the fat tissue." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Abnormality of the musculature of the limbs
data.def: "An increase in adipose tissue mass by hyperplastic growth (increase in the number of adipocytes) or by hypertrophic growth (increase in the size of adipocytes occurring primarily by lipid accumulation within the cell)." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Duplication involving bones of the feet
Depletion of mitochondrial DNA in muscle tissue
Duplication of bones involving the upper extremities
Supernumerary bones of the axial skeleton
Deviation of the hand or of fingers of the hand
data.def: "Displacement of the hand or of fingers of the hand from their normal position." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Radial deviation of the hand or of fingers of the hand
Radial deviation of the hand
data.def: "An abnormal position of the hand in which the wrist is bent toward the radius (i.e., toward the thumb)." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the epididymis
data.def: "An abnormality of the epididymis." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The epididymis is the structure that connects efferent ductules to vas deferens.

data.name: Abnormality of the subungual region
data.def: "A lesion located beneath a fingernail or toenail." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Abnormality of the antihelix
data.def: "An abnormality of the antihelix." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: An abnormal form of the antihelix, which is the curved prominence of cartilage, parallel with and in front of the helix, and which divides into the crura antihelicis, between which is a triangular depression, the fossa triangularis.

data.name: Large earlobe
data.def: "Increased volume of the earlobe, that is, abnormally prominent ear lobules." [HPO:probinson, pmid:19152421]
data.comment: All gradations in size of the earlobe may be seen from absent to clearly enlarged compared to average. This finding is highly variable. Lobe size increases throughout adulthood.

data.name: Popliteal pterygium
data.def: "A pterygium (or pterygia) occuring in the popliteal region (the back of the knee)." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: A minimally expressed form, especially when located fully laterally, may be more difficult to ascertain and would be a subjective feature. A band may break and leave no evidence of its presence. Note that the term is distinct from cryptophthalmos.

data.name: Low hanging columella
data.def: "Columella extending inferior to the level of the nasal base, when viewed from the side." [pmid:19152422]

data.name: Amniotic constriction ring
data.def: "Annular constrictions around the digits, limbs, or trunk, occurring congenitally (sometimes causing intrauterine autoamputation) and also associated with a wide variety of disorders. Constrictive amniotic bands are the result of primary amniotic rupture, which can lead to entanglement of fetal tissue (especially limbs) in fibrous amniotic strands." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Pseudoainhum is a rare condition of unknown etiology that produces digital constricting rings, most commonly on the small fingers.

data.name: Supernumerary spleens
data.def: "The presence of two or more accessory spleens." [HPO:curators]
data.comment: Branchial cyst have to be distinguished from the preauricular cysts and sinuses, which are ectodermal remnants from an aberrant development of the auditory tubercles, tend to be bilateral, and are localized anterior to the tragus of the ear.

data.name: Reduced number of teeth
data.def: "The presence of a reduced number of teeth as in Hypodontia or as in Anodontia." [HPO:sdoelken]
data.comment: Hypodontia describes a situation when there are fewer than the normal number of teeth, whereby 6 teeth or fewer teeth are missing (oligodontia refers to the condition of missing more than 6 teeth and the congenital absence of all teeth is called anodontia).

data.name: Peripheral neuropathy
data.def: "Peripheral neuropathy is a general term for any disorder of the peripheral nervous system. The main clinical features used to classify peripheral neuropathy are distribution, type (mainly demyelinating versus mainly axonal), duration, and course." [HPO:sdoelken]

data.name: Abnormality of hair pigmentation
data.def: "An abnormality of hair pigmentation (color)." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Abnormality of secondary sexual hair
data.def: "Abnormality of the growth of secondary sexual hair, which normally ensues during puberty. In males, secondary sexual hair usually comprises body hair, including underarm, abdominal, chest, and pubic hair. In females, secondary sexual hair usually comprises a lesser degree of body hair, most prominently underarm and pubic hair." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Underdeveloped supraorbital ridges
data.def: "Flatness of the supraorbital portion of the frontal bones." [HPO:curators, pmid:19125436]

data.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the earlobes
data.def: "Absence or underdevelopment of the ear lobes." [HPO:curators]
data.comment: This may take the form of a sharp cleft or a less well-demarcated area. This should be distinguished from a Question-mark ear. If the defect or notch occurs at the junction of the superior and descending portions of the helix, it should be coded as Darwin notch of the helix.

data.name: Anterior creases of earlobe
data.def: "Sharply demarcated, typically linear and approximately horizontal, indentations in the outer surface of the ear lobe." [pmid:19152421]
data.comment: Shallow grooves or indentations are quite common, especially in large lobes. Ear lobe creases may arise postnatally. Posterior helical pits can be a related finding but should be assessed and coded separately.

data.name: Duane anomaly
data.def: "Duane anomaly is a congenital eye movement impairment with limitation of the ability to adduct or abduct the eye. When affected eyes are adducted (moved inwards towards the nose), the eyeball retracts and the palpebral fissure narrows." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: The tunica vasculosa lentis anterior (pupillary membrane) normally undergoes atrophy in the third trimester of pregnancy. If the membrane does not completely atrophy, then remnants of membranous structures can be observed to emrge from the iris.

data.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia involving the nose
data.def: "Underdevelopment or absence of the nose or parts thereof." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Abnormality of the columella
data.def: "An abnormality of the columella." [HPO:curators]
data.comment: The columella is the fleshy external end of the nasal septum.

data.name: Abnormality of the 1st metacarpal
data.def: "A structural anomaly of the first metacarpal." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: In contrast to the metacarpals 2-5, the first metacarpal is embryologically of phalangeal origin and as such equivalent to the proximal phalanges of the digits 2-5, whereas the proximal phalanx of the thumb is equivalent to the middle phalanges of the other digits.

data.name: Abnormality of the 4th metacarpal
data.def: "Any abnormality of the fourth metacarpal bone." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Abnormality of the 5th metacarpal
data.def: "Any abnormality of the fifth metacarpal bone." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Abnormality of the first metatarsal bone
data.def: "An anomaly of the first metatarsal bone." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: In contrast to the metatarsals 2-5, the first metatarsal is embryologically of phalangeal origin and as such equivalent to the proximal phalanges of the digits 2-5, whereas the proximal phalanx of the big toe is equivalent to the middle phalanges of the other digits. This term applies to abnormalities of the first metatarsal.

data.name: Stomatitis
data.def: "Stomatitis is an inflammation of the mucous membranes of any of the structures in the mouth." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Abnormality of the salivary glands
data.def: "Any abnormality of the salivary glands, the exocrine glands that produce saliva." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: These bands must be distinguished from synechiaee between the tongue and palate (glossopalatal ankylosis) and from synechiae arising from the floor of the mouth (as in the subglossopalatal membrane), oropharyngeal isthmus (as in persistent buccopharyngeal membrane) or from the lower lip. If there is a complete soft tissue contiguity between the upper and lower alveolar ridges, the term, Fibrous syngnathia should be used instead.

data.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the uvula
data.def: "Underdevelopment or absence of the uvula." [HPO:curators]
data.comment: Sometimes accompanies a Submucous cleft palate, but this should be coded separately.

data.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the tongue
data.def: "Absence or underdevelopment of the tongue." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Ankyloglossia
data.def: "Short or anteriorly attached lingual frenulum, associated with limited mobility of the tongue." [pmid:19125428]
data.comment: The anterior third of the tongue is usually free or is partially attached to the floor of the mouth by the lingual frenulum. There is a spectrum ranging from fusion of the tongue to the floor of the mouth (ankyloglossia inferiorum) to a lingual frenulum that is short or anchored toward the tip of the tongue (sometimes called tongue tie). Ankyloglossia may be associated with a mild indentation of the tip of the tongue, which should not be coded as a Bifid tongue.

data.name: Bifid tongue
data.def: "Tongue with a median apical indentation or fork." [pmid:19125428]
data.comment: Bifid tongue can be associated with ankyloglossia, but this should be assessed and coded separately. Small indentations of the tip of the tongue should not be coded as a bifid tongue.

data.name: Abnormality of dentin
data.def: "Any abnormality of dentin." [HPO:probinson]
data.comment: Dentin is a calcified tissue of teeth that is covered by enamel on the crown and cementum on the root and surrounds the entire pulp.

data.name: Short thorax
data.def: "Reduced inferior to superior extent of the thorax." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Stridor
data.def: "Stridor is a high pitched sound resulting from turbulent air flow in the upper airway." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the breasts
data.def: "Absence or underdevelopment of the breasts." [HPO:curators]
data.comment: Various degrees of bifid sternum may occur, varying from an enlarged suprasternal notch to complete separation of the two halves of the sternum. Ectopia cordis may or may not accompany this defect in its more severe form.

data.name: Abnormality of the ventricular septum
data.def: "An abnormality of the interventricular septum." [HPO:probinson]

data.name: Pulmonary insufficiency
data.def: "The retrograde (backwards) flow of blood through the pulmonary valve into the right ventricle during diastole." [HPO:curators]

data.name: Aplasia/Hypoplasia of the spleen
